<FIRST>u a AM-WanderingPlane 3rdLd-Writethru a0779 07-13 0970</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wandering Plane, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0779,0992</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stricken Pilot Rescued After Plane on Autopilot Crashes into Atlantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf with 6 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from tape of
conversation between Root and controllers; picks up 9th graf, ``There was
...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LasePhotos WX26, MH1,2,4, LaserGraphic NY29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane with a stricken pilot flew hundreds of
miles down the Atlantic Coast on autopilot shadowed by military jets
Thursday, finally running out of gas and spiraling into the ocean.
The pilot then emerged from the wreckage and swam toward his
startled rescuers, authorities said.
   Thomas Root, a 36-year-old lawyer from Alexandria, Va., was
pulled from Bahamian waters by Air Force parachutists four hours
after he had first radioed he was in trouble. He was first taken to
Nassau and a Coast Guard helicopter then flew him to Florida.
   ``For him to survive a crash like that, it just sent us all into
shock,'' said Petty Officer Veronica Cady, a Coast Guard
spokeswoman. ``We didn't expect this story to have a happy ending.''
   Coast Guard Capt. Dr. James Rahman said Root may have passed out
from carbon monoxide poisoning in the cockpit of his single-engine
Cessna and that water splashing in his face apparently roused him.
   Root was taken to Memorial Hospital in Hollywood, where he
underwent three-hours of exploratory surgery for possible internal
injuries.
   After the operation, his condition was upgraded from critical to
stable, said hospital spokeswoman Cynthia Wine. Root's family
requested no information be released on his injuries, she said.
   Root's wife, Kathy, 35, told reporters from the porch of the
family home that her husband had been awake and talking to doctors.
She said she told hospital officials to send her husband the
following message: ``Root, you really did it this time.''
   The drama began about 8:30 a.m. when Root, who had taken off from
Washington National Airport about 6:30 a.m. for Rocky Mount, N.C.,
radioed air traffic controllers in Virginia.
   ``Yessir, we're having a little problem up here,'' Root told
controllers, according to a tape of the conversation played by
Washington television station WRC-TV.
   ``Seem to have a little trouble breathing,'' said Root, who also
reported chest pain. ``How far am I to Rocky Mount now?''
   ``You're about 17 minutes from Rocky Mount,'' replied an
unidentified controller.
   ``Uh,'' said the pilot.
   ``Niner niner one three Yankee, do you hear?'' said the
controller, calling the plane's number.
   There was no further radio contact, and military pilots who
tailed the plane reported he was slumped behind the controls as his
plane flew south off the coast, occasionally getting within 100
miles of the shore.
   Military pilots and rescuers trained to parachute into the ocean
to save ditched pilots could only watch helplessly as their aircraft
tracked the plane until it ran out of gas.
   After more than 3{ hours of radio silence, the plane spiraled
into the water and Root was rescued, 800 miles from his original
destination in North Carolina and 250 miles southeast of Miami.
   ``The words you keep hearing are, `You're kidding,''' said Ms.
Cady.
   The Coast Guard said the plane went down about 15 miles east of
the island of Eleuthera. ``It spiraled into the water, so it didn't
make the best of all possible landings,'' said Chief Petty Officer
Lou Parris.
   Coast Guard Lt. Commander Gary Poll, who was at the scene in a
jet when Root crashed, said the plane was at about 7,000 feet when
it began spiraling in like a corkscrew and spinning down at about
2,000 feet per minute.
   Poll said the nose and left wing hit the water at the same time
and the plane swiveled on its belly on a 360-degree spin. He said it
stayed afloat for several minutes and started to sink.
   Air Force Sgt. Paul Hayden, one of four Air Reserve Technicians
who parachuted into the water, said Root was first spotted swimming
away from the wreckage dressed only in pants and socks.
   Root was pulled onto a raft and given first aid, said Hayden,
based at the 301st Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron in
Homestead, about 20 miles south of Miami.
   ``He told us his abdomen is hurting a lot and we could see he was
bleeding,'' said Hayden. ``It was incredible. He had a sense of
humor about it.''
   Rahman, the doctor who treated Root in Nassau, said Root was
alert and could speak well but seemed to be in shock and had
abdominal injuries and fractured ribs. Rahman said there was no
indication of a heart attack and Root had no history of heart
trouble.
   ``It's definitely a miracle he's alive. He's a little confused by
it all,'' the doctor said.
   After its distress call, the plane was intercepted by two Marine
Corps F-A-18 jet fighters when it entered Norfolk Naval Station
airspace at 8:45 a.m., said Lt. Cmdr. Mike John, a Navy spokesman.
The pilots of the intercepting planes tried unsuccessfully to
contact the pilot by radio, he said.
   The Cessna 210 Centurion can seat four to six people, counting
the pilot, and cruises at about 190 mph. Bill Pierman, shift
supervisor in the air traffic control tower at Washington National,
told Raleigh radio station WPTF that the autopilot was set on a
heading that would have sent the plane toward Bahamas.
   ``Put an airplane on automatic pilot and it's going to continue
just exactly on the course that the automatic pilot is set for,'' he
said.
   At time of crash, Root was followed by a C-130 cargo plane from
Homestead Air Force Base near Miami and an HH3 helicopter from
Patrick Air Force Base, also on Florida's East Coast, said Lt. Col.
Margaret Stanek of Homestead. A flight surgeon was part of the
rescue teams, she said.
</TEXT>
