<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--TurbanedTrooper     07-13 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Turbaned Trooper,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh's Turban Causes Headache for Norwegian Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norwegian defense officials have added
turbans to the military dress code after a year-long battle by a
Sikh immigrant who demanded the right to keep his traditional dress
during military service.
   Harvinder Singh, 25, became the first Norwegian soldier ever
allowed to wear a turban on duty, the newspaper Verdens Gang
reported Wednesday.
   Singh, who came from India in 1978, was called up in July for a
year of compulsory military training. He wanted to serve but refused
to remove his turban, the newspaper said.
   Singh was sent home while military officials mulled over the
problem.
   The supreme command decided that Norway must adapt to recruits
from various cultures and ordered that standard issue turbans be
prepared to fit the military dress code, defense spokesman Erik
Sinstad told the newspaper.
</TEXT>
