<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--BirdBirth     07-13 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Bird Birth,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Artificially Propagates Crested Ibis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Beijing zoo has become the world's first to
artificially breed a crested ibis, a long-billed wading bird that is
near extinction, the China Daily said today.
   The 2-ounce bird was born Monday, ending a three-year effort by
the zoo to find a way to artificially propagate the species, the
official daily said.
   It said the 4-year-old mother delivered two eggs in mid-June, but
pecked one of the babies to death. The other was removed to a
breeding box for special care.
   The crested ibis was once found in the Soviet Union, the Korean
peninsula, Japan and Taiwan as well as China, but its population has
declined dramatically because of destruction to its environment, the
daily said.
   It said only about 48 of the species survive, two in Japan and
the rest in Yangxian County of central China's Shaanxi province.
</TEXT>
