<FIRST>r a PM-BlindCowboy     07-13 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blind Cowboy,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blind Cowboy Depends on Horses for Independence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARTESIA, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A horse that knows when it's safe to cross
intersections allows a blind former cowboy to keep his independence,
but the city says the man must clean up after the animal or lose the
privilege.
   George Bradford, 69, who retains about 1 percent of his sight in
one eye, has a year to persuade the City Council to let him keep two
horses, Blue Rocky and Buck, in his back yard.
   When Bradford rides Blue Rocky through town, the horse stops at
intersections and doesn't move until traffic is flowing in the
direction the horse is supposed to go.
   In 1981, the City Council granted Bradford a lifetime zoning
variance allowing him to keep the horses in town.
   But inspectors reported in 1987 that Bradford wasn't cleaning up
after the horses and was bothering neighbors with the smell. The
variance was revoked and a judge fined Bradford $100. The fine was
thrown out on appeal.
   Last month, a judge gave Bradford a year to change the council's
mind or move the horses.
   ``Now, hopefully, what we're doing is right,'' said Mayor Ernest
Thompson. ``As far as being unfair, he's the one who's being unfair
to his neighbors.''
   Bradford said the neighbor behind the complaints is Eddie
Wallace, who wanted to sell his house next door but was afraid
Bradford's horses would lower property values.
   Wallace is not on speaking terms with Bradford nor with reporters.
   ``I don't want to say nothing about that crap. No, bye,'' he
said, hanging up.
   Bradford, who likes to smoke hand-rolled cigarettes and reminisce
about the days when he worked as a cowboy in Texas and New Mexico,
had to stop working in 1964 because of retinitis pigmentosa, a
hereditary degenerative eye disease.
   But Bradford likes to ride Blue Rocky the two miles to downtown
Artesia, across six intersections with stoplights.
   He could see better about 10 years ago, when he got Blue Rocky
and started leading the horse on his walks into town. When Bradford
heard traffic going in the direction he was walking, that meant the
light had turned green and he would cross the intersection.
   Now the horse decides when it's time to cross.
   ``He automatically stops anyhow at any intersection,'' Bradford
said. ``I guarantee you he won't go unless the traffic is going my
way. Whether he can read the light is the $64 question.''
   Other times, Bradford rides his horse into the hills west of his
house.
   ``You know, I can get kind of down and out because I can't work,
and get on that old horse and ride five or six miles and, hey, I got
a different outlook on life all of a sudden,'' Bradford said. ``I'm
completely independent.''
   He shudders at the thought of losing his horses.
   ``Oh, I suppose somebody could take me places, but you have to go
back when they want to go back _ you know, you're not independent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Olivier'sHeirs Bjt   07-13 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Olivier's Heirs, Bjt,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Olivier's Death: The End of An Era?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurence Olivier is gone. Will the theater world
ever see his like again?
   Said critic Bernard Levin, who wrote in The Times after Olivier
died Tuesday: ``No one will replace the splendor that he gave his
native land with his genius.''
   Other critics say that while another Olivier may be in the wings,
they feel today's entertainment industry makes it doubtful.
   Primarily a man of the stage, Olivier became a superstar in all
media. The sheer quantity of his work is among the most noteworthy
aspects of a career that ended with his death at age 82, at his
country home south of London.
   But Olivier was also the consummate actor-manager _ a passionate
theater advocate as important behind the scenes as a director and
organizer as he was on stage as a performer.
   Few theater observers would dispute that first-rate British
actors continue to abound. Derek Jacobi, Vanessa Redgrave, Anthony
Hopkins, Glenda Jackson, Alan Bates, Maggie Smith and Ian McKellen
are just some of the generation after Olivier who have been widely
and often acclaimed.
   Then there's a still younger generation less known abroad but
already staring greatness in the eye: Kenneth Branagh, Antony Sher,
Juliet Stevenson, Fiona Shaw.
   And although Olivier's death is being called the end of an era,
he is survived by such stalwart knights and dames of stage as John
Gielgud, John Mills, Rex Harrison, Alec Guinness, Wendy Hiller and
Peggy Ashcroft.
   But it's Olivier's level of commitment to the art form he
cherished that may be in shorter supply.
   ``Will anyone ever again go on for so long, play so many great
parts, run so many companies?'' asked Michael Coveney in The
Financial Times. ``Will they want to enough? We must doubt it until
they do.''
   Milton Shulman in The Evening Standard also feared such
dedication was dying. ``The likes of Olivier, nurtured on
greasepaint, the footlights, and the effrontery of daring an
audience to like you, are fast becoming an endangered species.''
   The stage instead, he wrote, is ``fast becoming the casting
kindergarten for film and TV.''
   The trend is increasing in Britain as talented young theater
actors opt for the greater financial rewards of film and TV.
   Natasha Richardson, Hugh Grant, James Wilby, and Amanda Donohoe
are just some of the classically schooled young English talents who
work mostly on screen.
   Among the older generation, none has matched the initiative of
Olivier, who in 1963 realized an old dream of establishing a
National Theater of Great Britain.
   ``The quality of work we do here is mostly due to him,'' veteran
actor Michael Bryant told Tuesday night's audience at the National's
production of ``The Voysey Inheritance.''
   Some feel Olivier's death ends a kind of theatrical majesty that
transcends issues of talent.
   In an editorial entitled ``Stage Colossus,'' The Daily Telegraph
wrote: ``He was the undisputed leader of his profession, its
spokesman, and the brightest jewel in its crown. We shall not look
upon his like again.''
   Levin wrote: ``What we have lost with Laurence Olivier is glory.
... You could practically see it growing around him like a nimbus.''
   Denis Quilley, Olivier's co-star in a celebrated London
production of Eugene O'Neill's ``Long Day's Journey Into Night,''
said in an interview, ``There are people today (like Olivier) but
not on the same scale.''
   Would-be inheritors most frequently mentioned are men like
Michael Pennington and the protean Branagh, Guy Pringle in the TV
series ``Fortunes of War,'' who combine thespian dynamism with a
team spirit.
   Both have started theater companies _ Pennington, the English
Shakespeare Company, which finished a world tour in Britain this
spring, and Branagh, the Renaissance Theater Company, which had a
sell-out Shakespeare season on the West End last fall.
   Branagh, 28, tempted further comparisons to Olivier by starring
on stage and screen as Shakespeare's Henry V, one of Olivier's most
celebrated achievements. Branagh's film is due out in the fall.
   Antony Sher's 1984 Richard III also was likened to Olivier's. But
South African-born Sher, 40, has forsaken the spotlight to focus on
writing.
   Diana Rigg, who appeared with Olivier at Stratford-upon-Avon and
in his 1983 TV ``King Lear,'' says the case isn't closed on
greatness.
   ``It's impossible to say you'll never see the likes of him
again,'' she said in an interview. ``The profession is full of
incredibly talented people, some in the cradle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
