<FIRST>r a PM-People-King'sTreatment     07-13 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-King's Treatment,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi King Due at Cleveland Clinic for Exam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia's King Fahd, accompanied by an
entourage of up to 200, including his wives, plans to enter the
Cleveland Clinic for a physical examination and possible knee
surgery, a hospital spokesman said.
   Twenty rooms are being refurbished for security reasons and to
suit the 67-year-old monarch's tastes, said Gary Weiland, a clinic
spokesman.
   The exam will coincide with Fahd's official state visit to the
United States, Weiland said Wednesday night.
   Fahd is to meet with President Bush on July 27.
   A spokesman at the Saudi Arabian Embassy in Washington would
neither confirm nor deny Fahd's visit to Cleveland. Such a trip
would be announced once he arrived in the United States, the
spokesman said.
   Weiland said he did not know when the king would arrive.
   An advance team scouted hospitals in four U.S. cities and chose
the clinic because of its expertise in orthopedic surgery, and
because the king's half-brother, Khaled, had heart surgery there
twice, Weiland said. Khaled, who preceded Fahd as Saudi Arabia's
king, died in 1982.
   Extensive remodeling of the Clinic Center Hotel, which had been
scheduled this year, has been speeded up in preparation for the
visit, Weiland said. Some of the entourage will stay at other hotels.
</TEXT>
