<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Princess of Wales reportedly has decided
against plastic surgery on her nose because of fears the results
could be worse.
   The Ladies' Home Journal reports in its August issue that Diana's
doctor advised her against surgery on her ``conk'' _ British slang
for the proboscis.
   ``I couldn't go around with my nose in bandages for days,'' Diana
reportedly said during one of the women-only evenings the Journal
said she holds at Kensington Palace for her friends.
   ``Also, things go wrong, and it would be terrible if it looked
worse afterward,'' Diana said of her nose, which she described as
``too big.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moving on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CASTRO VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Canseco, the Oakland Athletics
slugger who has more speeding citations than major league hits this
season, had another brush with the law.
   Canseco got his latest ticket Tuesday while driving his new white
Porsche home to watch the All-Star game. He was ticketed for driving
51 mph in a 35 mph zone, said California Highway Patrol spokesman
Nick Verhoek.
   The officer who stopped him believed he was going over 65 mph on
winding Crow Canyon Road but couldn't get a radar reading, Verhoek
said. Canseco was ticketed on the same road a few months ago.
   ``I got stopped for going 13 miles over the speed limit. Can you
believe that?'' Canseco asked at a workout Wednesday at the Oakland
Coliseum.
   When asked if he got a ticket, Canseco said, ``Me? Not get a
ticket?''
   Canseco was voted the American League's Most Valuable Player last
year, but he hasn't played in major league games this year because
of a wrist injury.
   In February, Canseco was ticketed in Florida for driving 125 mph
in his $75,000 red Jaguar. Canseco said later he was doing only 120
mph. In March, he was ticketed again in Arizona.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A libel suit against pop rocker Daryl Hall has been
dismissed by a judge who ruled the plaintiff was ``forum shopping''
when he filed the lawsuit in Florida.
   U.S. District Judge James Lawrence King noted neither Hall nor
the plaintiff, fellow entertainment figure John Madera, had any
Florida connections.
   Madera claimed he was libeled in an interview given by Hall to
Music Connection magazine for its November-December 1986 issue.
   Hall described the deterioration of his relationship with Madera
in the interview. He was quoted as saying, ``He had his day in the
sun. But he was pretty much a small-time kind of guy.''
   Madera said Hall's statements damaged his reputation in the
entertainment industry.
   The judge noted that Hall, whose hits include ``Private Eyes''
and ``Rich Girl,'' lives in New York and the magazine was based in
California.
   Madera tried to sue before in New York and California, but the
cases exceeded the statute of limitations in those states, King said.
   He sued in Miami in May 1988, about 18 months after the alleged
offense. Florida has a two-year statute of limitations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., suffered a cut on
his forehead when his car struck a security barrier in the Capitol
parking lot.
   Conyers, chairman of the House Government Operations Committee,
was treated at Washington Hospital Center and released, a hospital
spokesman said.
   Conyers and the driver, Cedric Hendricks were thrown into the
windshield, which shattered, said Capitol police spokesman Dan
Nichols. At the time, the congressman was headed to the House floor
for a vote.
   Hendricks was admitted to the hospital, which did not have a
report on his condition.
   Nichols said Wednesday's accident was under investigation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Zsa Zsa Gabor admits she
slapped a police officer, but says he deserved it.
   ``The policeman is an empty-headed, gorgeous man,'' she said.
Then, in a stream of denunciations, compared him to Nazi soldiers in
her native Hungary.
   ``But the Nazis were smarter; they had the sense to mistreat
women in private,'' said Miss Gabor.
   Miss Gabor said she hit Officer Paul Kramer in self-defense
because he threatened to break her arm.
   She pleaded innocent Wednesday to several misdemeanor charges.
Municipal Judge Charles G. Rubin granted Miss Gabor's request for an
Aug. 2 pretrial hearing, and set her jury trial for Sept. 11.
   When arriving for Wednesday's arraignment, she was met at the
courthouse by a crowd of reporters and several relatives, who held
signs that said ``Free Zsa Zsa.''
   Miss Gabor was arrested June 14 after Kramer pulled over her
Rolls-Royce for an expired registration. She drove off as Kramer was
checking for other infractions, then slapped him when he got her to
stop two blocks later.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHEELING, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of country music fans will head
for the hills this weekend to see Kathy Mattea, Willie Nelson, The
Charlie Daniels Band and other stars at one of the nation's largest
outdoor country concerts.
   At least 60,000 people are expected at the 13th Annual Jamboree
in the Hills, said concert spokeswoman Kathy Oliver.
   More than 20 recording artists and bands will perform during the
19-hour festival, scheduled to begin at 11 a.m. Saturday with an
appearance by Louise Mandrell.
   One of the regular performers is Tom T. Hall, who has missed only
one of the outdoor jamborees.
   ``It's kind of like a homecoming for me,'' Hall said.
   Other stars scheduled are The Bellamy Brothers, Patty Loveless,
Mel McDaniel, Highway 101, Restless Heart, K.D. Lang, Michael Martin
Murphey, Mel Tillis and George Jones.
</TEXT>
