<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-13 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MICHIGAN CITY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marines were battling for every
inch of beachhead and met no resistance from about 2,000 spectators.
   Four amphibious landing craft from the USS Boulder bounded ashore
Wednesday and disgorged 90 Marines in full battle gear.
   Instead of charging deadly pillboxes and lethal snipers, the
leathernecks directed blank fire toward toward a pop stand, three
port-a-johns and a festively colored tent where a six-piece Navy
band had been playing.
   With bases concentrated on ocean coasts, the Navy and Marines
rarely get to show their stuff to Midwesterners, said Navy Lt. David
Knox.
   Spectators on the Lake Michigan beach broke into applause as the
blank automatic weapons fire finally ceased.
   ``It was really cool,'' said 13-year-old Ryan Huff.
   Mayor Robert Behler, an ex-Marine, rode in the assault wave
carrying a fantasy instead of a rifle.
   ``I wanted to dress like (Gen. Douglas) MacArthur and just stand
on the beach with my corncob pipe and glasses,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man climbed into a hot tub with a joke
and planned to keep up the routine for three days to set a new mark
for hot tub humor.
   ``It's great. Surf's up,'' John Parker said about a half-hour
into his marathon Wednesday. He plans to stay there for at least 73
hours, until Saturday morning.
   He started out with some elephant jokes.
   ``Why do elephants have flat feet?'' he asked. ``It's obviously
because they jump out of trees.''
   ``Most of the jokes are off the top of my head and are jokes I've
collected from 19 years in the radio business,'' said Parker, 36.
``Of course, after 27 hours or so you begin to hallucinate, so
fortunately the Guinness people allow me to use cue cards.''
   The 1989 edition of the Guinness Book of World Records lists him
as the record-holder for time spent telling jokes in a hot tub with
a 52-hour effort, but someone in Portugal has topped that mark.
   The effort to regain the title has its risks.
   ``I've got to keep the temperature of the water between 85 and 90
degrees,'' Parker said. ``Any lower than 85 and hypothermia sets in
without me knowing it. I can go numb, nod off. Any higher than 90,
and I can boil myself without knowing it.''
   Wrinkled feet are another hazard, said Parker, who has survived
four tub-joking marathons. He plans to solve the problem by keeping
his feet out of the water much of the time.
   Parker has a penchant for spending long periods in odd places.
``I once sat in spaghetti for three days,'' he said.
   Unfortunately, Guinness lists no record for spaghetti-sitting.
</TEXT>
