<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     07-13 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Tackles Spending, Deficit-Cutting Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is speeding up work on an assortment
of deficit-cutting and spending bills with the start of the 1990
fiscal year looming closer.
   The House passed the second of 13 annual appropriations
Wednesday, an $11 billion measure for the Interior Department and
cultural programs, on a 374-49 vote. The Senate has yet to approve
any appropriations measures, which provide money for federal
agencies.
   The House Ways and Means Committee gave preliminary voice vote
approval to a measure raising $5.3 billion in new tax receipts,
mainly by boosting a series of levies on businesses. The panel
rejected 22-11 President Bush's pet tax proposal _ a cut in the
capital gains tax that Democrats say benefits only the rich.
   But a deficit-slashing measure ran into problems in the House
Energy and Commerce Committee. The legislation would raise $50
million by increasing fees the Securities and Exchange Commission
charges investors and another $300 million by boosting Nuclear
Regulatory Commission fees imposed on utilities.
   It would also expand the Medicaid program an estimated $5 billion
to $13 billion over five years. That brought objections from Rep.
William Dannemeyer, R-Calif., who called the measure an example of
``the insidious practice of how we expand the liberal welfare
state.''
   Lawmakers returned this week from their Fourth of July recess to
eight weeks of work left until the Oct. 1 start of the next fiscal
year. They take a four-week break in August.
   They must keep the federal deficit to the Gramm-Rudman
deficit-reduction law's limit of $100 billion for 1990, out of a
$1.17 trillion budget, to prevent automatic, across-the-board cuts.
   Two House Appropriations subcommittees, meeting behind closed
doors, tried to finish spending bills for transportation programs
and for labor, health, and education initiatives.
   Across the Capitol, the Senate Appropriations Committee divided
programs worth $658 billion among its 13 subcommittees, opening the
way for those panels to begin writing their own versions of the
spending bills. Members of the committee complained that last
spring's budget deal between President Bush and congressional
leaders would not allow increases for programs that need more money.
   ``I wish we could do better, but we could only cut the cake so
many ways,'' said Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va.
   The House Committee on Post Office and Civil Service voted 23-0
for a package that claims $2.8 billion in savings. Some $1.8 billion
would come from a bookkeeping move _ shifting the Postal Service
``off-budget'' so its losses don't count towards federal red ink.
   Other claimed savings would come by shifting the date on which
the Postal Service reimburses the government $330 million for
workers compensation payments from fiscal 1991 into fiscal 1990.
Another $700 million in savings would be realized by spreading
federal civilian employees retirement payments over two years,
instead of in one single check.
</TEXT>
