<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Charity     07-13 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Charity,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charity Linked to Ex-HUD Official Not Registered to Solicit Contributions</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Retransmitting to include slug</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FOOD for Africa, a pet charity of a former top
official at the Department of Housing and Urban Development, has
raised thousands of dollars without proper registration in several
states, according to records.
   A check by The Associated Press of the offices of state attorneys
general and other agencies regulating charities found FOOD is not
registered in New York, Pennsylvania, Louisiana, the District of
Columbia, Colorado, California, Massachusetts or its home state of
Michigan.
   The organization raised at least $580,000 from 1986 to 1988, much
of it in those states, and half of that came from individuals or
firms known to be involved with HUD programs, according to an
internal agency report released in April.
   ``I was told we didn't have to have a license,'' Vasilios
Damavolites, FOOD's treasurer, said in an interview from Novi,
Mich., where the organization is headquartered.
   Damavolites, who is president of Dial Construction Corp. and goes
by the anglicized name of Bill Damas, said contributions have been
difficult to raise since the release of a HUD report that touched on
the organization and its links to former agency official Thomas T.
Demery.
   ``We don't want to operate illegally,'' Damas said. ``We're not
going to do anything else until we receive the proper license.''
   Despite lacking appropriate state registration, FOOD holds
federal tax exempt status from the Internal Revenue Service, meaning
that donations are tax deductible.
   Damas said information about state licenses is kept by Peter
Pretorius, who runs FOOD's relief operations from his home in South
Africa. Pretorius could not be reached for comment. His secretary in
South Africa said Tuesday that Pretorius and his wife, Ann, were
attending an evangelical conference in Manila, Philippines.
   FOOD for Africa was an obscure relief organization delivering
food and clothing to war refugees in Mozambique until the release of
a HUD audit in April. The report probed possible connections between
donations to FOOD by real estate developers and contracts awarded
under HUD's Moderate Rehabilitation program.
   The HUD rehabilitation program, which gave rent subsidies to
developers to renovate housing for low-income residents, was
suspended after the audit's release because of charges of favoritism
in the awarding of contracts.
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp said Tuesday he had instituted new
controls and restarted the program.
   Demery's links to FOOD date to 1985, when he helped establish the
charity. He quit his position as director after he moved to HUD as
assistant secretary for housing, according to the report.
   The report said Demery continued to work for the charity,
attending at least eight fund-raisers in the 20 months after he
became assistant secretary. A check of Demery's phone logs, obtained
under the Freedom of Information Act, revealed that Demery often
spoke to FOOD officials during working hours.
   After the investigation, HUD Inspector General Paul Adams
concluded that Demery may have violated the department's standards
of conduct, which prohibit employees from directly or indirectly
soliciting anything of value from anyone with ``interests that may
substantially be affected'' by HUD.
   Demery says the conclusions were based on circumstantial
evidence, and says he never asked for contributions from any HUD
developer.
   FOOD for Africa at one time held a license to solicit
contributions in its home state of Michigan, but allowed it to lapse
in September 1987, according to documents obtained from the Michigan
attorney general. A reapplication made this year has been delayed
until FOOD can provide notarized signatures of two officers, the
documents show.
   Yet FOOD held two fund-raisers in Michigan in 1988 and 1989, the
organization's treasurer said in a telephone interview this week.
FOOD also held at least 10 fundraising events in six other states
and the District of Columbia in 1987 and 1988, according to the HUD
audit.
   FOOD also filed papers with the Michigan attorney general in June
saying that it had ``pending applications in other states'' for
licenses, although Damas said he did not know which states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
