<FIRST>r w PM-Soviet-Psychiatric Bjt   07-13 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Psychiatric, Bjt,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Team Calls for Safeguards for Soviets Sent to Mental Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is still hospitalizing
citizens who are not mentally ill, says a team of U.S. health
experts who recommend additional reforms to prevent confinement of
political dissidents.
   The 26-member delegation's report, released Wednesday, said broad
concepts of ``social dangerousness'' have contributed to the Soviet
practice of hospitalizing people who are not mentally ill.
   In response, the Soviet side expressed disagreement with some
aspects of the study but nonetheless called it a ``valuable and
useful document.''
   The delegation visited the Soviet Union from Feb. 26 to March 12
to assess recent changes in Soviet psychiatry. They examined 15
patients and 12 former patients who had been released within the
preceding two years.
   Among the 12, ``the U.S. team found no evidence of any past or
current mental disorder in nine, and the remaining three had
relatively mild symptoms that would not typically warrant
involuntary hospitalization,'' said delegation member Darrel A.
Regier, director of clinical research at the National Institute of
Mental Health.
   The delegation's report said it ``recommends that additional
steps be taken to revise the Soviet Criminal Codes to remove all
prohibitions against expression of political or religious beliefs.''
   In addition, the report said new legislation or regulations
appear necessary to limit involuntary hospitalizations solely to
those who are a direct danger to themselves or others.
   The report also recommended increased use of defense lawyers to
guard against abuse of patients, and the use of periodic reviews to
ensure that hospital stays are not excessively long.
   According to the report, the Soviet hosts generally complied with
the terms of the agreement under which the visit was made although
there were some ``significant procedural obstacles'' that made
completing the task more difficult.
   The preliminary Soviet response to the report acknowledged the
existence of such obstacles but said the problem ``by no means meant
that the Soviet specialists artificially created difficulties and
tried to limit access to the necessary information on the patients.''
   The Soviet response said efforts are being made to bring Soviet
laws into conformity with international standards.
   In addition, it said, there has been discussion of the creation
of an independent commission ``to examine any and all complaints of
wrongful acts by employees of the psychiatric service, and for
public monitoring of the activity of psychiatric institutions.''
   The U.S. team made the visit against a background of allegations
about misuse of psychiatric treatment in the Soviet Union. One
report cited 346 cases of alleged psychiatric abuse between 1977 and
1983.
   The perception that the problem was rampant prompted the World
Psychiatric Association to condemn Moscow in 1977 for the alleged
practices.
   Faced with expulsion from the group, the Soviet All-Union Society
of Neuropathologists and Psychiatrists resigned from the WPA in 1983.
   But the American delegation acknowledged there has been progress
in recent years toward establishing some legal protection for
patients subject to forced confinement.
</TEXT>
