<FIRST>r w PM-NorthropSuspension     07-13 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northrop Suspension,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northrop Division Temporarily Suspended By Air Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A division of the Northrop Corp. won't be
allowed to do business with the government because of alleged fraud
connected to two weapons systems the division worked on.
   Precision Product Division of Norwood, Mass., was suspended
temporarily because of criminal charges brought last spring over the
division's work on the flight data transmitter for the air-launched
cruise missile and a stabilization system for the Navy's AV-8B
Harrier jet, Northrop said Wednesday.
   The suspension is temporary pending completion of the legal
proceedings, according to the Air Force letter informing Northrop of
the suspension.
   The letter, obtained by The Associated Press, said the indictment
returned in the federal court in Los Angeles alleged Northrop and
others ``conspired to defraud the government by knowingly supplying
untested and out-of-specification flight stabilization and control
packages and making false, fictitious and fraudulent statements and
representations'' regarding the cruise missile and the Harrier jet.
   The suspension involves only future business at Precision
Products, not contracts elsewhere at Northrop or contracts at
Precision on which work is now underway. The company said the
division accounts for about 2{ percent of sales and less than 4
percent of its $5 billion order backlog.
   Northrop is a major defense contractor, building the new B-2
``stealth'' bomber.
   Northrop spokesman Loye Miller called the government's charges
``unwarranted and exaggerated,'' and the suspension ``unnecessary.''
   ``The company intends to provide information in opposition to the
government's temporary suspension of the unit,'' the statement said.
   Northrop's statement said the company has taken ``strong
actions'' to assure that it is a responsible contractor, including
the closure of a facility in Pomona, Calif., and the dismissal of
several employees.
</TEXT>
