<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-13 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Cites Collision Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy says its safety record is ``second to
none,'' even though its submarines have been involved at least 42
collisions with other vessels since 1983.
   Navy spokesman Cmdr. Mark Baker said Wednesday that the number
includes 15 incidents with other U.S. Navy vessels and work boats,
including minor collisions with the tugboats that help a sub enter a
harbor.
   Baker was commenting on a report in the Long Beach, Calif.,
Press-Telegram over the weekend that said Navy documents revealed
that the service's submarines have been involved at least 42
collisions with other vessels, including five fishing boats, since
1983.
   In the most serious incident, the attack submarine USS Houston
snagged a towing cable of the commercial tugboat Barcona off Long
Beach last month. The tug was sunk and one member of the three-man
crew drowned.
   The Navy has that case under investigation.
   Baker said the Barcona fatality ``is the only one that we know
of.''
   The spokesman said a Navy study of collisions involving
submarines from 1983 to 1987 found that five collisions had occurred
with other submarines, one with a destroyer and one with a rescue
salvage ship.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Senate Panel Approves Health Insurance Bill</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee has approved a measure by
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy to require American employers to provide
health insurance to all their workers and their workers' dependents.
   The measure cleared Kennedy's Labor and Human Resources Committee
on a 9-7 party-line vote Wednesday. But it's strongly opposed by the
administration and other powerful groups, including many business
organizations.
   The Kennedy bill is intended to provide coverage for the
estimated 37 million Americans not now covered by any public or
private health insurance.
   Although many of the details have been reworked, the bill is
similar to one that cleared the committee last year but was not
considered in either the full Senate or House.
   Kennedy noted that the majority of businesses already insure
their workers, ``yet two-thirds of all the Americans who lack basic
health insurance protection are workers or members of working
families.''
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole, argued against the measure in a
letter to Kennedy, saying enactment of his bill ``would result in a
significant loss of job opportunities, impair our nation's economic
competitiveness, and interfere with the right of employees and
employers to determine between themselves the most appropriate
compensation package to meet their circumstances.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Cable Association Says Baseball Growing on Local TV, Too</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local television stations, not just cable TV
networks, are increasing the number of Major League baseball games
they carry, a cable TV group says.
   The National Cable Television Association on Wednesday disputed
claims that cable companies are stealing baseball from ``free TV.''
   Local broadcast coverage of professional baseball has grown by
nearly 40 percent over the past 15 years, from 1,190 games in 1975
to 1,647 games in 1989, the association said.
   The number of baseball games televised by both local broadcast
stations and by regional cable sports networks has increased 7
percent since 1985, the NCTA said.
   ``As a result, cable's baseball coverage has served to
supplement, rather than reduce, the number of games aired by local
broadcasters,'' the cable association said in a report,
``Availability of Baseball Games on Broadcast and Cable Television.''
   It said some broadcasters have contended that baseball on cable
has reduced the number of games carried by local television stations.
</TEXT>
