<FIRST>r a PM-NationalGuard-Gangs     07-13 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-National Guard-Gangs,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon National Guard Called Out to Fight Gangs, Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD GREEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Guardsmen have joined police in
their battle against violent, drug-dealing gangs from Los Angeles
that have wreaked havoc on Portland's north side.
   Mayor Bud Clark and state officials said Wednesday the first of
36 National Guardsmen reported to work late last week with the
Portland Police Bureau and the Oregon State Police.
   The rest will join the ranks by the end of this week and eight
others will be on call, said the guard's director, Gen. Fred Rees.
   The guardsmen will fill support roles, acting as Spanish
interpreters, taking telephone tips and doing paperwork. That will
enable police to deploy more officers on the streets.
   Portland is beset by gang violence, with five killings blamed on
drive-by gang shootings since August.
   There have been about four dozen gang-related shootings this
year, including one Tuesday night that seriously wounded a
13-year-old boy.
   ``It's clearly a problem,'' said Gregg Kantor, Governor Neil
Goldschmidt's spokesman. ``It's not as big as Los Angeles' gang
problem, but it is very serious for us and one we don't intend to
tolerate.''
   Officials have not decided how long the guardsmen will remain in
Portland, but the effort has federal financing through October.
   ``It's just one more increment, one more step,'' Robert Jackson,
the governor's anti-crime coordinator, said at a news conference.
``The gang problem is bigger than this; the narcotics problem is
bigger than this.''
   Drive-by gang shootings were unheard of in the Pacific Northwest
until last summer, when the rival drug-dealing Crips and Bloods
gangs began expanding from Los Angeles to Portland and other cities.
   Turf battles ensued and the region's first fatal drive-by gang
shooting occurred last Aug. 17.
   ``We're not going to walk away from this saying 36 or 40 troops
is enough until we have gotten rid of the drug problem in Oregon and
specifically in Portland,'' Jackson said.
   Portland Deputy Chief Dan Noelle said the guardsmen will free up
more officers for street deployments.
   ``In terms of looking at raw numbers, it's not a big deal,''
Noelle said, but in terms of support work, ``it's a real asset.''
   The state received $474,000 from the Department of Defense to use
the National Guard to fight crime. About half that money will be
used to pay troops in Portland through Sept. 30, Rees said.
   Congress specifically said the National Guard could be used only
for support when it passed an act giving states $300 million for
anti-drug efforts, Rees said.
   ``The National Guard is not supposed to be in the arrest or
seizure business,'' he said.
</TEXT>
