<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WarholCollages     07-13 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Warhol Collages,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Questions Raised About Authenticity of Warhol's Superman Collages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The authenticity of 19 Superman collages by Andy
Warhol has been called into question by two comic book experts who
say the Superman cut-outs didn't appear in print until years after
the date on the artworks.
   ``Either they were misdated or somebody has made some work that
is not what it purports to be,'' said Robert Miller, a New York art
dealer who owns 18 of the collages.
   The discrepancy was detected by comic book experts Arlen Schumer
and Richard Sheinaus during independent visits to a Warhol
retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art in New York, which ran
from Feb. 6 to May 2.
   Schumer said in a telephone interview Monday he was looking in
the exhibition catalog at an untitled Superman collage, dated
1960-61, when he recognized the inking style of the artist who did
the cartoon panel.
   ``I remembered that Jack Abel did not start inking Superman until
the late 1960s, maybe 1969. And I thought `Hold it, something is
wrong here!'''
   ``When I met Sheinaus a month later, he said, `Did you notice
anything funny about the Warhol exhibition?''' Schumer said. ``I
looked him right in the eye and said `One has got to be a fraud.'
   ``He said, `You won't believe this but there are about 15 of
them.'''
   The series of 19 collages has been estimated to be worth about $5
million. Each piece was signed twice and dated 1960-61. The DC
Comics they came from _ like ``Superman's Greatest Blunder'' (1968)
and ``Muto vs. the Man of Tomorrow'' (1966) _ sold for 12 cents each.
   Seven of the collages _ cut-outs from original comic books that
were pasted on paper and splattered with red or blue paint _ were on
display during the MOMA retrospective; six were loaned by Miller,
one by an unidentified private collector, said Jeanne Collins, a
museum spokeswoman.
   In a statement, the museum said, ``Works of art are selected for
exhibitions based on careful research and on the best information
available at the time.
   ``In any retrospective of an artist there may be questions
regarding dating; however, we have no reason whatsoever to doubt the
authenticity of any of the works included in the Andy Warhol
retrospective,'' it said.
   Edward Hayes, a lawyer for the Warhol estate, said that the
discrepancy in dating was being investigated but that a preliminary
examination indicated the collages were authentic.
   However, Vincent Fremont, a director of the estate, told the San
Francisco Chronicle, which reported on the mismatch in dates on
Monday, that he didn't recall seeing the collages during the '60s
and '70s.
   ``I've worked with Andy since I was 18, and you didn't see them
being bought and sold,'' he said. ``You see what I am saying?''
   Gerard Malanga, who in 1963 became Warhol's first studio
assistant, said he saw the collages for the first time at the
exhibition.
   ``I was fascinated because I knew almost everything Andy was
doing at that time, and I thought `Why didn't I know about these
things?'''
   He said that later when he learned about the discrepancy in
dates, he doubted that the works were Warhol's.
   ``Those pieces require someone to sit down at a kitchen table
with scissors and glue,'' he said. ``Andy would not have taken the
time to do something like that.''
   He also noted that during 1961-62, Warhol's comic book images
were paintings not collages. Warhol quit using comic book images
after about 1962, when he learned Roy Lichtenstein was also using
them.
   Malanga also noted that Warhol often had his assistants sign his
works for him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
