<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0502EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-13 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops In Tokyo, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen in quiet
trading in Tokyo today, while stock prices slipped.
   The dollar closed at 139.05 yen, down 1.45 yen from its finish on
Wednesday. After opening lower at 139.63 yen, the U.S. currency
ranged between 138.82 and 139.68 yen.
   Currency dealers said the market was quiet as players waited for
the release of U.S. economic figures, including producer prices for
June, retail sales and industrial production, all due out Friday.
   ``There was some profit-taking, causing the dollar's fall,'' said
Masato Sanjo, a dealer in the Tokyo office of Manufacturers' Hanover
Trust.``But I don't expect any major movements in the market until
the release of economic indicators tomorrow.''
   Another dealer said a comment Wednesday by the governor of the
Bank of Japan also encouraged the dollar-selling. Satoshi Sumita
reportedly told journalists that the U.S. currency was still too
strong against the yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which shed 45.25 points Wednesday, lost another
70.36 points, or 0.20 percent, closing at 33,631.16.
   Securities dealers said the recent strong performance of overseas
stock exchanges was encouraging investors on the Tokyo market, but
the low volume of trading reflected investors' lack of interest and
concern over continuing political uncertainties in Japan.
   ``The external environment is not too bad, but investors find it
hard to particapate in trading as long as political uncertainties
persist,'' said Ichitaro Watanabe, a dealer for Nikko Securities.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party's majority in the upper
house of the Diet, Japan's parliament, is widely seen in jeopardy in
upcoming elections because of the party's involvement in scandals
and a public uproar over an unpopular 3 percent consumption tax
which began April 1.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange, which lists
major issues, was estimated at 550 million shares, compared with
Wednesday's 600 million shares.
</TEXT>
