<FIRST>r a PM-Executions     07-13 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Executions,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mentally Retarded Killers: One Spared Electric Chair, Second Awaits
Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A killer was spared the electric chair as state
justices reviewed conflicting laws on executing mentally retarded
people, while federal judges considered the same issue in the case
of an Alabama killer.
   The cases followed the U.S. Supreme Court decision two weeks ago
that allows states to execute mentally retarded murderers as long as
sentencing juries or judges have considered the defendant's mental
condition.
   The Georgia Supreme Court voted 4-3 Wednesday to delay the
scheduled execution of Son Fleming, who was sentenced to die for the
1976 slaying of a Georgia police chief. The stay came Wednesday five
hours before the 59-year-old Fleming was to go to the electric chair.
   In the second case, attorneys for murderer-rapist Horace Franklin
Dunkins Jr. turned today to the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta in a bid to halt his execution at 12:01 a.m. Friday in
Alabama. The lawyers claim Dunkins is mentally retarded.
   A U.S. District judge on Wednesday turned down the appeal.
   In the Fleming case, a new Georgia law bans executions of the
mentally retarded but it does not apply retroactively. Fleming's
death warrant runs for a week, and he could be executed at any time
during that period if the court rules by then. Court officials said
the review could take several days.
   Fleming's IQ scores range from 64 to 72; a person with an IQ of
70 is considered mentally handicapped.
   ``The execution of the mentally retarded in Georgia is cruel and
unusual punishment,'' said Fleming's attorney, Ken Shapiro. ``There
should be no fine line between those who happen to be tried in 1989
and those who happen to be tried in 1976. That's an arbitrary
distinction, happenstance that should not be applicable.''
   On Tuesday, the Pardons and Paroles Board rejected Fleming's
appeal for clemency. Board chairman Wayne Snow said the decision was
made on grounds that Fleming was aware of the consequences of his
actions, no matter what his IQ.
   Snow said the U.S. Supreme Court decision also was a factor in
the board's decision.
   Fleming, of Rochelle, was convicted along with Henry Willis III
of killing Ray City Police Chief Ed Giddens in 1976. Willis was
executed May 18. Fleming's nephew, Larry Fleming, is serving a life
sentence for murder in the case.
   Dunkins' attorneys, meanwhile, argued his execution should be
halted on grounds that a jury didn't consider Dunkins' alleged
mental deficiency during his 1981 trial. In court documents,
Dunkins' IQ was listed at 69.
   In Wednesday's denial of a stay of execution, U.S. District Judge
James Hancock said that even if jurors didn't consider Dunkins'
mental condition, the trial judge did. The judge sentenced Dunkins
to die in Alabama's electric chair.
   Alabama has no state law prohibiting the execution of the
mentally retarded.
   A jury convicted Dunkins in May 1981 of capital murder in the
rape and slaying of Lynn McCurry, a 26-year-old mother of four from
Warrior, Ala.
</TEXT>
