<FIRST>r a PM-Executions-Stevens     07-13 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Executions-Stevens,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Justice Questions Deterrent Value of Death Penalty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Executions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA NIGUEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice John Paul
Stevens said death penalty cases are ``a very severe burden on the
judicial system'' and questioned whether executions deter crime.
   Stevens, speaking Wednesday to the annual conference of the 9th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, said states should consider the
judicial burden when the issue of capital punishment arises.
   ``I would think from time to time, when legislators confront
whether the capital sentencing, whole death-penalty business, is
really worth the cost, one of the elements of the costs that ought
to be factored into the equation is the very severe burden on the
judicial system, both state and federal,'' Stevens said.
   He cited the Supreme Court's emergency hearings on requests for
stays of execution. The hearings are often late at night.
   ``As the number of executions is continuing to increase ... one
can raise the question whether they're really doing all that much to
deter crime,'' Stevens said.
   Asked afterward whether he thought the burdens of the death
penalty on the legal system outweighed the benefits, Stevens said,
``There is a serious question,'' and declined to comment further.
   Stevens, a 1975 appointee of President Ford, has voted to allow
some executions but dissented from the court's recent rulings that
allowed states to execute 16-year-olds and mentally retarded adults.
   On another topic, Stevens said the court wasn't affected by the
flood of letters before last week's abortion ruling.
   The only problem was ``sorting that stuff out and throwing it in
the wastebasket, because nobody read any of it,'' said Stevens, who
voted against the decision that gave states to more power to
regulate abortions.
</TEXT>
