<FIRST>u a PM-FloridaGuns     07-13 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Guns,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Kills Sister Hours After Florida Gun Bill Signed Into Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infant was killed with a gun her
6-year-old sister found under their parents' pillow hours after Gov.
Bob Martinez signed a bill intended to protect children from
accidental shootings.
   Ten-month-old Enercida Suarez was shot late late Wednesday and
died early today at St. Joseph's Hospital in Tampa, police said.
   She was the seventh victim of such an accident since June 1.
   ``The 6-year-old found the .38-caliber revolver laying on their
parents' bed under a pillow ... and thinking it was a toy, and fired
it one time, striking the girl in the head,'' said Tampa police
officer S. Middleton.
   Possible charges are pending against the girls' parents, Amancio
and Reina Suarez, and police are continuing to investigate the
shooting, Middleton said.
   But the law Martinez signed Wednesday doesn't take effect until
October 1 and won't apply in this case, he said.
   The law requires gun owners to take reasonable precautions to
keep loaded weapons in their homes and businesses out of the hands
of children age 15 and younger by using trigger locks or keeping the
weapon in a locked box.
   ``This will assist in protecting our children throughout the
state,'' Martinez said. ``The added public awareness will prompt
adults to keep guns out of reach.''
   Wednesday's signing ceremony also came one day after a 9-year-old
Clearwater boy shot himself in the finger. Tomy Zemko found the
.25-caliber pistol after climbing onto a chair to get some potato
chips from atop the refrigerator in his grandmother's home. He was
treated for a broken finger.
   Three children died and two were wounded in the earlier
shootings, inspiring lawmakers to push for the first-of-its kind
legislation during a special session last month.
   The law provides for adult gun owners to be charged with a
felony, punishable by up to five years in prison and a $5,000 fine,
if a child shoots himself or another child because of the owner's
carelessness.
   If a minor threatens someone with the gun or displays it in
public, its owner faces a misdemeanor charge and up to 60 days in
jail with a $500 fine.
   No grieving parent of an injured or fatally wounded child shot by
another member of the family could be arrested until seven days
after the shooting.
   There are exemptions for hunting and target-shooting accidents
and those involving guns taken illegally.
   The measure also will authorize the development of a gun safety
program in the state's public schools.
   The Unified Sportsmen of Florida, the state affiliate of the
National Rifle Association, helped lawmakers write legislation it
could support after a stronger version it opposed was rejected
during the Legislature's regular 60-day session, which ended June 3.
   The Florida law may inspire similar legislation in other states,
said Bernard Horn, state legislative director for Washington-based
Handgun Control Inc.
   Lawmakers from states including California, New York, Illinois,
Ohio, Wisconsin, Connecticut, Massachusetts, Maryland and Virginia
have contacted Horn's organization about the law, he said.
</TEXT>
