<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HarpMovers     07-13 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harp Movers,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Men Span the Globe to Move Harps, Keep Performers Loose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone can move a harp, but few can do
it with the charm and wit of Hans Verbugt and George Bruls.
   Organizers of the USA International Harp Competition realized
this when they invited the ``Dutch boys'' to move harps here during
the 10-day competition.
   ``They're just really fun to have around,'' said Elizabeth
Hainen, one of four finalists. ``They're good for everyone's
spirits.''
   The two have been known to dance all night and move harps all day
without losing their charm. They take seriously the task of
entertaining contestants who have been eliminated.
   Their responsibilities, however, are not all fun and games.
   Carrying the harp with its 47 strings and 2,000 moving pieces is
serious business. Elaborate charts are required to get the right
harp in the right place at the right moment.
   ``Contestants are very nervous normally,'' Bruls said. ``To break
a harp is one thing. If you put it down with a bump, then they start
saying, `Oh no, the tuning is gone.' Before you break it, you can
really screw up the tuning.''
   The men also shuffle two piano benches and several special harp
chairs for contestants.
   ``They want their own chairs,'' Verbugt said. ``It has to be in a
particular position, with this side facing out or that one.
Everything has to be that way, otherwise they cannot get into their
proper mood.''
   ``They take the load off our shoulders,'' said Robert G.
Campbell, president and executive director of the competition.
``We'd have to hire somebody who'd have to be trained how to handle
harps.''
   During this competition at Indiana University, Bruls and Verbugt
have moved harps from practice rooms to the stage for 37
competitors. They also have stood on their heads to evoke smiles and
held a harpist tightly when a painful finger forced her to quit the
competition.
   Verbugt, a musicologist, and Bruls, a physicist, are the last to
see a harpist before she goes onstage and the first to congratulate
or console her after the performance.
   ``Some need a shoulder to cry on. Some need someone to laugh
with,'' Bruls said. ``This stupid carrying, anyone can do it. The
atmosphere you have to create, that makes it interesting to us.''
   The men came upon their hobby by accident. Bruls' former
girlfriend in Holland was a harpist, and he was enlisted to help
move instruments at the first World Harp Congress there in 1983.
   That led to an invitation to the second congress in Israel in
1985 and the third in Vienna in 1987.
   ``It's a very nice way to see the world,'' Bruls said.
   The two say they've noticed that it also is a nice way to meet
beautiful women. Ninety-nine percent of the world's top harpists are
women.
   ``They need special attention,'' Verbugt said with a knowing
smile.
   Verbugt comes to harp competitions to research a book he is
writing on Dutch harpist Phia Berghout.
   Bruls uses them to escape the stress of physics and enjoy the
heavenly sounds.
   ``I really like the music,'' he said. ``It's the best music there
is.''
   In addition to Ms. Hainen, 22, of Toledo, Ohio, the other
finalists are Kirsten Agresta, 18, of Bloomfield Hills, Mich.; Maria
Casale, 26, of North Hollywood, Calif.; and Marie-Pierre Chavaroche,
19, of France.
   All four will perform solo and with orchestra Friday night in the
last stage of competition.
   The first-place winner will receive a Lyon and Healy concert harp
worth more than $17,000 and a New York debut recital March 13 at
Lincoln Center.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
