<FIRST>u a PM-Fires-Glance     07-13 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires-Glance,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Forest Fires At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a state-by-state glance at details on fires in the West:
   _Utah: Nine fires still active that had burned 34,480 acres, with
all but a 100-acre fire near Green River contained. Largest, a
15,500-acre fire 20 miles west of the Colorado line, was contained
Wednesday. About 950 firefighters had been on the lines, but most
were being demobilized Wednesday.
   _Arizona: Firefighters were being sent to other states Wednesday
after rain helped them contain and control most of the state's
lightning-caused fires, and 360,000 acres in the Coconino and
Apache-Sitgreaves national forests in the northern and eastern
sections of the state were reopened.
   _California: Four fires still active that had burned 16,473
acres, with two of them contained. Largest fire, east of San Diego,
had burned 4,670 acres and was 80 percent contained. Officials
pushed back the target for containing a 2,900-acre fire in rough
terrain near Big Sur to Friday evening.
   _Colorado: A half-inch of rain fell in Boulder Canyon, helping
crews contain a 2,000-acre fire that destroyed 37 homes and damaged
19 other buildings, and a 2,600-acre fire in Mesa Verde National
Park was controlled without damaging ruins left by 13th century
Anasazi Indians. Four fires still active that had burned nearly
6,000 acres, with three of them contained.
   _Nebraska: Fort Robinson fire was contained Wednesday but several
hot spots remained well within the fire line. Land burned by the
5-day-old fire was estimated at 50,000 to 100,000 acres. Believed to
have burned 14 unoccupied structures.
   _Wyoming: Four fires still active, with three of them contained.
Largest fire, in Bridger-Teton National Forest, had burned 3,447
acres and was contained Monday but still burning.
</TEXT>
