<FIRST>r a PM-JetEngines-Sting     07-13 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jet Engines-Sting,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airmen, Wife Plead Innocent In Jet-Engine Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kimberly Stroud arrived at federal court to
hear her husband plead innocent to charges of stealing three Air
Force jet engines. By the end of the hearing, she was standing next
to him as a defendant.
   Mrs. Stroud, who was unaware of the allegations against her, was
named in a 22-count grand jury indictment released Wednesday at a
detention hearing for her husband, Senior Airman Danny Joe Stroud,
and Airman 1st Class Brian David Roth, both military policemen at
Hill Air Force Base.
   Roth, 22, of Chesterland, Ohio, and Stroud, 23, of Wichita, Kan.,
were arrested Monday in the July 3 theft of three 3,200-pound F-16
fighter jet engines from the northern Utah installation. The jets
are valued at $2 million each.
   Mrs. Stroud, 22, was charged at the detention hearing, where all
three defendants pleaded innocent to the counts and were given Sept.
10 trial dates by U.S. Magistrate Ronald Boyce.
   The Strouds' attorney, Stephen Madsen, said Mrs. Stroud had been
due to be summoned to court rather than arrested.
   ``She did appear voluntarily and she was not aware of this until
she did appear,'' he said.
   The arrests and 12 other indictments against as-yet unidentified
people capped an FBI sting operation aimed at servicemen, civilians
and wholesalers in stolen goods at Hill, other Utah military
installations and elsewhere, the FBI said.
   Roth and the Strouds were charged with selling or disposing of
government property valued at more than $8.1 million, including the
three engines, a flight-line tow tractor and three engine trailers.
   Mrs. Stroud's alleged involvement was not explained.
   In Count 2, Roth and Stroud were charged with aiding and abetting
each other in stealing and selling $64,000 worth of Zenith computers.
   Roth alone was named in Counts 3 through 22, which charged theft
of such items as a combat helmet, chemical protective clothing,
military supplies, aviation instruments, radios and bullet-proof
vests.
   Boyce ordered Roth held in the Salt Lake County jail after FBI
agent Donald Roberts testified that Roth told undercover agents that
if he was caught, he would ``run and not be found.''
   The magistrate ordered Stroud confined to barracks pending an
agreement between prosecutors and his commander and also granted
Stroud supervised visits with his 5-month-old daughter and wife, who
was released.
</TEXT>
