<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BuggedPoliticans     07-13 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bugged Politicans,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Restaurant Frequented by Politicians Finds It is Bugged by FBI</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tiny video camera and cable used in a federal
investigation of political corruption were uncovered by a busboy at
a restaurant across from City Hall, an attorney for the restaurant's
owners says.
   ``The FBI planted the listening devices, and they were discovered
by one of our busboys,'' attorney Nicholas M. Spina was quoted as
saying in today's editions of the Chicago Tribune.
   George Borovilos, co-owner of the restaurant, said he waited
several days to call the FBI about the equipment because ``we didn't
know who it belonged to.''
   Borovilos said that after he talked to the FBI Tuesday, agents
removed the camera from the restaurant. They left behind the
connecting wire that ran under a seat cushion, through a concrete
wall and down into the basement of the building, he told the Tribune.
   Spina said the sophisticated wide-angle camera, with a lens the
size of a little finger, was found Friday hidden in the base of a
booth at Counselors Row Restaurant, a popular spot for lawmakers,
lawyers, government workers and other City Hall employees.
   He said the camera was pointed at a table often used by Alderman
Fred Roti, Democratic ward Committeeman John D'Arco and influential
businessman Pat Marcy.
   The paper quoted unidentified sources as saying the FBI also
tapped a telephone on a pedestal next to the table.
   Spina said the restaurant's owners were ``shocked, outraged and
extremely upset that this type of conduct exists in the United
States.''
   Gary Shapiro, the federal prosecutor in charge of organized crime
investigations in Chicago, said he had authorized planting the
device, Spina said.
   Spina said a judge approved the installation of the surveillance
equipment and it was placed in the restaurant without the owners'
consent, apparently on a weekend when the place was closed.
   Alderman Richard Mell, who also frequents the table or ones
nearby, said, ``I have no problem with (the bugs). Is it true?. It
looks like a very interesting story.''
   Roti said in a statement, ``There is no reason for me to be
investigated, and no reason to believe that I am being
investigated.''
   The NBC network affiliate WMAQ-TV reported that the strike force
has been investigating possible corruption in the 1st Ward,
including gambling in its Chinatown section.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas declined to comment, as did Shapiro,
director of the U.S. Justice Department's Organized Crime Strike
Force, the television station said.
   Dan Gillogly, spokesman for the U.S. Attorney's office, told The
Associated Press early today he didn't know anything about the story.
   D'Arco and Marcy didn't return telephone messages, WMAQ and the
Chicago Tribune said.
</TEXT>
