<FIRST>r a PM-SerialSlayings 1stLd-Writethru a0518 07-13 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Serial Slayings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Slaying Seen Linked to 41 Other Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lede, 2nd graf to move up number of women killed.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homicide detectives believe a 22-year-old woman
is the latest victim in a series of 41 killings dating back to 1985.
   Sheriff's deputies found Nicolette Jean Frye's body Monday in a
ravine in East San Diego County. The investigation of her death has
been taken over by a task force looking into the deaths of the other
women in similar circumstances.
   Frye had been dead three or four days when her body was found
lying at the bottom of a steep embankment near La Mesa, which is
north of San Diego.
   Her body was fully clothed, unlike most of the other victims, who
were left naked or partially clad.
   Court records show that Frye had a history of prostitution and
drug use as did most of the other victims.
   An autopsy on Frye's body was inconclusive. The cause of death
will not be known until further tests have been conducted.
   Metropolitan Homicide Task Force spokesman Jim Cooke said there
are no suspects.
   Frye's boyfriend, Fernando Astorga, and others said she was
trying to put her life back together.
   But Astorga said Frye's problems with drugs were not over and
that she probably was working as a prostitute on the streets shortly
before she died.
   Many of the deaths are similar to an unsolved string of 48
killings in the Seattle area from 1982 through 1984.
</TEXT>
