<SECOND>PM-College Shooting,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman in Wig Kills College Maintenance Chief, Escapes into Subway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman wearing a wig and dark glasses shot and
killed a college maintenance chief in the school courtyard, then
fled into a nearby subway station and escaped in the morning
rush-hour crowds, police said.
   George Roscoe, 43, was shot three times in the back Wednesday. He
died a short time later at New York Hospital.
   The woman, wearing a red jogging suit, had been seen lurking that
morning at Hunter College, on Manhattan's East Side, for Roscoe to
show up for work, authorities said.
   The killer, described as in her 20s, yelled, ``You lying
mother,'' before shooting Roscoe with a small-caliber handgun, a
security guard told police, according to the New York Post in
today's editions.
   Before disappearing into the subway station, the woman shed the
black wig and sunglasses, which were retrieved, said police
spokesman Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell. The gun was not recovered.
   About 50,000 subway commuters were delayed for more than 30
minutes after police stopped a train to search for the suspect, said
Transit Authority spokesman Termaine Garden.
   The New York Post and New York Newsday both reported that Roscoe
had recently moved out of his girlfriend's apartment. The woman was
questioned but released without charges, police sources said.
   Roscoe, the divorced father of two children, was acting director
of housekeeping services, said Hunter spokeswoman Patricia Falk.
</TEXT>
