<FIRST>r w PM-BlackCatholics 1stLd-Writethru a0437 07-13 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Catholics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Bishops Urge Suspended Priest to Return to `Unity of the Church'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to specify that all black bishops made the appeal;
subs 3rd graf, Stallings told, to insert total church membership; makes
second reference to Ricard in last graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspended Roman Catholic priest is rejecting
a call by the church's U.S. black bishops that he abandon his
unsanctioned African-American Catholic congregation.
   ``The people have spoken,'' the Rev. George A. Stallings Jr.,
said Wednesday, citing the number of people who attended the first
two weeks of services at his Imani Temple.
   Stallings told The Washington Post the bishops' statement was
``predictable'' and said they ``opted for office and position over
their ability to exercise a prophetic voice'' in the leadership of
the 53-million-member American church's nearly 2 million black
members.
   The priest said he has no intention of abandoning his church,
adding instead that he plans to expand it. He has contended that the
Catholic church fails to address the needs of its black parishioners.
   The bishops, in a statement, said Stallings ``possesses the
vibrancy of our culture and spiritual heritage'' but should make
those changes within the church.
   ``We implore him to return to the unity of the church,'' the
bishops said, ``and to continue to urge reform ... within the unity
of the one Catholic church.''
   Cardinal James A. Hickey, archbishop of Washington, said in a
column published in the Post today that the controversy over
Stallings' church ``is not a dispute between those who oppose racism
and those who support it.''
   The dispute ``has more to do with the problems and expectations
of one individual than broader questions about the adequacy of the
church's ministry in the black community,'' Hickey said. ``To Father
Stallings, I say come home.''
   In a statement distributed by the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops, the 13 bishops said racism exists in the church but that
the problem must be solved by dialogue between the black community
and the church leaders.
   Baltimore's auxiliary Bishop John Ricard said in an interview,
``It is the absolute intent of the black bishops to seek some type
of reconciliation with Father Stallings. In no way do we want to cut
off dialogue.''
   The bishops said they had a ``dual love and devotion'' to the
faith of the church and to their black cultural heritage, but unlike
Stallings, they did not feel the two were in conflict.
   Stallings' suspension means he may not celebrate mass or
administer any Roman Catholic sacraments.
   An estimated 1,000 people have signed up for the Imani Temple,
and Stallings has received more than $39,000 in church offerings in
just two weeks.
   Stallings has said he wants to see establishment of an
African-American rite within the Catholic church. Earlier this week,
he said he would present a reconciliation plan to the archdiocese of
Washington, but only on his terms.
   Signing the statement were Ricard and Archbishop Eugene Marino of
Atlanta, Bishop Joseph Howze of Biloxi, Miss.; and auxiliary bishops
Harold Perry of New Orleans, Joseph Francis of Newark, James Lyke of
Cleveland, Emerson Moore of New York, Moses Anderson of Detroit,
Wilton Gregory of Chicago, J. Terry Steib of St. Louis, Carl Fisher
of Los Angeles, Curtis Guillory of Galveston-Houston, and Leonard
Olivier of Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Georgiemania 2ndLd-Writethru a0535 07-13 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georgiemania, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0535,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Drew Crowds but Failed to Set Hearts Aflutter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS pvs 13th graf bgng, During a, to CORRECT von Weizsaecker's
name.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Somewhere in this Central European
capital there is a tiny elderly woman who will forever treasure
President Bush's visit.
   She bears his raincoat as a souvenir, given to her by the
president after he spoke Tuesday in a driving rainstorm in Kossuth
Square. (The raincoat, it turned out, belonged to a Secret Service
agent accompanying Bush.)
   But among the vast populace of Hungary and Poland, there was
little evidence that the people have fallen victim to Georgiemania
to rival the emotion Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev stirred
in his own recent travels to Western Europe.
   Still, Bush was a hit, especially in Gdansk, the Baltic seaport
city that gave birth to the Polish trade union movement Solidarity.
Roughly 25,000 people swarmed around the monument to slain workers
to cheer Bush with chants of ``Bush, Bush, Bush, Bush!'' They sang
the Solidarity anthem and flashed the Solidarity ``V'' for victory
salute beneath the 80-foot-high monument at the shipyard gates.
   Shouts of ``Stay with us, stay with us!'' rang out after Bush
said that if he were a young man he would want to stay to
participate in Poland's transformation to a free-market economy. But
the prediction of Steve Studdert, a White House advance man, that
tens of thousands would turn out for Bush in Warsaw did not
materialize.
   Nor was there an immense turnout in Hungary even though Bush was
the first American president to visit the country _ and he brought
promises of U.S. aid to Budapest, as he had to Warsaw.
   Gorbachev, by contrast, made a tremendous political impact on
both West Germany and France, though the turnout in Paris, at least,
was widely considered to be a disappointment.
   The reason may be the Soviet leader represented a historic change
in Moscow's approach to the East-West problem.
   Bush, on the other hand, also promoted a relaxation of tensions,
but he is a relatively colorless American leader who does not
approach Gorbachev's charisma.
   Besides, for policy reasons, Bush forswore any intended rivalry
with Gorbachev.
   ``We're not trying to make things more difficult for him,'' the
president said before setting out for Europe. ``Just as when he goes
to France and Germany I don't think he's trying to make things more
difficult for the United States.''
   Gorbachev was welcomed last month in Bonn by large crowds
shouting ``Gorby, Gorby'' everywhere he went. He constantly outranks
all Western leaders in popularity polls in West Germany.
   During a ceremony at the official residence of West German
President Richard von Weizsaecker, the Soviet leader kissed a high
school girl. The next day, the mass-circulation Bild newspaper ran
the picture on the front page with a banner headline: ``A kiss for
Annette, a kiss for Germany.''
   In Paris, though, Gorbachev's public appearance stirred less of a
public response.
   ``French crowds simply tend to be less demonstrative than German
ones,'' said Dominique Moisi of the French Institute of
International Relations.
   But Gorbachev's political impact was unquestioned.
   French President Francois Mitterrand, in a rare gesture, invited
Gorbachev and his wife to dinner at their apartment in the Latin
Quarter.
   This may have been the first time a Soviet leader was invited to
dine at the home of a Western leader, and it signaled how important
Gorbachev's visit was taken by the French. And yet, Gorbachev was
supposed to work the crowd at the Place de la Bastille, but shook
only a few hands and did not stay long.
   On the other hand, in Kossuth Square, about 2,000 drenched
Hungarians withstood a driving rain to see Bush on Tuesday.
   The president appeared to be touched by their tribute. He tore up
his speech and said he wanted to ``just speak from the heart.''
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, clearly not an impartial
observer, was asked to compare Bush's travels with Gorbachev's at a
news conference Wednesday.
   He said he thought the president's crowds were ``pretty good _
pretty terrific, as a matter of fact, in Poland, and particularly in
Gdansk.''
   But Baker urged reporters to keep in mind the president's
objective _ active engagement with Poland and Hungary as they pursue
fundamental reform efforts.
   ``And that's why we're here,'' Baker said, ``not out of any idea
that we need to compete with General Secretary Gorbachev.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
