<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ShingleBan     07-13 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shingle Ban,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Bans Wood Shake Shingles For New Construction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council voted to ban roofs made of
wood shingles to protect buildings from fire, despite objections
from industry officials who said the shingles are safe.
   The proposal, approved 11-1 Wednesday, would apply to new
buildings and to roofs requiring repairs to 10 percent or more of
their surfaces. The measure goes to Mayor Tom Bradley, who has taken
no position.
   If the proposed ordinance is signed into law and survives a
possible legal challenge, Los Angeles would become the first major
American city to ban wood shake shingles.
   The measure was strongly opposed by the cedar-shingle industry,
which counts on the Los Angeles area for three-quarters of its $50
million in annual sales of shingles treated with fire-retardant
chemicals.
   At stake are hundreds of jobs and millions of investment dollars
in the Pacific Northwest and Canada, where most of the lumber for
the shingles is harvested and processed.
   The industry contends that the treated shingles are as safe as
those made of asphalt or Fiberglas.
   But city fire officials said the treated shingles lose their
effectiveness with time. ``There is not one shred of doubt in my
mind,'' City Fire Marshall Craig Drummond told the council.
   If Bradley approves the ban, the industry will take the matter to
court, said Michael M. Westfall, president of the Cedar Shake and
Shingle Bureau.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
