<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0919EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BaySwim     07-13 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bay Swim,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight-year-old Swims the Golden Gate Waters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old girl has become the youngest
person on record to swim the rough, icy waters of the Golden Gate,
the mile-wide passage where the Pacific Ocean meets San Francisco
Bay.
   ``It was scary and the waves were high and I wanted to give up
100 yards from the finish,'' Emma Macchiarini-Mankin said Wednesday
at a news conference after the 68-minute swim.
   Hypothermia and the tortuous, 60-degree current were the biggest
risks for the 5-foot, 75-pound, freckle-faced swimmer, who avoided
an outgoing Navy ship during the swim from Fort Point to the
seaweed-covered rocks at Lime Point. The distance is one mile and 52
feet.
   Emma was accompanied on the swim by her distance coach and
father, Danny Macchiarini. Macchiarini, who made his 12th crossing
of the strait, introduced Emma to pool swimming at 10 months and
dunked her in the bay when she was 5.
   Asked why she wanted to swim from San Francisco to Marin County,
she said, ``Because I don't know how to drive a car there.'' She
then added, ``I want to be famous and have all the money.''
   She alternated strokes _ seven minutes freestyle, seven
breaststroke and seven on her back, spouting seawater. Her father,
who has coached her in thrice-weekly swims, said her speed improved
dramatically in the past week.
   The fourth-grader, who wore a green, red and purple suit with a
pink bow in the back, held both arms up like a winning boxer as she
emerged from the water.
   Before Emma, the youngest swimmer was Mike Lynch, who was 12 in
1964 when he made it in 54 minutes and 30 seconds.
   Emma said she feared sharks during the swim, although her father
insisted there were none in the bay.
   ``I made a deal with the sharks,'' she said. ``I wouldn't eat
them if they wouldn't eat me.''
</TEXT>
