<FIRST>r a PM-MassSlaying     07-13 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mass Slaying,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Recommends Death For Man Convicted In Oakland Mass Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of a shooting rampage that
killed a former girlfriend, three of her relatives and two others
should receive the death penalty, a jury recommended.
   Sentencing was set for July 26 for David ``Moochie'' Welch, 31,
after the jury issued its recommendation Wednesday.
   The same jury on June 19 convicted Welch of six counts of murder
stemming from the Dec. 6, 1986, rampage, described as Oakland's
worst mass killing.
   Welch and his girlfriend burst into the home of Dellane Mabrey,
17, his former girlfriend, and went from room to room shooting
occupants, some of whom were asleep. Welch had a long-running feud
with the woman's family.
   Ms. Mabrey died, along with two of her brothers, Sean, 21, and
Darnell, 20; her 2-year-old daughter, Valencia Morgan, 2; and two
houseguests, Kathy Walker, 34, and her 4-year-old son, Dwayne
Miller. Two other people, including Ms. Mabrey's 3-month-old son,
were wounded.
   Welch, 31, showed no emotion as the verdict was read. However,
after the jury had been dismissed, he said he was ``relieved for the
victims' families and for mine that this ordeal has finally come to
rest.''
   Throughout the proceedings, Welch had been combative with his
attorneys and the judge.
   Prosecutor James Anderson told the jury before sentencing that
Welch was a ``miserable, miserable, violent thug,'' and said he was
elated about the jury's verdict.
   ``The jury saw the gravity of his offenses, his lifestyle and his
violent conduct in prison and did what it had to do,'' Anderson
said. The prosecutor had produced evidence that Welch assaulted
guards and his wife while he was an inmate at San Quentin on
previous convictions.
   Spencer Strellis, one of Welch's two attorneys, said defense
witnesses included a psychologist and a psychiatrist who testified
that Welch had a history of mental illness.
   ``In our case, we asked, `Do you execute a sick man?''' Strellis
said. ``The jury answered, `yes.'''
   Rita Lewis, Welch's girlfriend who participated in the attack,
pleaded guilty to six counts of first-degree murder and was
sentenced in December 1987 to 51 years to life in prison.
</TEXT>
