<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     07-13 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Aquits Soldiers In Philippine Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court today acquitted 23
soldiers of massacring 17 civilians. Another tribunal dismissed
charges against a prominent officer accused of taking part in a
bloody coup attempt in 1987.
   A six-member court-martial ruled unanimously that there was
insufficient evidence to convict the 23 members of the army's 14th
battalion of killing the civilians in the town of Lupao on Feb. 10,
1987.
   ``I am very happy because that means I can go back to the
field,'' said Sgt. Nestor Garcia, one of the defendants. A survivor,
Ricardo Carnate, had testified he saw Garcia stab his father to
death during the slayings.
   In a separate case, another court dismissed charges against air
force Lt. Col. Eduardo ``Red'' Kapunan. He had been accused of
organizing cadets at the Philippine Military Academy to join the
Aug. 28, 1987 attempt to overthrow President Corazon Aquino in which
53 people were killed and hundreds wounded.
   Kapunan was an associate of the coup leader, former Lt. Col.
Gregorio ``Gringo'' Honasan, and a prominent member of a clique of
officers loyal to Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, the former defense
minister. Kapunan was placed under house arrest in September.
Honasan remains at large.
   In the Lupao case, human rights groups and the military
prosecutors expressed surprise over the verdict because witnesses
had identified that several of the accused as having taken part in
the killings.
   Three of the defendants also were acquitted of charges they stole
$500 from the survivors in the village, 85 miles north of Manila.
   Survivors told officials that troops dragged villagers from their
homes and shot them with semi-automatic weapons after their
lieutenant was shot and killed by communist New People's Army
guerrillas.
   Mrs. Aquino visited the village soon after the slayings and
promised justice to the villagers. Human rights organizations cited
the Lupao killings as an example of civil liberties abuses under the
Aquino administration.
   Filipino and international groups also had criticized the
military because no one had been punished in the incident.
</TEXT>
