<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Khomeini 1stLd-Writethru a0545 07-13 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Khomeini, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millions Converge On Cemetery To Mark End of 40-Day Mourning</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 13-14, ``Iran's...Iraq.'' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with more on insurance, DELETES `pro-Western' as incorrect. Pickup last,
``The grave...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranians beating their heads and chests in
grief flocked to Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's gold-domed tomb today
to mark the end of 40 days of mourning for the founder of the
Islamic Republic.
   The official media, including Tehran Radio and the Islamic
Republic News Agency, said millions of people braved scorching heat
and turned out for the ceremony at the Baheshte Zahra cemetery.
   IRNA said 20,000 people ``suffered heart problems,'' were
injured, or simply collapsed as temperatures soared to 104. Some
were reported in serious condition even after treatment at makeshift
medical facilities set up along roads leading to the cemetery, said
the agency, monitored in Nicosia.
   The crowds began gathering at the cemetery at 5 a.m., more than
13 hours before a religious ceremony at the grave.
   Broadcasting live from the graveyard 10 miles south of the
capital, Tehran Television showed mourners being carried over the
crowds, apparently after fainting. Firefighters sprayed the crowd
with water.
   Mourners beat their heads and chests in a traditional Shiite
Moslem expression of grief, stopping occasionally to wipe sweat away
with handkerchiefs or the sleeves of their shirts.
   Loudspeakers along the roads and at the cemetery blared recitings
from the Koran, Islam's holy book.
   Relief facilities included a central clinic with 1,000
physicians, nurses and relief workers on duty round the clock. Fifty
makeshift medical centers and four rest houses also were set up to
offer services to motorists and pedestrians, IRNA said.
   It said dozens of stands offering food and refreshments dotted
highways and streets connecting Tehran with other cities and
provinces.
   The government provided about 600 vehicles to ferry mourners to
the cemetery, but many ended up walking as human waves blocked the
streets.
   Khomeini died June 3 at age 86.
   At least eight people were killed and thousands collapsed from
exhaustion in the mayhem of his funeral June 6 when millions packed
Tehran's streets.
   A government insurance program covered all those who gathered at
the tomb today, the end of the period of mourning in the Shiite
Moslem faith.
   Iran's state-run insurance companies announced that $13,500 will
be paid to the family of anyone who dies or is seriously injured
during the ceremony today. Medical expenses of up to $2,000 will
also be paid.
   Khomeini, who toppled 2,500 years of monarchy, was buried in a
dusty plot alongside thousands of followers killed in the 1979
revolution and thousands who died later in the war with Iraq.
   The grave has become a shrine, with hundreds of thousands of
Iranians gathering around it each day.
</TEXT>
