<FIRST>u w AM-US-HonduranAttack     07-13 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Honduran Attack,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Soldiers Injured in Honduran Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven U.S. Army soldiers were wounded early
today when an ``explosive device'' was thrown at them as they were
walking through a village in northern Honduras, the Pentagon said.
   The condition of the soldiers was not immediately available, but
they are being treated in a local hospital, said a Defense
Department spokeswoman, Army Maj. Kathy Wood.
   She said said nine soldiers were involved in the incident, but
only seven were injured. She said the military personnel apparently
were off duty and were walking through the village at the time of
the attack.
   ``They were just walking down the street in La Cieba,'' the
spokeswoman said. ``Some sort of explosive device was thrown at
them.''
   She said she had no specific information about the identities of
the personnel, their specific units, rank or sex.
   ``The facts are very sketchy,'' she said.
   The soldiers are based at Sotocano Air Base, near Comayanga in
central Honduras, where the United States has temporary facilities.
   U.S. personnel are currently involved in a road-building exercise
near La Cieba, a northern coastal town, Maj. Wood said, but she was
not certain whether the wounded soldiers were assigned to that task.
   The spokeswoman said various reports have come in about the
incident, and that one said the explosion occurred at 2:30 a.m. EDT.
</TEXT>
