<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     07-13 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Death Reported in Disputed Soviet Region</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Armenian motorist was shot to death in a
disputed enclave of Azerbaijan, and a government official said he
was probably a victim of the ethnic unrest that has plagued the
region since early last year.
   An Interior Ministry spokesman, Alexander Timokhin, said the
Armenian's body was found Wednesday on the road to Stepanakert, the
main city in the enclave, Nagorno-Karabakh. The body of Artur
Toniyan was left by his car near two villages populated by
Azerbaijanis, Timokhin said in a telephone interview.
   The official said the attack was probably ethnically motivated.
   Tensions between Armenians, who are in a majority in
Nagorno-Karabakh, and Azerbaijanis have run high since February 1988
because of a territorial dispute over the tiny, fertile region 1,200
miles south of Moscow.
   Armenians, who are predominantly Christian, claim they are
persecuted by Azerbaijanis, who are mostly Moslem, and want
Nagorno-Karabakh to be placed under the control of the nearby
republic of Armenia.
   Two Azerbaijanis were killed and a third was seriously wounded on
Tuesday near the village of Kirkidzhan. Reports conflicted about the
circumstances, with some saying the men were ambushed by Armenians
and others claiming they died in a car accident or killed each other
in a dispute.
   A 1 a.m.-5 a.m. curfew remained in force in Nagorno-Karabakh, a
two-month-old strike was keeping most businesses closed, and armored
personnel carriers patrolled the streets of Stepanakert.
</TEXT>
