<HEAD>Jailed Surgeon Released From Punitive Custody</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts dropped word ``cell'' in graf 3, A search. Makes second
reference ``Morgan'' throughout.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the District of Columbia Jail
has overturned a decision that placed jailed plastic surgeon
Elizabeth Morgan in punitive confinement for possessing contraband
jewelry and perfume.
   Morgan, who has been held for 23 months on contempt charges for
failing to divulge the whereabouts of her 7-year-old daughter in a
child custody case, was sentenced to special confinement by a
disciplinary review board on Monday.
   A search of Morgan's cell uncovered earrings, a gold chain and
perfume that authorities said were not authorized.
   Jail director David Roach reversed the review board's ruling
Wednesday. ``The review panel had made some procedural errors'' in
reaching the decision, so Roach granted Morgan's appeal that she be
released from punishment that kept her in her cell 23 hours a day,
said corrections department spokeswoman Pat Wheeler.
   The spokeswoman did not specify what errors had been made but
said Morgan was being returned to the jail's general female inmate
population.
