<FIRST>u i PM-Azores-Rescue     07-13 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Azores-Rescue,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Helps Save Canadian From Burning Yacht</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Air Force officers helped rescue a
Canadian who was severely burned when a stove exploded and a fire
broke out aboard his yacht in the Atlantic Ocean, officials said
today.
   The sailor, Albert Edward Wilson of Ontario, Canada, was taken
from the burning 30-foot yacht Wednesday night, Portuguese air force
officials said. Wilson was the only person aboard the vessel.
   The officials said the sailor's distress call was heard at a U.S.
Air Force base in Lajes, on the Azores island of Terceira, and a
U.S. reconnaissance plane located the yacht while vessels rushed to
the scene.
   Wilson was saved about 130 miles west of the Azores, mid-Atlantic
islands owned by Portugal, the officials in the Azorian city of
Ponta Delgada said.
   Lorne Bawers, a Canadian ham operator in Charlottetown, Prince
Edward Island, said he was in contact with Wilson all night and that
the sailor was coherent and cheerful despite his ordeal.
   He said Wilson told him he was trying to circumnavigate the
Atlantic.
   Portuguese officials said Wilson was very badly burned. Reports
overheard by a ham radio reporter in Maine said Wilson was near
death after sustaining burns on his hands, arms, legs and stomach.
   Wilson was taken aboard a merchant ship identified as the
Charlotte Lake, they said, adding they did not know the nationality
of the ship.
</TEXT>
