<SECOND>PM-Shooting Spree, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0550,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Shoot Nine in Crowded Street, Smash Into Roadblock</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with police now saying nine wounded, sted
11, ADDS identification of two suspects, updates condition of wounded with
some released from hospital.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three gunmen shot nine people on a crowded
street before leading police on a 12-mile chase that ended when
their vehicle smashed into patrol cars at a roadblock, police said
today.
   Police had no motive for the Wednesday night shootings, which
witnesses said appeared to be indiscriminate.
   ``All of a sudden I saw these dudes coming down the middle of the
street, shooting up in the air,'' said one witness, Ernie Dumas.
``They were saying things like `You think you're bad.'''
   Stamford police Lt. Joseph Falzetti said today that nine people
were wounded.
   ``None of the injuries are life threatening although some are
more serious than others,'' Stamford Deputy Police Chief John
Perrotta said.
   After firing at the people, the gunmen led police on a
circuitous, 60-mph car chase that ended in New Canaan when their car
crashed into two police cruisers and a stone wall, said New Canaan
Police Capt. Christopher Lynch.
   One of the suspects was listed in critical condition at St.
Joseph Medical Center in Stamford, a hospital official said. The
other two suspects are in serious condition.
   Charges were pending against the men, Perrotta said. Two were
identified as James McGraw, 18, and Damian Jackson, 21, both of New
York City. The third was not identified.
   Falzetti said five of the victims were taken to St. Joseph's;
four others were taken to Stamford Hospital. Each hospital treated
and released one person. The others remained hospitalized today in
serious conditon.
</TEXT>
