<FIRST>u a PM-WanderingPlane 2ndLd-Writethru a0567 07-13 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0567,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Plane With Apparently Unconscious Pilot Wings Southward Over Atlantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with further details on planned rescue effort,
recasts. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small aircraft, its pilot apparently unconscious
or dead, flew southward over the Atlantic Ocean off the East Coast
this morning and was rapidly running out of gas, officials said.
   Military jets and a cargo plane with a parachute rescue team
aboard chased the twin-engine Cessna 210 as it flew down the coast.
   The unidentified pilot reported to air traffic controllers at
8:30 a.m. that he was having chest pains and difficulty breathing.
   ``There has been nothing more from the pilot,'' said Fred Farrar,
a Federal Aviation Administration spokesman in Washington.
   Pilots who tracked the plane later said he appeared to be slumped
over the controls. There was no one else visible in the plane,
officials said.
   Officials gave conflicting reports on how much fuel the plane,
apparently on autopilot, had left at midmorning and on its location.
Farrar said that at 10 a.m. the plane was about 250 miles northeast
of Brunswick, Ga.
   Farrar said the plane would run out of gas about 11:30 a.m.,
while Lt. Cmdr. Jeff Karonis of the Coast Guard said the pilot
indicated at 8:30 a.m. that he had four hours of fuel left.
   Steve Sapp, Coast Guard spokesman in Miami, said an Air Force
C-130 with a parachute rescue team aboard and a Coast Guard C-130
plane were following the plane down the coast. If it runs out of
fuel at 11:30 a.m., he said, it would be about 250 miles east of
Cape Canaveral.
   ``There's apparently nothing more we can do until it splashes
down,'' Sapp said. ``When it does, the pararescue people will jump
out of the plane.''
   A helicopter would likely be sent from the Coast Guard's Cape
Canaveral station, he said.
   The Cessna aircraft took off from Washington National Airport at
about 6:30 a.m. Its flight plan indicated it was headed for Rocky
Mount, N.C., Farrar said.
   After its distress call, it was intercepted by two Marine Corps
F-A-18 Hornets when it entered Norfolk Naval Station airspace at
8:45 a.m., said Lt. Cmdr. Mike John, a Navy spokesman.
   The pilots of the intercepting planes saw the pilot slumped over
the controls, John said. The Marine fliers were unable to establish
voice contact with the Cessna pilot, he said.
   Karonis said the plane was flying steadily at 10,000 feet. He
said its heading varied from southeast to southwest ``as it gets
pushed about by the wind.''
</TEXT>
