<FIRST>r w PM-Mexico-American     07-13 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-American,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body Identified As That of AID Employee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A body that ashed ashore near a southern
Mexican village six weeks ago has been tentatively identified as
that of an employee of the U.S. foreign aid agency who had been on a
hiking trip, U.S. officials said today.
   The officials said dental records appeared to confirm that the
victim was Frank Fairchild, 43, who went to Guatemala on a hiking
trip alone in May and crossed into Mexico on June 1.
   The cause of death has not been established. The remains have
been sent to Mexico City for further examination, said the
officials, who insisted on anonymity.
   Fairchild's body washed ashore at Puerto Arista, in the Mexican
state of Chiapas, on June 5 and was buried by Mexican authorities.
There was no identification on the body.
   The Mexican officials informed the State Department about the
incident after U.S. officials became concerned about Fairchild's
disappearance and began making inquiries about his whereabouts in
late June.
   Fairchild joined the Agency for International Development in 1979
and spent his first seven years with AID in Guatemala. He was
preparing for reassignment to Washington this summer after a
two-year tour of duty in Pakistan.
   Fairchild was born in Los Angeles and was raised in High Point,
N.C.
