<SECOND>PM-PTL Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0508,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Testify Taggarts Said Their Wealth Was Inherited</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with today's testimony; Picks up
4th graf, `Federal prosecutors ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former furniture salesman testified
today that former PTL executives David and James Taggart used a PTL
credit card to pay off a $15,000 debt for furniture that was
delivered to their New York apartment.
   Preston Mitchell, who worked at the Mecklenburg Design Center in
Charlotte in 1985, said the Taggarts purchased more than $20,000
worth of furniture for their $640,000 one-bedroom apartment in Trump
Tower. Mitchell said he went to New York to set up the sofas,
tables, custom area rug and chairs.
   The Taggarts are charged with evading $487,000 in federal income
taxes from 1984 to 1987.
   Mitchell said David Taggart used a credit card issue to PTL to
pay off the $15,350 balance on the purchase. The credit card receipt
introduced by Justice Department prosecutor David Brown carried a
hand-written notation that the furniture was purchased for the
Heritage Grand Hotel.
   The hotel is on the grounds of Heritage USA, the PTL Christian
theme park south of Charlotte.
   Brown also entered documents showing David Taggart had used his
personal credit card to purchase $6,200 in bedroom furniture for the
Taggarts' home in Charlotte.
   A handwritten note on that charge slip indicated the canopy bed,
mattress and armoire were to be used in the presidential suite at
the Heritage Grand Hotel, the suite used by PTL founder Jim Bakker.
   On Wednesday, friends of the Taggarts testified that the two told
friends their wealth came from a family inheritance.
   ``They told me about growing up in Detroit, that they got an
inheritance from their grandfather,'' Penny Hollenbeck, who became
friends with David and James Taggart when they worked together at
PTL in the early 1980s, testified for the prosecution Wednesday.
   Federal prosecutors say the brothers diverted $1.1 million of
ministry funds to their personal use by taking cash advances on PTL
credit cards and using blank ministry checks to pay the credit card
bills. They have argued that the Taggarts lied even to their closest
friends about the source of their wealth to conceal their actions.
   Eugene Shelton IV, another former PTL aide and friend of the
Taggarts, said he asked David Taggart about his money while the two
were on a trip to Florida in 1985.
   ``I believe I was blunt, I came out and asked,'' Shelton said.
``He told me he had received a trust fund from family ... I believe
from his parents. It was $6 million _ $3 million each.''
   Last week, testimony from the Taggarts' father, Henry Taggart,
established that the claims of family wealth recalled by their PTL
co-workers were false.
   Two women who described themselves as longtime friends of the
Taggarts described being taken on expensive trips to California,
Florida and London.
   Lucinda McLellan and Darlene Peterson said the trips included
$3,000 hotel bills, dinners costing $600 each and shopping sprees
that cost several thousand dollars.
   In other testimony, a representative from a New York City fur
shop said the Taggarts spent about $35,000 on mink coats and other
furs for themselves at her store. And a salesman for a New York shoe
store said the Taggarts spent nearly $100,000 from 1982-86 on shoes
for themselves.
   Television evangelist Rex Humbard, a former PTL board member,
testified that he keeps tight spending controls at his ministry in
Boca Raton, Fla.
   ``Nobody in our organization is authorized to spend more than
$10,000 outside the budget without authorization from the board of
directors.''
   If convicted on the tax evasion charges, the Taggarts each could
be sentenced to 25 years in prison and face fines totaling about $1
million.
</TEXT>
