<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-ArmsControl     07-13 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Arms Control,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Welcome U.S. Bid to Speed Up Conventional Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union today welcomed a U.S. effort to
speed up negotiations to reduce conventional forces in Europe and
said a deal might be possible within six months.
   ``We have no intention of delaying this important matter of
reducing the level of military confrontation,'' said the Foreign
Ministry spokesman, Gennady Gerasimov. But he said it might be hard
to meet a Bush administration proposal to make the cuts by 1992.
   President Bush proposed at a NATO summit May 29 that the United
States and Soviet Union reduce their troop levels to 275,000 each in
central Europe.
   According to NATO, that would mean a reduction of 30,000 U.S.
troops from Europe, and a cut by the Soviet Union of more than 10
times that, or 325,000 troops.
   Gerasimov said that in general the NATO ideas ``are viewed by us
as serious and constructive proposals, meeting our own proposals
halfway.''
   The Soviet spokesman noted that President Bush ``also proposed to
conclude an agreement on conventional forces during the next six to
12 months and aim to comply with this agreement in 1991-92.
   ``The Vienna talks, given a constructive approach, can arrive at
specific agreements by next year. We will do everything to reach
those agreements within six months.
   ``Of course, to reduce substantial numbers of personnel and
material by 1992 is not an easy matter. We may suppose that the
schedule proposed is an unusual one for NATO countries and has been
created mostly by political considerations,'' he said.
   Gerasimov did not comment on a proposal by Secretary of State
James A. Baker III to limit each side to a ceiling of 5,700 combat
aircraft, of which 1,900 would be helicopters.
   The official Tass news agency, however, said the NATO proposal
contained some ``disturbing points,'' especially the inclusion of
combat aircraft able to carry out both offensive and defensive
missions.
   ``It is precisely strike aircraft of frontline (tactical)
aviation that constitute an important component of surprise attack
capability. NATO has a considerable advantage in this area,'' Tass
commentator Vladimir Chernyshev said.
   Gerasimov also noted that Soviet and U.S. warships would pay
reciprocal visits this summer in a program of expanding military
cooperation.
   From July 21-25, the cruiser Usinov will be among the Soviet
warships visiting visit Norfolk, Va., home of the U.S. Atlantic
Fleet.
   From Aug. 4-6, U.S. Navy ships will return the visit by stopping
at Sevastapol on the Black Sea.
   The visits will be the first of their kind in 14 years, said
Gerasimov.
</TEXT>
