<HEAD>Indiana High Court Rules Teen-age Murderer Cannot Be Executed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with attorney's reaction, move
up reference to pope's appeal, CORRECTS that he made appeal in 1987, sted
1988; Picks up 10th graf, `Orr and ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paula R. Cooper, convicted of a murder
committed when she was 15, cannot be executed, the Indiana Supreme
Court ruled today.
   The court unanimously upheld Cooper's conviction in the 1985
stabbing death of an elderly Bible teacher but said she should be
sentenced to 60 years in prison.
   Cooper's case has drawn international attention, and in 1987 Pope
John Paul II appealed for mercy on her behalf.
   The court based its decision on a 1987 change in Indiana law
raising the minimum age for a death penalty defendant from 10 to 16
and on a 1988 U.S. Supreme Court decision barring executions of
juveniles under 16 at the time of the crime.
   But the court said although the law was compelling, ``this is a
difficult conclusion to reach because of the gruesome nature of
Cooper's acts.''
   ``We won! I'm elated, relieved,'' said Cooper's attorney, William
Touchette. ``I'm very happy for Paula. I'm just so relieved that
this is over. It was not an easy case.''
   Cooper pleaded guilty to the stabbing death of Ruth E. Pelke, 78,
a retired Bible teacher in Gary. According to court records, Pelke
was stabbed 33 times after Cooper and three friends broke into her
home to get money and jewelry.
   The three other young women received prison terms ranging from 25
to 60 years for their roles in the crime.
   Cooper, now 18, is an inmate at the Indiana Women's Prison in
Indianapolis.
   Roman Catholics and some European leftist groups have adopted
Cooper as the figurehead of their campaign against capital
punishment. Amnesty International and the American Civil Liberties
Union have also pleaded on her behalf.
   In March an Italian group presented a petition with 1 million
signatures to United Nations officials urging clemency for Cooper,
and in 1987 the pope wrote to then-Gov. Robert D. Orr to ask for
mercy for the young woman.
   Orr and current Gov. Evan Bayh have said they didn't want to
intervene in the Cooper case until the appeal was resolved.
   In today's opinion, the Supreme Court concluded that executing
Cooper would be unfair because she would be the only person under 16
ever executed in the state.
   The General Assembly, after much debate in 1987, changed the
minimum age for a death penalty defendant but made it clear that
Cooper wasn't to be affected by the change. But the court said
exempting Cooper from the change is inappropriate.
   ``Now that Indiana law establishes 16 as the minimum age for the
imposition of the death penalty, Paula Cooper would be both the
first and last person ever to be executed in Indiana for a crime
committed at the age of 15,'' Chief Justice Randall T. Shepard wrote
for the court.
   ``This makes her sentence unique and disproportionate to any
other sentence for the same crime,'' Shepard wrote.
   The state court also said that last year's divided U.S. Supreme
Court ruling on an Oklahoma case signals that four justices believe
``it is cruel and unusual punishment to execute a juvenile convicted
of a murder committed before the age of 16, and one justice believes
it is unconstitutional to executive a juvenile unless the death
penalty itself identifies a minimum age for the death penalty.''
   While sparing Cooper from the electric chair, the Supreme Court
said the circumstances surrounding her crime ``clearly support the
next most severe penalty under the statute, namely, the maximum
sentence of imprisonment.''
   Cooper will be eligible to apply for parole after serving half of
the 60-year sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
