<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st item with cause and place of death; No separates moved
for the PMs cycle.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Tommy Tucker</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tommy Tucker, a big band leader of the
1940s, died of heart failure in a hospital Tuesday. He was 86.
   Tucker led his traveling dance band, Tommy Tucker and his
Orchestra, in worldwide appearances from 1936-1958.
   Tucker, who played the piano, trumpet and trombone, was familiar
to radio fans who tuned into the shows ``Sing for Your Supper with
Tommy Tucker,'' ``Thirty Minutes in Hollywood'' and ``Hit Parade.''
And he made numerous television appearances on ``The Kate Smith
Show,'' ``Cavalcade of Bands,'' ``Arthur Murray House Party'' and
``Strike It Rich.''
   Tucker recorded the hits ``I Don't Want to Set the World on
Fire,'' ``The Man That Comes Around,'' and an original theme song,
``I Love You.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Harry Lyons</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KONA, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cartoonist and columnist Harry Lyons, who
worked for 20 years at The Honolulu Advertiser, died Wednesday at
home. He was 59.
   Lyons became a cartoonist for the Honolulu newspaper in 1959. He
was president of the Honolulu Press Club for three terms and won the
Grenville Clark Editorial Award in the field of political cartoons
three times.
   In 1973, he branched into sportswriting with a weekly column
called ``Lyons Through His Teeth.''
   He moved to Kona in 1979, and began writing a a thrice-weekly
column for West Hawaii Today called ``Lyons on the Loose.''
   Six years ago he began publishing a monthly news, feature and
humor magazine called ``Harry Lyons' Kona Coast.''
   He is survived by three children, Jennifer, Stacy and Steven.
</TEXT>
