<FIRST>u i PM-Bush-Briefing 1stLd-Writethru a0531 07-13 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Briefing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0531,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Dismisses Reports Soviets Unable to Meet NATO Target</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Paris, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs after 4th graf bgng, `Experience shows,' to
UPDATE with Gerasimov comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD AIR FORCE ONE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today dismissed
reports that Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is unable to meet
a NATO target date for the Soviet Union to reduce its conventional
military forces.
   ``The idea that some Soviet spokesman yesterday said they can't
meet these timetables _ I don't want to believe that that's Mr.
Gorbachev speaking,'' the president said in an impromptu news
conference as Air Force One flew to Paris from a two-night stop in
Budapest, Hungary, the second leg of a 10-day trip.
   Lt. Gen. Viktor Starodubov, chief of the disarmament branch of
the Communist Party's policy-making central committee, said Tuesday
that Moscow would not be able to meet the timetable.
   The Soviet official said that although Gorbachev, like the
Western nations, is seeking an early agreement, ``there are
realities which cannot be suppressed.''
   ``Experience shows that even when the principal elements are
resolved, we need a considerably longer period for solving the
details of the document,'' Starodubov said.
   In Moscow today, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady
Gerasimov provided a more tempered response, saying his country
welcomed a U.S. effort to speed up negotiations to reduce
conventional forces and indicated that a deal might be possible
within six months.
   ``We have no intention of delaying this important matter of
reducing the level of military confrontation,'' said Gerasimov who
was questioned about the NATO proposal submitted today.
   But the Soviet official said reductions in ``substantial numbers
of personnel and material by 1992 is not an easy matter. We may
suppose that the chedule proposed is an unusual one for NATO
countries and has been created mostly be political considerations.''
   Gerasimov did not comment on Starodubov's remarks Tuesday.
   The NATO proposal calls for military cutbacks that would fix the
same ceiling of 275,000 troops in Europe for each superpower.
According to NATO statistics, that would require the United States
to remove 30,000 troops from Europe while the Soviets would have to
pull out more than 10 times that, or 325,000.
   The proposal, which also includes deep cuts in armaments, called
for reaching agreement in six months to a year, and for reductions
to be carried out by 1992 or 1993.
   The NATO members, seeking an early agreement at talks in Vienna
on conventional disarmament, submitted a proposal today that
specifies the types of combat aircraft it wants covered by an arms
accord.
   Bush told reporters that he is convinced that ``Gorbachev knows
that we're serious. Indeed we have an opportunity now to encourage
him to move along faster on conventional force reduction.''
   The president also said his journey to Poland and Hungary had
been ``watched by the people of other Eastern European countries and
hopefully given encouragement to those who want to go the path of
reform, political change, economic change.''
   On the Middle East, Bush said the United States will not overhaul
its policy on the Middle East in response to political turmoil in
Israel, a nation he said is having ``great difficulties.''
   Bush emphasized that Israel should go forward with elections
among Palestinians in the occupied territories as a step toward
peace.
   Amid charges that the United States is meddling in Israeli
politics, Bush said, ``The U.S. policy is set. I am the president of
the United States. Israel is a friend and will remain a friend. but
I have to say what our policy is.
   ``I don't think there is great heartburn here but I just want to
continue to articulate what we believe,'' he said.
   The decision by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc to
harden its stand on peace negotiations has strained U.S.-Israeli
relations. In Washington, Assistant Secretary of State John H. Kelly
said hard-liners are damaging prospects for Palestinian elections in
the occupied lands.
   ``If anybody can make a case to me that the recent deliberations
in that (Likud) party will enhance the election process, then I
would say `great.' But I am afraid that other people are looking at
it and saying that what has happened does not enhance the possiblity
of elections,'' the president said.
   The Bush administration plans to send an emissary to Israel to
discuss U.S. differences with its longtime ally, but the president
said, ``there are no plans for high-level shuttle diplomacy.''
</TEXT>
