<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-FlagBurning     07-13 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Burning,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Urges Bill to Outlaw Flag Burning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee
today urged a House panel to pass quickly his bill to outlaw flag
burning, but other lawmakers said nothing short of a constitutional
amendment would suffice.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said regular legislation was the best
way ``swiftly and simply'' to overcome the Supreme Court ruling last
month that protected flag burning as a form of free speech.
   ``No matter how we cut it, a constitutional amendment is going to
take some time'' and leave a gap in the law during which flag
burning would remain legal, Biden said. A bill could take effect
almost immediately, and if it still didn't meet constitutional
muster, then an amendment could be pursued, he said.
   ``Let's heal the wound, pass the legislation and move on,'' urged
Biden.
   Biden's testimony came as the House subcommittee on
constitutional law opened a series of hearings on what to do about
the Supreme Court ruling.
   House Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., testified in favor of
the constitutional amendment supported by President Bush.
   ``We believe there is no quick legislative fix on this issue,''
said Michel, who was joined by Rep. Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss.,
chairman of the House Veterans Affairs Committee.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said he opposed a constitutional
amendment on flag burning, although he conceded most people
disagreed with him.
   ``It is that very freedom, the right to protest even when it is
offensive, that makes us different from the rest of the world,'' he
said, comparing the United States with the current repression
against protesters in China.
   Legislative efforts short of an amendment might be impossible, he
said.
   ``I'm not certain it is possible to draft a constitutionally
solid statute,'' he said.
   Subcommittee chairman Don Edwards, D-Calif., urged his colleagues
to be cautious.
   ``The flag is sturdy, flying proudly through every fierce battle
of every war and through times of social upheaval,'' he said. ``The
Constitution, however, is fragile and can be amended by the votes of
legislators caught up in the emotional whirlwinds of the moment.''
   Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner of Wisconsin, the ranking Republican on
the subcommittee, said he believed the constitutional amendment
should be quickly passed and sent to the states for ratification
because of the uncertainty that a statute would hold.
   ``If we want to heal the wounds'' of the Supreme Court decision,
``we ought to make sure the patient doesn't have a relapse,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
