<SECOND>PM-NAACP, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle: Bush Won't Seek Reversal of High Court Rights Rulings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Louis Sullivan speech; Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, `The convention....'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The health gap between white and non-white
Americans is widening, and closing the disparity will be tough,
Secretary of Health and Human Services Louis Sullivan told the NAACP
today.
   Sullivan, the third member of the Bush administration to address
the civil rights group's national convention, spoke a day after Vice
President Dan Quayle. House and Urban Development Secretary Jack
Kemp spoke on Monday.
   ``There is a large, and growing disparity in the health of our
minority population and the white population,'' Sullivan said.
   He said the average life expectancy was up to 74.8 years in 1986.
   ``But the shocking news is that, for the second year in a row,
the life expectancy for black Americans declined _ falling to 69.4
years, having been 69.5 in 1985 and 69.7 years in 1984,'' he said.
   Those figures, and the infant-mortality rate that is twice that
of whites, are ``a national tragedy,'' said Sullivan, who is black.
   Sullivan said the Bush administration favored a plan to make
Medicaid more available to infants and pregnant women and increase
funding for demonstration projects on maternity care.
   Quayle told delegates that President Bush was committed to civil
rights and black economic progress. Some listeners weren't impressed.
   ``His speech lacked any real substance,'' said Keith M. Jones,
president of the New Jersey branch of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People. ``This administration vetoed a
minimum wage bill and there is nothing kinder and gentler about
that.''
   The convention closes tonight with a speech by the Rev. Jesse
Jackson.
   In his speech to nearly 3,000 delegates Wednesday, Quayle did not
address one of the hotter convention topics _ recent U.S. Supreme
Court decisions that have been interpreted as setbacks for civil
rights.
   The high court struck down contract guarantees for minority firms
and made it tougher to prove bias in the workplace, while making it
easier for white males to contest affirmative action.
   When pressed on the issue later at a news conference, Quayle
said, ``The president does not feel that those decisions need to be
overturned to advance the cause of civil rights.''
   He said the president might reconsider if the impact of the
rulings proves discriminatory.
   Quayle was asked if the president planned to respond to the
decisions affecting civil rights with a constitutional amendment
like the one he proposed to counter a ruling that upheld
constitutional protection for burning the American flag.
   ``He feels very strongly about civil rights, he's talking about
civil rights, he's talking about decency,'' Quayle said.
   Earlier, Quayle told delegates: ``I am committed and President
Bush is committed to fostering good and better relations with the
civil rights community.''
   Bush has met with civil rights leaders in the White House and
held ceremonies honoring the Rev. Martin Luther King's legacy and
observing the 25th anniversary of the Civil Rights Act of 1964,
Quayle said.
   He cited equal opportunity programs including the Job Training
Partnership Act that he co-wrote as a senator, and educational
initiatives including establishment of a $60 million fund during the
next four years to build endowments of historically black colleges
and universities.
   ``We are the ones who are going to give a person a job,'' Quayle
said.
   On the Supreme Court's decision giving states more power to
regulate abortions, Quayle said he and the president won't take part
in state-level debates on the issue.
   But, he added, ``both of our positions are pro-life.''
   Quayle also said the administration stands behind its February
nomination of former Wayne County Executive William Lucas to head
the U.S. Justice Department's civil rights division.
   Groups including the NAACP have opposed the black Republican.
NAACP Executive Director Benjamin Hooks said Sunday that Lucas lacks
the necessary legal knowledge.
   ``We know of the opposition of the NAACP, and we have talked to
them about that, but we stand foursquare behind Bill Lucas,'' Quayle
told reporters.
</TEXT>
