<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   07-13 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the country.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July 7
   The Providence (R.I) Journal-Bulletin, on use of animals to test
cosmetics:
   Two cheers for Avon and Revlon, the cosmetics manufacturers,
which recently announced that they would no longer use animals to
test new products. Both companies have been under siege in recent
years _ indeed the whole industry felt the pressure, here and in
Europe _ to stop using animals and start employing computer models,
existing safety records, and even human volunteers, for new formulas
and toiletries.
   It is not widely understood that a significant proportion of the
animals killed or injured annually in laboratories are not used for
medical research but for product testing.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 11
   Bangor (Me.) Daily News, on Vietnamese immigrant's appointment to
U.S. Naval Academy:
   The latest wave of immigration, from Southeast Asia, is adding
cultural and ethnic diversity to this country, and it also is
re-energizing society, as eager people, aspiring and hungry to
achieve, work toward their goal of realizing a dream of freedom and
security in the United States.
   One man who personifies the spirit of the new wave is Thaison
Nguyen of Atlanta, Ga., who in 1983 successfully fled Vietnam in a
small boat, and was rescued at sea by a U.S. destroyer. Nguyen
started learning English in the eighth grade, and this month was
accepted into the U.S. Naval Academy. He had to ovecome initial
rejection because he was one-quarter inch too short (5 feet, 2
inches is the requirement); and his verbal skills were said to be
mediocre, but he was able to make a powerful, eloquent and
compelling case in his own behalf.
   Seen through the eyes of a naturalized citizen, who braved
gunfire and starvation for the opportunity to succeed, America looks
like a very different place:
   ``Somebody picked me out of the ocean, got me here, educated me,
and gave me a chance. This is my country.''
   America is fortunate to have him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 5
   Daily Record, Morristown, N.J., on changing American coins:
   If Diane Wolf of the U.S. Commission of Fine Arts has her way the
nickel, the dime, the quarter, the half dollar and the penny could
all get a facelift. The U.S. Senate has already given its go-ahead
and the House appears to be right behind, leaving only President
Bush between the venerable, 70-year-old Lincoln penny and a more
modern 20th-century version.
   Commissioner Wolf says we're the ``only western country in the
world that hasn't changed its coins in recent years. We're the only
ones that have been stuck in a rut.''
   Doesn't sound broken to us, so why spend all the time, effort
and, assuredly, tax dollars on the project?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 11
   Kennebec Journal, Augusta, Maine, on President Bush's fireworks
show:
   What a bust! They came _ some 40,000 people _ and assembled in
Kennebunkport. The purpose of the assembly, attracting visitors from
far and near, was to celebrate the most important revolution in
history and to see a fireworks display which had received advance
hype as the American equivalent of a royal command performance: the
best in the world, because this is for the president.
   Then, when all was in readiness and the expectant throng stood
waiting for its thrill of thrills, it is reported that Barbara Bush
sent word to the fireworks maestro to in effect ``start early and
make it short.'' So in less than 15 minutes the anxiously awaited
``extravaganza'' was over _ to the acute disappointment of many
onlookers.
   It's still not clear why the fireworks display was cut short.
Considerations of safety to the president were cited, though it's
hard to see why no one thought of that beforehand. The president and
Mrs. Bush were reported to have spent part of the next morning
cleaning up after the display, so perhaps housekeeping was the issue.
   But since the town of Kennebunk canceled its fireworks show in
favor of the president's, expectations were naturally high. Next
year, the Bushes ought to deliver as promised, or withdraw from the
extravaganza buisness.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
