<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--PanickedCows     07-13 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Panicked Cows,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bovine Rampage Injures 50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of cows rampaged through the
capital's crowded markets, injuring about 50 people waiting to buy
the animals for an Islamic celebration, officials said Thursday.
   Thousands of cows and goats were on sale in 20 bazaars for
sacrifice during Friday's Eid Al-Adha festival. Animal slaughter
during Eid is a traditional symbol of sacrifice.
   On Wednesday, police said, several hundred cows in the central
Fulbaria bazaar and Gabtali market on the northeastern outskirts
panicked because of noisy crowds.
   Eight people were admitted to the Dhaka Medical College Hospital
with head injuries, doctors said. The rest were treated and released.
   Eid al-Adha is the second-biggest Islamic holiday, observed 40
days after Ramadan, the month of fasting. About 90 percent of
Bangladesh's 110 million people are Moslems.
</TEXT>
