<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Pope-Vacation     07-13 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Pope-Vacation,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope on Summer Holiday in Mountains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INTROD, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Thursday began a
nine-day summer holiday in the Aosta Valley, a scenic Alpine region
near the French border.
   The pope is staying in a two-story stone villa in Introd, a
village of 480 people 10 miles from the regional capital, Aosta.
   The villa commands a view of Mont Blanc, Monte Rosa and the Gran
Paradiso and is surrounded by secluded valleys and forests of pine
and beech.
   The pope arrived Wednesday by military helicopter and was greeted
by about 80 people.
   His entourage includes personal secretary Monsignor Stanislaw
Dziwisz; a longtime friend and fellow Pole, the Rev. Tadeusz
Styczen; and Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro.
   John Paul, an avid outdoorsman, is expected to take daily walks
through the countryside.
   The past two years, he took summer holidays in the Dolomites, the
Alpine range in eastern Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
