<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--RefugeeSlaying     07-13 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Refugee Slaying,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Sentenced to Death For Murder in Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Vietnamese were sentenced to death Thursday
in the slaying of a fellow refugee during a brawl, government radio
said.
   The five had been convicted by the Hong Kong High Court in the
death of a 25-year-old Vietnamese who had been attacked with
crowbars and knives during a fight at the Sham Shui Po refugee camp.
The victim was stabbed 33 times.
   Another man who tried to save the victim was slashed several
times but escaped, the radio said.
   No one has been executed in Hong Kong since the mid-1960s.
Criminals sentenced to death usually see their sentences changed to
life in prison.
   More than 49,000 Vietnamese refugees pack several camps around
this British colony. Many live in squalid conditions. Britain has
said it is close to an agreement with Vietnam on repatriating the
refugees.
</TEXT>
