<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hajj     07-13 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hajj,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems End Pilgrimage to Mecca</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a million Moslems today
descended Mount Arafat and crossed a scorching plain to the holy
city of Mecca for prayers culminating their annual pilgrimage.
   This year's pilgrimage, or hajj, to Saudi Arabia was conducted
under the guard of anti-terrorist security squads.
   The worshipers filed past the road in Mecca where two bombs
exploded Monday, killing one person and injuring 16.
   Waves of men in white seamless robes _ signifiying equality in
the eyes of Allah _ and women in long dresses and head scarves
participated in the prayer, broadcast live via satellite to scores
of countries.
   About 1.8 million Moslems came from more than 80 countries for
the hajj, which every financially able Moslem is expected to make at
least once.
   Iran boycotted this year's hajj to protest restrictions on the
number of pilgrims. Each nation was given a quota of 1,000 pilgrims
per million people.
   Iran alleged the restrictions were intended to limit the number
of Iranian pilgrims. It also accused Saudi authorities of
fabricating Monday's bomb incident to discredit Iran. The Saudis
have not accused Iran of planting the bombs.
   At twilight, the pilgrims offered the Eid Al-Adha, or Feast of
Sacrifice, prayers before slaughtering hundreds of thousands of
sheep, cows and camels.
   They then streamed down Mount Arafat to the Mina plain and on to
Mecca for the farewell prayer before dispersing. Arafat, Mina and
Mecca are all about four miles apart.
   Some pilgrims walked from Mina to Mecca, but most took advantage
of air-conditioned buses provided by the Saudis.
   In traditional messages, Saudi Arabia's King Fahd and his crown
prince, Abdullah, made no mention of the bombings.
   The king said it was a ``sacred duty'' for him as ``custodian of
Islam's holiest shrines'' to complete renovation and modernization
plans at Mecca to provide pilgrims with better conditions for future
pilgrimages.
   Saudi Arabia cited the construction under way as the main reason
for curtailing the number of pilgrims. Limits on pilgrims first were
imposed in 1988.
   The previous year, demonstrations by thousands of the
150,000-strong Iranian hajj contingent led to clashes with Saudi
police. At least 402 people died, most of them Iranians.
   Scores of Iranians were arrested during the 1986 hajj when they
tried to bring in explosives.
   Princes and dignitaries from Arabia, merchants and paupers from
Bangladesh and India, Cossack and Tartars from the Soviet Union,
mingled with other pilgrims from Poland, Hungary, Spain, Senegal and
Indonesia _ all chanting in union ``Allah Akbar Kabeera,
Walhumdillah Katheera,'' Arabic for ``God is so great and to Him we
pay high tribute.''
   The hajj is performed during the Islamic lunar months of Shawwal,
Zul-Quideh and Zul-Hijjeh. Similar rituals performed out of the
season are called ``Umrah,'' or lesser hajj.
   The hajj proper is limited to six days. A pilgrim may commence
the rituals at any time during the three months, but the actual
congregational rites were conducted this year between July 8 and
July 13.
   Hajis are required to pray at the Grand Mosque in Mecca and
circle its Kaaba, a granite cube draped with gold-embroidered black
brocade. Moslems honor the Kaaba as the house of Allah. As they
circle the cube, pilgrims often bend to kiss the sacred black stoe
set in silver on the east corner of the granite structure.
   The pilgrims also run back and forth seven times between Safa and
Marwa, two hills 800 yards apart, enclosed within a huge mosque.
They commemorate the agony of Hagar, Abraham's estranged wife, who
ran frantically in the same spot searching for water for her son
Ismail, until Allah guided her to a spring.
   The spring today feeds the sacred well of Zamzam in the heart of
the Grand Mosque.
   When they go to Mina, each pilgrim throws seven stones at each of
the three ``devil pillars,'' a spot where Moslems believed the devil
tried to tempt Abraham to disobey Allah and refuse to sacrifice his
son.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
