<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-Scandal     07-13 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Scandal,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Agrees to Investigate Ex-minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament voted today to investigate a
former minister accused of responsibility for a major agricultural
scandal that defrauded the European Economic Community.
   Nikos Athanasopoulos, deputy finance minister in the former
Socialist government, is accused of arranging for a shipment of
9,000 tons of Yugoslav corn to be issued with Greek certificates of
origin in 1986 and sold to a member state of the European Community
by a Greek state company.
   The European Court ruled against Greece in May this year, citing
lost revenues of $2 million which should have been paid on corn
imported from a non-member country. Sentencing is expected later
this year.
   Legislators from the conservative New Democracy party claimed in
Parliament that Greece will be made to pay at least $3.6 million in
reparations.
   Legislators from the governing alliance of the New Democracy and
the Coalition of the Left and Progress carried the motion to
investigate Athanasopoulos with 168 votes in the 300-member
Parliament.
   The Panhellenic Socialist Movement, which was swept from office
amid a series of scandals in June 18 elections, abstained from the
vote.
   Athanasopoulos, who was not re-elected, submitted a memorandum
denying involvement in the scandal.
   ``We have to note our international disgrace and the irreparable
ethical damage done to our country in the eyes of our community
partners,'' said one legislator.
   ``Where did the money go?'' New Democracy party leader
Constantine Mitsotakis asked Parliament about the money from the
duties that were not paid.
   Under the law governing the culpability of Cabinet ministers, a
special committee of 12 legislators will investigate the charges
against Athanasopoulos and decide whether the former minister should
stand trial.
   The coalition government has pledged to investigate and punish
those involved in scandals in banking, the arms industry and alleged
phone-tapping by the former socialist administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
