<FIRST>u a PM-DukakisVeto     07-13 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis Veto,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Outlines $491 Milion in Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seeking to shock legislators into supporting a tax
increase, Gov. Michael S. Dukakis today outlined $491 million in
cuts in the Massachusetts state budget.
   ``I'm today doing the worst thing I ever had to do in my
political career,'' Dukakis said at a noon news conference, at which
he blamed himself and the Legislature for the state's fiscal mess.
   The package of impounded funds and vetoes cuts into a $12.3
billion state budget for the fiscal year that began July 1.
   The cuts include a freezing of welfare benefits at current
levels, cuts of $16 million in environmental affairs and $17 million
judiciary and district attorney accounts and a reduction in state
scholarship funds. The welfare move means that the state's poor
receiving general relief will get no cost-of-living increase.
   ``All of us in state government have arrived at this unhappy
moment through a combination of miscalculations, mistakes and
misinformation,'' Dukakis said. ``I'm disappointed in myself. I'm
disappointed in the legislature. I'm disappointed in all of us who
have let the talkmasters and the columnists define our values, our
commitment to public service, our commitment to each other.''
   The Dukakis plan includes an across-the-board reduction in
administrative costs by 10 percent.
   ``The first 250 million hits the bone and will cause real pain,''
Dukakis said. ``The balance hits raw nerve and will be devastating
to people, to families and to communities. I'm doing what I'm doing
today because I have to do it to avoid fiscal chaos. I can't let the
state go down the drain financially and I won't.''
   Key pieces of the Dukakis package of state spending reductions
include:
   _Total cuts in public education and higher education of $62
million.
   _A cut in the state human services budget of $97 million.
   _Reduction in the state AIDS program of $2 million.
   _A cut in Aid to Families with Dependent Children of $22 million.
   _$8 million from the state mental health budget.
   The Legislature has already given initial approval to a tax
increase to balance the previous year's budget. Now the issue of a
tax increase for this year looms.
   Using the line-item veto and his power to impound funds, Dukakis
said he also plans to eliminate the office of University of
Massachusetts President David Knapp and cut two-thirds of the 2,100
additional state employees planned for in the budget, leaving prison
guards as one of the few categories to be increased.
</TEXT>
