<HEAD>Woman Survives in Flattened, Asphalt-Covered Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYOSSET, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck filled with hot asphalt overturned
onto a woman's car, nearly sealing it with the steaming goo, police
said Thursday.
   Patrons of a restaurant nearby used shovels to clear a space so
the woman could breathe, and she let her rescuers know she was alive
by honking the horn.
   The woman, Pamela Cohen, 26, of Bay Shore, was in stable
condition Thursday at the Nassau County Medical Center with leg
injuries.
   County police said the truck was turning into the restaurant
Wednesday when it toppled, spilling much of the 325-degree asphalt.
Rescuers poured water on the asphalt periodically to cool it down.
Steam injured three firefighters.
   The driver of the truck, Ralph Uliano, 37, of Huntington Station,
was charged with driving while intoxicated.
