<FIRST>r i AM-Norway-Soviet     07-13 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Soviet,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norway Wants Treaty With Soviets on Military Accidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway will propose a bilateral agreement
with the Soviet Union covering warnings on military accidents, a
report said Thursday.
   Norway began drafting the treaty two years ago and made it a high
priority after a recent Soviet navy accidents off northern Norway,
according to the newspaper Klassekampen.
   ``Norway is ready to enter an agreement with the Soviets about
warnings on military incidents,'' acting Foreign Ministry spokesman
Oeyvind Nordsletten told the newspaper. He did not say when the pact
would be presented.
   Oslo complained of Soviet slowness in providing warnings and
details of accidents aboard two Soviet nuclear submarines near
Norwegian territory.
   On April 7, a Soviet submarine sank in the Norwegian Sea. On June
26, another Soviet sub suffered a reactor breakdown off northern
Norway.
   Nordsletten said the draft treaty is similar to those the Soviets
recently signed with the United States, Britain, France and West
Germany.
   The treaty also would require warning when ships or aircraft from
the countries approach each other, he said. There is heavy air and
sea traffic off northern Norway from Soviet miltary bases on the
Kola Peninsula, just across the Norwegian-Soviet border.
   ``One example of an incident that might have been covered was
when a Norwegian Orion surveillance plane was damaged by a Soviet
fighter that flew too close over the Barents Sea in 1987,'' he said.
   Last fall, the two nations agreed to inform each other of
civilian nuclear accidents, such as the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant disaster in 1986.
</TEXT>
