<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-13 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites ,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At age 8, Emma Macchiarini-Mankin not only
conquered the treacherous waters of the Golden Gate but also proved
herself a master of the athletic interview.
   ``I made a deal with the sharks _ I wouldn't eat them if they
wouldn't eat me,'' she said Wednesday after becoming the youngest
person to swim the mile-wide passage where the Pacific Ocean meets
the San Francisco Bay.
   With coach and father Danny Macchiarini at her side, Emma
completed the swim in 68 minutes, braving 60-degree temparatures and
tricky currents and maneuvering around a Navy ship.
   Emma, who took to the pool at 10 months and had her first dip in
the bay at 5, bested the youngest-swimmer record set by 12-year-old
Mike Lynch in 1964.
   The 5-foot, 75-pound athlete admitted having doubts near the end
of the swim, but was more than ready when the press asked the
inevitable, ``Why?''
   ``Because I don't know how to drive a car there,'' she said,
adding, ``I want to be famous and have all the money.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to fighting City Hall, Dr. John
Pittman sure knows how to raise a stink.
   When zoning authorities rejected the heart surgeon's request to
put up low-rise office buildings on his 68-acre property in this
wealthy suburb, Pittman turned the place into a hog farm.
   The unexpected whiff of rural Indiana is anything but welcome
among tenants of the new tinted-glass office buildings in the
neighborhood.
   ``There's an old adage you don't have a pig in a parlor,'' said
F. Richard Rembusch, executive vice president of Browning
Investments and one of many unhappy purveyors of office space.
``There is just a foul odor.''
   Pittman swears he didn't bring in the pigs out of spite. He said
it was the only thing he could do with the property after his
building plans were blocked.
   There are signs the standoff may be easing. Recently, Pittman
sold about 200 of his 300 hogs _ because of declining prices, he
said.
   But Mayor Dorothy Hancock maintained she struck a ``gentlemen's
agreement'' with Pittman to scale back the pig operation ``in the
interest of not making people madder.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hamburg residents turn out to celebrate the
104th anniversary of the ``Birth of the Burger'' Saturday, but
there's a sizzling debate over the true origin of that most American
of meals.
   Seymour, Wis., boosters spurn the Hamburgers' claim that the meat
patty was first served in this Buffalo, N.Y., suburb at the 1885
Erie County Fair by entrepreneurs Francis and Charles Menches.
   Dick Tepp, organizer of a 100th anniversary bash for the burger
in Seymour on Aug. 5, says he can prove the hamburger was first
fried and sold by Charles Naygreen at the Outagamie Country Riding
Fair in Wisconsin in 1889.
   ``We've done a lot of research, and we have factual, hard
evidence _ pictures, newspaper clippings and even a living
descendant,'' Tepp says.
   Violet Gauerke, daughter of ``Hamburger Charlie,'' says her
father was 15 when he got the idea to flatten out meatballs and
stick them between slices of bread to make them easier to eat.
   ``He was known all over the country for it,'' she says.
   Hamburg Mayor Richard Hansen is unimpressed.
   ``We believe that we were the first,'' he says. ``And that's all
that matters.''
</TEXT>
