<SECOND>AM-Gore-Audit,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>FEC Says Gore Didn't Get Favored Treatment from Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. didn't get favored
treatment from banks that loaned him $1.6 million for his
unsuccessful run for the Democratic presidential nomination, the
Federal Election Commission said Thursday.
   Most of the loans were taken out around the time of a group
Southern primaries in March 1988. The Tennessee senator had pinned
much of his hopes for winning the nomination on those primaries.
   Election commission auditors initially questioned whether some of
the banks making the loans had gotten enough collateral and
assurances of repayment. Four of the banks are in Tennessee, and the
other is in the District of Columbia.
   Gore's campaign argued that the loans had been repaid in full,
which should serve as the ultimate proof of the soundness of the
decision to lend the money.
