<DOCNO> AP890713-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DC-Police     07-13 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-Police,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Hiring Plan Gets OK from Senate Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel Thursday approved a $127 million
bill to pay for 700 additional District of Columbia police in an
effort to stem the burgeoning murder rate in the nation's capital.
   The House already has approved the plan for the federal
government to pick up the tab for the extra officers.
   By Thursday, 229 people had been killed in the district this
year, compared with 159 at the same time in 1988. A record 372
people were killed last year.
   Police blame more than 60 percent of the slayings on drugs.
   Before the Governmental Affairs committee approved the five-year
plan, Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said he might introduce an amendment
requiring the city to pay for part of the program.
   The city already has agreed to pay about $2 million in recruiting
and training costs.
   However, Levin may drop plans to have the city pay for the
officers if he's convinced the district is also making efforts to
hire police, said Levin aide Linda Gustitus.
   The city is adding 200 officers in the current fiscal year, while
300 more are to be hired in the fiscal year that starts Oct. 1.
   The panel also approved an amendment by Sen. Jon Heinz, R-Pa.,
that requires the city to share routine arrest information and other
police data with the FBI and other federal law enforcement groups.
   Because of a 1968 law establishing a balance of power between the
federal and local police departments, the district is the only
jurisdiction in the nation not to share such information.
</TEXT>
