<DOCNO> AP890713-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-US     07-13 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed Soviet Law on Emigration Boosts Applications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed liberalization of emigration laws has
nearly quadrupled the number of Soviets seeking to settle in the
United States, a U.S. official said Thursday.
   About 33,000 Soviets moved to the United States in 1988. This
year, Soviets are registering their intent to emigrate at an annual
rate of 120,000, and that could reach a quarter-million by 1990,
said Max Robinson, consul-general at the U.S. Embassy.
   ``The United States has a policy of giving all Soviets who seek
to emigrate to the United States the chance to do so,'' Robinson
said. ``That dates back to a very recent time when we were engaged
in a major human rights struggle with Soviet officials to free up
emigration. They are doing so at rates that we did not expect but
are delighted to see.''
   ``I think that once the new emigration law comes into effect and
a pattern is established, it could double next year and come awfully
close to a quarter million,'' he said.
   That many Soviet emigres could overwhelm the U.S. immigration
system, since 200,000 would approximately equal the number allowed
into the United States from rest of the world, Robinson said.
   ``That creates an imbalance that we are going to take a good hard
look at from a policy perspective,'' said Robinson. ``The policy is
under review Washington,'' by the administration and Congress.
   President Bush has said if the Soviets enact the proposed changes
in their emigration law, he will urge Congress to pass a one-year
waiver of the Jackson-Vanik amendment, thereby reducing the tariffs
on Soviet goods exported to the United States. The law, passed in
1972, was sponsored by the late Sen. Henry Jackson and then-Rep.
Charles Vanik.
   Soviet officials involved in drafting the liberalized emigration
law want it enacted as speedily as possible, said Yuri Reshetov,
head of the Foreign Ministry human rights department.
   ``The draft law ... establishes freedom of entry and departure.
Exit or entry on a permanent or temporary basis will be free,''
Reshetov told a news conference. ``The law is on par with
international practice in this area.''
   The key change will be dropping the requirement that Soviets
seeking to emigrate obtain an invitation from an immediate family
member abroad. Instead, Soviets will need only an invitation from a
friend, relative or commercial enterprise saying the emigre will be
supported, according to U.S. officials familar with drafts of the
law.
   The draft addresses two other often-criticized points in the law,
which deny visas to people who have conducted classified research
and require would-be emigres to secure statements from relatives
that they leave behind no outstanding financial obligations,
Reshetov said.
   Terms of secrecy will expire after five years, and the cases of
so-called ``poor relatives'' will be handled by family courts, he
said.
   Foreign Ministry officials have tried to impress upon members of
the new legislature, the Supreme Soviet, ``the necessity of the
speedy adoption of this law,'' Reshetov said.
   The U.S. consul-general said Soviet citizens were lining up for
visas in anticipation of the new legislation.
   Of the 33,000 Soviet citizens who entered the United States in
1988, said Robinson, 20,000 first went to Rome on Israeli visas and
then on to the United States, and the remainder went directly on
U.S. documents.
   So far in 1989, Soviets are registering with U.S. officials at
the rate of 60,000 a year, and at the same rate at the Dutch
Embassy, which handles consular affairs for the Israeli government.
   In any recent week, he said, 1,200 to 1,500 Soviets registered at
the U.S. Embassy, of whom 40 percent were Armenian, 25 percent
Jewish, 15 percent ethnic Russians, 5 percent to 8 percent
Ukrainians and 5 percent Balts. Others were Azerbaijani, Turkish,
Georgian or Tadzhik or another nationality.
   Of the comparable number that register weekly at the Dutch
Embassy for Israeli visas, he said, about 95 percent are Jewish.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
