<FIRST>b a PM-WanderingPlane 8thLd-Writethru a0659 07-13 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane, 8th Ld - Writethru, a0659,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Rescued After Plane Crashes Into Atlantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with man reported to have swum
toward rescuers, name of man, other detail. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Reports
from...'. SUBS penultimate graf to DELETE extraneous `she said.'; ADDS
2 grafs on end with further detail on co-workers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane with a stricken pilot ran out of gas
and crashed into the ocean today after flying hundreds of miles on
autopilot. Astonished rescuers said the man swam toward them and was
pulled alive from the water.
   The pilot, identified as a Washington, D.C., lawyer, was taken by
helicopter to Nassau, the Bahamas, and will be flown by jet to
Florida, the Coast Guard said.
   ``The words you keep hearing are: `You're kidding,''' said Petty
Officer Veronica Cady, a Coast Guard spokeswoman.
   Military pilots and rescuers trained to parachute into the ocean
to save ditched pilots could only watch helplessly as their aircraft
tracked the single-engine plane for nearly four hours while it
slowly ran out of gas. The plane crashed in the Atlantic in the
Bahamas.
   ``With all that time he didn't answer us, no communciation
whatsoever, seen slumped behind the wheel, we assumed he was at the
least unconscious,'' Ms. Cady said. ``For him to survive a crash
like that, it just sent us all into shock. We didn't expect this
story to have a happy ending.''
   Rescuers didn't know how he got out of the plane, she said. There
was no immediate word on the man's condition.
   The Federal Aviation Administration declined to identify the
pilot, but staff members at the Washington law firm of Thomas Root,
36, a communications lawyer, confirmed that he was the man.
   Nothing more was heard from him after he reported to air traffic
controllers in Virginia at 8:30 a.m. that he was having chest pains
and difficulty breathing. He had taken off from Washington's
National Airport at about 6:30 a.m., bound for Rocky Mount, N.C.
   The man was glimpsed, apparently unconscious, at one point as the
plane headed southward roughly parallel to the East Coast. There was
no one else visible in the plane, and radio messages to the plane
went unanswered.
   The Coast Guard said the plane ran out of gas and crashed into
the ocean in the central Bahamas, about 15 miles east of the island
of Eleuthera. The site is about 250 miles southeast of Miami and 800
miles from the pilot's original destination.
   Reports from the planes tailing the Cessna were that ``it
spiraled into the water, so it didn't make the best of all possible
landings,'' Chief Petty Officer Lou Parris said.
   FAA spokesman Jack Barker in Atlanta said that as the plane
headed southward it had gotten as near as 100 miles from the East
Coast shore because of the curvature of the coastline.
   Hans Hess, manager of the Rocky Mount-Wilson, N.C., airport, said
the plane had been due to arrive there at 7:49 a.m. Hess said a
person had been waiting to meet the pilot and the plane. He did not
know if that person was a relative and did not identify the person.
   After its distress call, the plane was intercepted by two Marine
Corps F-A-18 Hornets when it entered Norfolk Naval Station airspace
at 8:45 a.m., said Lt. Cmdr. Mike John, a Navy spokesman.
   The pilots of the intercepting planes tried unsuccessfully to
establish voice contact with the pilot, he said.
   The Cessna 210 Centurion can seat four to six people, counting
the pilot, and cruises at about 190 mph.
   Bill Pierman, shift supervisor in the air traffic control tower
at Washington National, told Raleigh radio station WPTF the plane
``very easily'' could wind up in the Bahamas.
   ``Put an airplane on automatic pilot and it's going to continue
just exactly on the course that the automatic pilot is set for.''
   He said the automatic pilot was set on a heading that would have
sent the plane toward Bahamas, but the pilot would have made a turn
for the Rocky Mount-Wilson Airport.
   The two rescue teams are part of the 301st Aerospace Rescue and
Recovery Squad. The C-130 part of the squad is based at Homestead,
the helicopter part at Patrick, said Lt. Col. Margaret Stanek of
Homestead Air Force Base.
   A flight surgeon was part of the rescue teams as well as the
people trained to parachute in the water, she said.
   Root's staff gathered around a portable radio to hear news that
he had been fished out of the water alive, but Signe Schilperoort, a
paralegal in the office, said they had received no word on the
rescue or on Root's condition from authorities.
   She said Root had no history of medical problems and had been
flying since he was a teen-ager.
</TEXT>
