<FIRST>r w AM-PuertoRico     07-13 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Complains of Administration Inaction on Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a Senate committee drafting a
Puerto Rican plebiscite bill criticized the Bush administration
Thursday for failing to answer questions concerning the economic
impact of proposed statehood or ``enhanced'' commonwealth status.
   Those alternatives to Puerto Rico's commonwealth status will be
on the ballot when the people of Puerto Rico vote in a referendum
scheduled for 1991, and Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., thinks the
voters should know in advance what their choice will entail.
   Johnston, irritated by the absence from Washington of President
Bush's aide handling Puerto Rican affairs, told a U.S. Treasury
official that his request to leave the Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee hearing early was an ``insult to this committee
and to the Puerto Rican status issue.''
   Kenneth W. Gideon, assistant secretary of the Treasury for tax
policy, responded that the administration is willing to work with
the Senate committee on the plebiscite. He told the committee, ``The
choice facing the people of Puerto Rico is fundamentally a political
one, with long-term implications for their rights and obligations as
citizens.''
   But this view clashed with that of Johnson, who believes Puerto
Rican voters should know in advance what they should expect in terms
of future U.S. funds for food, health and other basic programs under
any transition afforded under independence or statehood.
   Johnston is asking the administration to spell out in detail the
fiscal impact of major federally funded programs and is seeking
information regarding all 385 federally funded programs on the
island.
   Puerto Rico presently participates in all but 30 U.S.-funded
programs under its present commonwealth status.
   In seeking ``enhanced'' commonwealth status, Gov. Rafael
Hernandez Colon seeks a larger voice for the island in determining
which federal laws should be applicable to the island. The governor
first proposed the holding of a status plebiscite during an
inaugural address earlier this year.
   Johnston, who earlier scored President Bush for remarking on his
personal preference on the island, said he hopes for an evenhanded
approach to all options during the referendum. He said the Bush
administration needs ``a totally new attitude'' regarding the
plebiscite and the present hearings on legislation setting up the
federally supported referendum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
