<FIRST>r i AM-Summit-Security     07-13 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Security,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Mount Massive Effort to Protect Foreign Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit-Overview, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rooftop marksmen, airborne television cameras and a
security force of 30,000 protected the leaders of 34 nations
Thursday as they kicked off the bicentennial celebration of the
French Revolution.
   Extra radar installations and even ground-to-air missiles were in
place for the three-day celebration and for the summit of the
world's seven leading industrialized democracies, which begins
Friday.
   ``It's going well, very well,'' said Jean Hanot, chief of police
at the summit site in western Paris. ``Anyhow, you can't be a
pessimist in this business.''
   The guns and guards were focused first on Paris' main boulevards,
where red, white and blue flags flew and noisy motorcades carried
leaders to an array of bicentennial events _ not always to the
pleasure of pedestrians.
   On the Rue du Faubourg St. Honore, the elegant street on which
the Elysee Palace of President Francois Mitterrand is situated,
police shoved Parisians back into their shops as motorcades sped by.
   ``I thought this was our city,'' one resident grumbled.
   Parts of the city were closed to drivers through the weekend.
Although many residents fled the city to avoid the mess, police said
1,000 cars were towed Thursday alone.
   Popular low-lying ``fly boats'' for tourists were forbidden from
plying the Seine River running through Paris.
   A 200-foot-long blimp, which can carry a crew of 10, relayed live
television pictures from two cameras to ground command centers.
   The dirigible, estimated to cost $7 million, was used earlier
this month for surveillance during the visit of Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Mirage fighters and Crotale ground-to-air missiles backed up the
blimp, and six radar systems were added to the four normally
installed around Paris to ensure that uninvited guests did not enter
the skies, security officials said.
   At the Arch, the gleaming arch-shaped building where the seven
summiteers will meet, police also planned air protection, said Hanot.
   He said that in addition to 4,000 police in and around the steel
fence ringing the site, 200 sharpshooters were to be stationed on
the rooftops of the jumble of skyscrapers in the area.
   During the summit, traffic will be halted along the five-mile
route from central Paris to the Arch for an hour each in the morning
and the afternoon to allow the foreign leaders to travel, said
police.
</TEXT>
