<FIRST>r i AM-France-Choir     07-13 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Choir,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Children in Peace Theme To Honor French Declaration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Bicentennial, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A choir of children from 15 countries, including
three from the United States, highlighted a theme of international
peace Thursday at the start of celebrations for the bicentennial of
the French revolution.
   The children sang, played games and cast laurels, toys and
flowers before 32 world leaders assembled at Trocadero, across the
Seine from the Eiffel Tower, to honor France's 1789 declaration of
human rights.
   President Francois Mitterrand, seated between President Bush and
Ivory Coast leader Felix Houphouet-Boigny, smiled as the children
ran toward the world leaders and put down the laurels.
   ``We wanted to symbolize peace,'' said Harvey K. Smith, director
of the Phoenix Boys' Choir.
   Smith brought three boys from Phoenix and helped train the
48-member choir, titled ``Little Singers of the World.'' It was
assembled by the United Nations Children's Fund.
   ``The children brought things from their world and shared them
with those here today,'' Smith said.
   The children sang ``Song of Joy,'' a piece of composed for the
celebrations.
   The choir also included three Soviet children, and youths from
Poland, Finland, West Germany, France, Japan, Rwanda, Togo,
Australia, Canada, Mexico, Hungary, Lebanon and the Philippines.
   The children gathered up the toys after the ceremony and then
sang in English the song, ``Nobody Knows The Troubles I've Seen.''
</TEXT>
