<FIRST>r i AM-Mandela     07-13 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Botha-Mandela Visit Sows Confusion Among Anti-Apartheid Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid groups, unsure
how to react to talks between President P.W. Botha and black leader
Nelson Mandela, reversed course Thursday and said the meeting was a
positive development.
   ``We do not condemn the meeting at all,'' Mandela's wife, Winnie,
was quoted as saying Thursday by the independent South African Press
Association. ``For us to get to the negotiation table, we have to
start somewhere.''
   Neither Botha nor his heir apparent, National Party leader F.W.
de Klerk, has commented on the July 5 meeting at the presidential
residence in Cape Town.
   Anti-apartheid groups, including Mandela's African National
Congress, initially dismissed the talks as government propaganda
that involved no shift in policy.
   But in a statement Wednesday, Mandela appeared to welcome his
chance to talk with Botha.
   ``I only would like to contribute to the creation of the climate
which would promote peace in South Africa,'' the jailed, 70-year-old
activist said. ``I would also like to confirm that my release is not
an issue at this stage.''
   The statement was Mandela's first since 1985 that was approved by
the government for public release.
   Member of Parliament Helen Suzman, a longtime apartheid foe, had
lunch with Mandela on Thursday but would not disclose anything he
said except, ``He told me he was pleased to have met ... President
Botha.''
   She had not seen him since August, when he was being treated in
hospital for tuberculosis. She said he described his health as good
and he was in very good spirits. ``He keeps fit with the help of an
exercise bicycle and he is visited regularly by his doctor,'' she
said.
   Anti-apartheid leader Frank Chikane appeared with Mrs. Mandela on
Sunday and said the meeting was ``political mischief'' intended to
``sow confusion in the minds of black people.''
   The South African Council of Churches, which Chikane leads, said
Wednesday it was a ``calculated attempt by the government to make
maximum political gain.''
   However, Chikane said Thursday: ``I welcome Mr. Mandela's
commitment to contribute in any way possible to the creation of a
climate which will promote peace in South Africa.''
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu said Mandela's statement was
``remarkably statesmanlike'' and should dispel the belief among many
South African whites that Mandela is a ``so-called terrorist.''
   ``White South Africa is going to be quite, quite amazed when they
get to hear him speak for himself,'' Tutu said.
   The outlawed African National Congress dismissed the meeting
Monday as a ``public relations exercise.'' It has not commented
publicly on Mandela's statement.
   ``Mandela Wants Peace,'' said the front-page headline in Die
Burger, a pro-government Afrikaans-language newspaper. ``Mandela:
Peace By Dialogue,'' said The Citizen, a pro-government
English-language daily.
   Such headlines were considered unthinkable until recently. Both
newspapers regularly referred to the African National Congress as a
terrorist organization.
   ``There is something Oriental in the way (Mandela) has turned
weakness into power,'' said the anti-apartheid Business Day, the
leading financial daily.
   ``He has achieved much by doing virtually nothing, forcing his
jailers progressively to ease the conditions of his release,'' the
editorial added. ``It is not too much to say that the government is
now the prisoner of its prisoner: it cannot escape his embrace.''
   The government has said Mandela, founder of the congress'
guerrilla wing, must renounce violence before he can be freed. But
Botha this year has suggested those terms may be eased.
   Mandela, serving a life sentence for sabotage and plotting to
overthrow the government, has said he will not disavow violence
until his organization is legalized and apartheid is dismantled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
