<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PorkOutlook     07-13 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pork Outlook,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>More, Cheaper Pork Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers are seeing more pork this year and
some easing of prices at meat counters, the Agriculture Department
said Thursday.
   ``Hog producers have experienced a steep drop in returns over the
past year but have made only a modest cutback in hog numbers,'' the
department's Economic Research Service said.
   Commercial output of pork for all of 1989 is estimated at 15.9
billion pounds, up 2 percent from last year and the most since 1980,
the agency reported. Market prices of hogs going to slaughter are
expected to average $40 to $43 per 100 pounds, compared with $43 in
1988.
   The all-cut retail price of pork may be around $1.80 per pound in
1989, down 3 to 5 cents per pound from last year's average, the
report said.
</TEXT>
