<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-13 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shooting Reported in Ethnically Troubled Territory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People are shooting at towns and roads and setting
up roadblocks to disrupt traffic in Nagorno-Karabakh, a disputed
territory swept by ethnic violence last year, Tass said Thursday.
   An Armenian motorist was found shot to death on a road leading to
Stepanakert, and ethnic Azerbaijanis ``started a pogrom'' in the
city of Shusha, the official news agency reported.
   Rioters destroyed a store and the airport dispatcher's office in
Stepanakert, the territorial capital, it said.
   The Tass report said roving bands erected barriers on many roads,
and ``bus connections between Stepanakert and other towns have been
interrupted. Automobile traffic into the territory is blockaded.''
   Soviet central authorities have sent a group of ranking police
and internal affairs officials to direct law enforcement in
Nagorno-Karabakh, where ethnic conflict started riots last year that
killed more than 90 people in the neighboring southern republics of
Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   Ethnic Armenians, most of them Christians, make up three-quarters
of Nagorno-Karabakh's population, but the fertile region was
assigned in 1923 to Azerbaijan, a predominantly Moslem republic. It
is about 1,200 miles south of Moscow.
   Tass said Thursday that one man was hospitalized because of the
trouble in Shusha, but also quoted authorities as saying many
injuries were not being reported.
   ``Recent days have been marked by people firing hunting guns on
towns,'' it said. A highway checkpoint in the Askeransky region was
shot at Thursday night, according to Tass, and officers at another
were fired on when they sought to check the documents of a truck
with no license plate.
   Because of the roadblocks, ``bus connections between Stepanakert
and other towns have been interrupted,'' the news agency reported.
``Automobile traffic into the territory is blockaded.''
   In Moscow, Interior Ministry spokesman Alexander Timokhin said
Artur Toniyan, the Armenian found dead Wednesday on a road between
two Azerbaijani villages, apparently was the victim of an ethnically
motivated attack.
   Two Azerbaijanis were killed and a third seriously wounded
Tuesday near Kirkidzhan village. There were conflicting reports that
Armenians ambushed the men, that they died in a car accident or
killed each other in a fight.
   A 1 a.m.-5 a.m. curfew is in force in the territory, a
2-month-old strike is keeping most businesses closed and armored
personnel carriers patrol the streets of Stepanakert and other
cities.
   Residents of the capital spoke in telephone interviews of rumors
that Azerbaijanis attacked the ethnic Armenian village of Dashpulag
on Wednesday.
   ``Two buses went there yesterday to help the wounded,'' said
Armen Khachaturyan, who works at the Stepanakert television station.
   Timokhin, the Interior Ministry spokesman, said no reports of
such an attack had reached Moscow.
</TEXT>
