<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Khomeini 1stLd-Writethru   07-13 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Khomeini, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0669,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millions Throng Khomeini's Grave At End Of 40 Days Of Mourning</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS grafs 5-6, `Khomeini's son...climaxed Thursday' to CLARIFY
that weeping uncle is Pasandideh. Pick up 7th pvs, `As the...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions chanting ``Death to America!''
and beating themselves in grief surrounded the gold-domed tomb of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on Thursday to end 40 days of mourning
for the founder of the Islamic republic.
   His successor as Iran's religious leader, President Ali Khamenei,
appeared in public for the first time since Khomeini's June 6
funeral and delivered a tirade against the ``terrorists'' of the
United States and its allies.
   The speeches by Khamenei and other Iranian leaders turned the
religious ceremony into an rally against the United States, Israel
and Saudi Arabia.
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, seen as Khamenei's
successor, was cheered when he appeared on a podium some distance
from the grave, accompanied by bodyguards carrying automatic rifles.
   Khomeini's son, Ahmad, and Khomeini's elder brother, Ayatollah
Morteza Pasandideh, were also hailed by the crowd when they appeared
on the podium.
   Ahmad, 43, flanked by his weeping uncle, said Iran should stand
firm ``against plots in the region against us,'' an apparent
reference to Saudi Arabia's curb on Iranians from making the annual
pilgrimage to Mecca that climaxed Thursday.
   As the representative of Khomeini's family, he declared the
mourning period over.
   Iranian media monitored in Cyprus said ``millions'' of people
rhythmically thumping their chests and heads in a ritualized frenzy
of grief packed an area 1{ miles deep around the shrine in the
Behesht-e Zahra cemetery outside Tehran.
   There was no independent estimate of the crowd, but aerial views
shown on Iranian television indicated it was as big as the gathering
at Khomeini's funeral, which authorities estimated was attended by
10 million people.
   Khomeini died June 3 at the age of 86, 10 years after his Islamic
revolution toppled Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
   Iranian TV showed swarms of wailing mourners pressing around
Khomeini's shrine, which is considered sacred. They believed
Khomeini's blessing and protection would be bestowed on anyone who
touches the temporary square monument that has been constructed over
Khomeini's grave.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said 10,000 people
collapsed with ``heart problems'' or were injured in the suffocating
throng. Another 10,000 were overcome by the 110-degree temperatures,
IRNA said.
   The live broadcast from the cemetery 10 miles south of the
capital showed those who had collapsed being handed by other
mourners over the heads of the crowd to first aid teams waiting on
the fringes. Iranian media reported many were in serious condition
even after treatment at 50 medical stations set up along roads
leading to the cemetery.
   Firefighters sprayed water on the people to cool them down as
loudspeakers blared readings from the Koran, Islam's holy book.
   Many traveled from across the country before Thursday's
ceremonies to keep an all-night vigil around the shrine, IRNA
reported.
   Only low-ranking officials from a few countries attended
Thursday's ceremonies. Major world leaders also shunned Khomeini's
funeral.
   Khamenei denied Iran was behind the bombings in Mecca on Monday
that killed one person and wounded 16 during the pilgrimage.
   ``If exporting the revolution means exporting explosives, and
creating havoc among other nations, then this accusation is far from
the hands of the Islamic republic,'' he said.
   ``Exporting mischief and corruption belongs to America and ...
other aggressive governments,'' he declared.
   ``The hands of the America and its underlings ... are stained
with the blood of innocents. They are the terrorists. The Islamic
republic is absolved of these allegations.''
   Thursday's scene was similar to the mass outpouring of grief at
Khomeini's funeral, when at least eight people died and 11,000 were
injured as frenzied crowds struggled to catch a glimpse of his
shrouded body.
   But this time the authorities were better prepared and
organization was more evident, with medical tents, a fleet of 600
buses, centers for lost children and enough food for 10 million.
   This time, mourners were also covered against death and injury by
a special government insurance scheme.
   Iran's state-run insurance companies announced that the
equivalent of $13,500 will be paid to the family of anyone killed or
seriously injured in the service. Medical expenses of up to $2,000
also will be paid.
   IRNA said 7,000 workers toiled since the funeral to erect the
monument over the grave and levelled a a 43-acre area around it to
accomodate the hundreds of thousands who gather there every day.
</TEXT>
