<FIRST>u w AM-NASAResignations 1stLd-Writethru a0699 07-13 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA Resignations, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Not Ready for Major New Projects</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Quayle on Space Council considerations, subbing
6 grafs for grafs 7-9 pvs, ``I read ... not sustained.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If President Bush lays down a major new
challenge for American space exploration next week NASA won't be
ready, the new head of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration said Thursday.
   ``Today's NASA can't do it,'' said Richard H. Truly in his first
news conference as NASA's administrator.
   ``We have been through several years of very marginal funding,''
he said. ``We have a lot on our plate and to take on new challenges
would require buttressing the facilities and the people to do the
job.''
   The National Space Society has urged Bush to announce a national
goal of establishing a settlement on the moon in his speech July 20
commemorating the first landing on the moon 20 years ago, just as
President John F. Kennedy established a moon landing target nearly
30 years earlier.
   ``Any new goal in whatever year is going to require adequate
resources to do it,'' said Truly. ``Given the adequate resources, I
think NASA is very strong and I think that we have a NASA that can
be built upon to take on major new challenges. But I'll tell you
this: Today's NASA can't do it.''
   Truly denied a published report that the National Space Council,
of which he is a member, has decided to make a formal recommendation
for such a major effort when Bush returns from Europe next week.
   Earlier Thursday, however, Vice President Dan Quayle briefed
about a dozen congressmen about ``a major new initiative'' the
council is considering.
   ``They basically outlined three options,'' said Rep. Robert
Walker, R-Pa., the ranking Republican member of the House Space
Science Subcommittee. ``One, for the United States to move ahead
with a robotic program and gradually phase men out of the space
program; another to go back to the moon ... and then going from
there to Mars, and third, to take us directly to Mars after the turn
of the century.''
   Walker said the council was trying to decide among the three
options before making a recommendation to Bush.
   He said the preferred option, as it was outlined to the
congressmen, ``is the mission that would take us back to the moon,
establish a permanent base some time after the first of the century
and to Mars within the first decade.''
   ``It will require doubling the size of NASA and the NASA
budget,'' Walker said.
   The space agency has asked for $13 billion in the next fiscal
year.
   Truly said a new government ethics law that goes into effect on
Sunday along with a pay cap on senior executives has cost his agency
several top managers and has created ``a very disturbing situation.''
   ``I think this ethics legislation has caused us to lose an
inordinate number compared to the average,'' he said.
   ``There are people who have left who could have given us three or
four more years of service and that's a crying shame,'' he said.
   He spoke a day after Richard O. Aller, head of NASA's Office of
Space Operations, quit suddenly _ the ninth high-level agency
resignation this year. Aller was the third to say publicly he is
leaving because of the ethics law.
   ``We know of a few others who are making their final decisions
today and tomorrow literally,'' Truly said.
   ``It's not so much the number, but the quality and experience of
these people,'' he said. ``When 10 senior service executive people
leave you, they take with them 250 to 300 years of government
leadership and experience when they walk out the door.''
   Truly said it is ``an unhealthy situation'' to have a public
service that people can't afford to work for. ``That's not a good
situation,'' he said, ``and it's one we need to deal with.''
</TEXT>
