<FIRST>u w AM-RescueUnit     07-13 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rescue Unit,1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot's Rescuers Trained to `Bring 'Em Back Alive'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs `The three ...' with 1 graf to fix syntax
and style on 10, sted ten</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wandering Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rescue team aboard the HC-130 Hercules that
participated in Thursday's dramatic water rescue of a stricken pilot
is composed of Air Force reservists trained to ``bring 'em back
alive,'' a spokesman said.
   ``We're called weekend warriors, and we're really not,'' said Air
Force Lt. Col. Robert Dubiel.
   Dubiel, interviewed by telephone from the Air Force Reserve
Headquarters in Robins, Ga., said the rescuers came from the 301st
Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squad, based at Homestead Air Force
Base on Florida's east coast.
   The Florida unit, composed of 235 reservists, is one of three
such rescue teams based around the country. The others are based
near Detroit, Mich., and near Portland, Ore., he said.
   The three squads have racked up more than 400 military and
civilian saves, or rescues, over the past 10 years, Dubiel said.
   ``They've been trained to bring 'em back alive,'' he said.
   ``We do all kinds of things _ we search for lost hikers on
mountaintops. We provide standby rescue support for the space
launches,'' Dubiel said. From the Florida base, the crews ``are
regularly called to assist the Coast Guard in the Atlantic and the
Caribbean,'' he said.
   The parachutists are specially trained to dive into the ocean to
make their rescues. And not only do the resuers have to be trained
medically to assist victims in distress, ``they have to know how to
pull them from the water, pluck them off a mountian if they have
to,'' Dubiel said. ``They have to be in super condition.''
   The job of the Air Force Reserve _ composed of some 82,000 people
_ is to augment the Air Force in crises and in peacetime and provide
backup and ``daily support'' to the military force, Dubiel said.
   A certain percentage of the reservists are on duty full time.
   Dubiel said they tend to bristle at the idea that they are called
to duty only part-time or on the weekends.
   Of the six crewmen aboard the HC-130 and the four parachutists
who dove into the water, only the co-pilot is a part-time reservist,
Dubiel said.
   The HC-130 is a four-engine turboprop plane that has been
outfitted specifically for search and rescue missions. It can also
refuel helicopters in flight.
   On Thursday, six crewmen and four parachutists aboard the plane
participated in the rescue, and all were from Florida, Dubiel said.
</TEXT>
