<FIRST>r w AM-FishWars     07-13 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish Wars,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Releases Taiwanese Vessel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard has released a Taiwanese
fishing vessel held in Midway Island after Taiwan agreed to
prosecute its captain and crewmembers on charges of illegal driftnet
fishing and trying to bribe U.S. personnel, a State Department
official said Thursday.
   ``We have assurances from the president and prime minister (of
Tawian) that both counts will be prosecutued to the maximum extent
possible under their laws,'' said Ed Wolfe, the department's
ambassador for oceans and fisheries.
   The Ta Chieh No. 3 left for Taiwan on Saturday after being
detained at Midway for several weeks while the State Department and
Taiwanese Foreign Ministry worked out details of its release and the
prosecution.
   A Coast Guard party, suspecting illegal fishing, boarded the Ta
Chieh No. 3 with permission on July 6, and was offered gold, money,
alcohol and sexual favors in return for ignoring the violations.
   When the bribes were turned down, Coast Guard officials said, the
vessel's captain ordered the boarding party to leave.
   U.S. personnel were allowed to reboard the ship two days later
and found a ship's log that indicated the vessel had been fishing in
prohibited waters for at least three years.
   The Midgett then escorted the Ta Chieh to Midway while the two
nation's negotiated over its release and the prosecution of the
captain and crew.
   State Department officials had previsouly said the incident
helped prompt the Taiwanese to the negotiating table and eventually
led to a tentative monitoring and enforcement agreement for North
Pacific driftnet fishing.
   The agreement will allow U.S. officials to board Tawianese
vessels suspected of illegal fishing on the high seas and will
require that all Taiwanese driftnet vessels be equipped with
satellite transponders in 1990.
</TEXT>
