<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-IRAArrests     07-13 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IRA Arrests,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calif., Pa. and Mass.-N.H. Residents Arrested in Bomb Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI has arrested three members of the
Provisional Irish Republican Army and accused them of developing
devices to set off for remote-controlled bombs to be used against
British targets, the agency announced Thursday.
   Richard Clark Johnson, 41, of Nashua, N.H., and Harwich, Mass.,
Martin Peter Quigley, 27, a citizen of the Republic of Ireland who
has been living since April in Bethlehem, Pa., and Christina Leigh
Reid, 25, of Sunnyvale, Calif., were arrested Wednesday by agents in
Massachusetts, Pennsylvania and California, the FBI said.
   The three face federal charges of conspiracy to injure and
destroy the property of a foreign government, specifically Britain,
the FBI said.
   Details on bail and the current status of the three were not
immediately available, said FBI spokesman Mickey Drake.
   FBI Director William S. Sessions said in a statement that the
three had backgrounds in electrical engineering and were developing
highly sophisticated circuits to be used in remote-controlled
explosive devices.
   The arrests, Sessions said, ``demonstrate the high level of
technical sophistication being employed by terrorist organizations
to further violence worldwide.''
   The FBI will continue its investigation into the organization to
try to identify other operatives of the Provisional Irish Republican
Army, the PIRA, in the United States, he said.
   A federal magistrate in Boston has issued an arrest warrant for
Peter Eamonn Macguire, an Irish citizen national living in Ireland
who is linked to the organization's explosive research program, the
FBI said.
   Drake said he had no additional information on those arrested or
Macguire.
   In affidavits filed Wednesday in U.S. District Courts in
Massachusetts, Pennsylvania and California in support of search
warrants, the FBI detailed the PIRA's efforts to obtain devices
known as tone frequency switches, which are electronic encoders that
allow radio commands to detonate explosives.
   The affidavits recounted a 1982 seizure in Newark, N.J., of a
quantity of the switches destined for the PIRA.
   Since then, the FBI said, British and Irish authorities have
recovered at least six switches in unexploded PIRA bombs in Northern
Ireland.
   It was the 1982 seizure which ultimately led to the FBI's
interest in Johnson, the FBI said. Sessions said cooperation among
the FBI and British and Irish authorities led to the arrests.
</TEXT>
