<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FlyWar     07-13 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fly War,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Try New Tactics in Fly War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old-style swat teams haven't worked, so
Agriculture Department scientists are trying new tactics to curb
flies where the nation's farms meet the cities.
   ``We've seen instances all over the country where urban
encroachment in agricultural areas has caused problems for
homeowners and agricultural producers,'' said Ralph A. Bram of the
department's Agricultural Research Service.
   Cities are sprawling into the countryside at an estimated rate of
900,000 to 1.5 million acres a year, he said Thursday in an agency
report. And to the newcomers, flies and barnyard odors aren't part
of their idyllic country dream.
   Some flies can travel great distances from manure piles or other
barnyard breeding places to find targets. The stable fly can migrate
up to 135 miles.
   Bram is the national program leader for insects affecting humans
at the agency's research facility in Beltsville, Md.
   ``We have to learn how to increase non-chemical fly control and
how to make the save chemicals we have work better,'' he said. ``It
goes beyond relying on screen doors, sprays and swatters.''
   Possible tactics include non-chemical baits in traps to lure
flies; natural predators such as wasps that prey on flies while in
their pupa stage of development; and natural organisms such as fungi
and bacteria that attack flies in cattle feedlots.
   The USDA attack is directed at four main kinds of flies:
   _Stable flies, which have biting mouth parts and feed on blood.
   _House flies, which secrete digestive enzymes onto their food,
then suck up both enzymes and food.
   _Horn flies, which bother only livestock on pastures and
rangeland.
   _Face flies, also pests of livestock, but an annoyance to
homeowners in the fall.
   Stable flies and house flies from farms are the major problem
species for homeowners, said Gustave D. Thomas, an entomologist and
research leader at the agency's Midwest Livestock Insects Research
laboratory, Lincoln, Neb.
   ``In the United States, the stable fly is estimated to cost $400
million annually in damage to cattle,'' he said.
   ``It's hard to put a dollar value on the damage caused by the
house fly. But worldwide, this fly may rank in the top 10 insect
problems because it can transmit a lot of diseases.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 2040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Strike     07-13 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strike,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Siberian Coal Miners End Strike After Gov't Agrees to Better Conditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 12,000 striking Siberian coal miners agreed
Thursday to return to work after the government agreed to provide
better work and living conditions, mine officials and strikers said.
   The two-day strike began Tuesday at all five mines in
Mezhdurechensk, prompting Communist Party and Coal Ministry
officials to rush to the western Siberian town of 107,000 to settle
the dispute, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda said.
   Strikers said Thursday they were satisfied with government
concessions that included better night-shift pay, said Victor
Ivanov, a member of the government commission negotiating with the
strikers.
   Strikes are becoming more common in the Soviet Union, where they
once were considered a Western phenomenon brought on by capitalist
exploitation of workers. Strikes used to be brutally repressed and
hushed up, but this year miners' strikes have generally ended within
days with government concessions.
   Night-shift workers at the Shevyakov mine began the strike
Monday, and it spread Tuesday to about 12,000 workers citywide,
Pravda said.
   The newspaper described the strikers' demands sympathetically,
including calls for round-the-clock cafeteria service, meat and
sausage for underground workers, free soap, one free towel per month
and a quilted jacket in winter.
   The strikers' 30 demands included economic independence for the
mines, extended vacations for underground workers and improved food
and housing, the labor daily Trud reported.
   Calls for greater financial independence of individual mines and
for increased night-shift pay were among those immediately granted,
said Alexander Kolmagorov, a worker at the Shevyakov mine.
   Requests for better food supplies and housing will take more
time, Kolmagorov said by telephone from the mine's strike
headquarters.
   ``People are back at work,'' Ivanov said. ``All their demands are
legal and are being decided. Most of them are satisfied, but some
will take time.''
   Trud said the demands resulted from long years of neglect by
authorities interested only in coal production and not in the
miners' needs.
   Mezhdurechensk, about 1,600 miles southwest of Moscow, produces
30 million tons of high-quality coal per year, Trud said.
   In a bitter letter Trud published in January, Mezhdurechensk
miners complained that 10,000 families are waiting for apartments;
hospitals and clinics are as crowded ``as anthills,'' with patients
waiting a week or more to see a doctor; and schools are overcrowded.
   The situation was aggravated when the ministry recently took away
two housing complexes from miners to accommodate other workers, Trud
said.
   A top Soviet official said in May that new legislation is being
drafted that will give unions the legal right to strike.
   Similar strikes were reported in March and April in the Urals
Mountain city of Vorkuta and the Siberian city of Norilsk but both
ended without incident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
