<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-DukakisVeto     07-13 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dukakis Veto,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Outlines $491 Million In Cuts; Says Tax Hike Unlikely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis cut nearly half a billion
dollars from the state budget Thursday in a move he said was made
necessary by ``miscalculations, mistakes and misinformation.''
   He said the needy would be hurt the most, and he renewed his call
for a tax increase.
   The spending cuts in the $12.3 billion budget include a $210
million reduction in aid to cities and towns, a freeze in welfare
benefits and a $62 million cut in public and higher education
spending.
   Dukakis, whose state's budget problems have called into question
the ``Massachusetts Miracle'' he touted during his Democratic run
for the presidency, had argued for six months for tax increases to
avoid such cuts.
   The House has given initial approval to a $744 million tax
increase, but that is a temporary, two-year hike that only pays
leftover bills from the fiscal year that ended June 30. The cuts
made by Dukakis are for the new fiscal year.
   The state constitution effectively requires a balanced budget.
   ``All of us in state government have arrived at this unhappy
moment through a combination of miscalculations, mistakes and
misinformation,'' Dukakis said.
   ``I'm disappointed in myself for not being more effective and
persuasive. I'm disappointed in the Legislature's failure to send me
a balanced budget. I'm disappointed in all of us who have let the
talkmasters and the columnists define our values, our commitment to
public service, our commitment to each other.''
   The mood was somber as Dukakis outlined the cuts before about 700
state employees, lobbyists and others who packed a Statehouse
auditorium.
   ``This state is bankrupt and somebody better realize it,''
Worcester Mayor Jordan Levy said afterward. ``The Democratic Party
is going to be finished business in Massachusetts.''
   Dukakis insisted the Legislature's budget understated expenses by
about $351 million and overestimated revenue by $140 million. He
used his line-item veto authority and his power to withhold funding
to cut the budget.
   Targets of cuts include human services; aid for the mentally ill;
environmental programs, and the state AIDS program.
   Of the $491 million in vetoes and ``conditional cuts'' that would
be restored if money becomes available, the $210 million local and
school aid reduction is most likely to generate controversy.
Communities depend on the state for about 40 percent of their
revenue for everything from schools to police and fire protection.
   Barbara Anderson, head of Citizens for Limited Taxation, said of
higher taxes: ``It isn't going to happen. There aren't going to be
any more taxes than they've already done.''
</TEXT>
