<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-PLO     07-13 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-PLO,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Secretary Meets With PLO Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's foreign secretary met with a Palestine
Liberation Organization official Thursday and urged the PLO to
follow a moderate line despite ``disappointing'' moves in Israel,
the Foreign Office reported.
   It said Sir Geoffrey Howe's 10-minute meeting with Bassam Abu
Sharif was the first between a British Cabinet officer and a senior
PLO official.
   Sharif told reporters afterward it was a ``very important
political meeting, especially at this delicate moment in the Middle
East, due to the decisions taken by the Likud party giving a blow to
peace efforts.''
   Last week, the right-wing Likud bloc of Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir set new Israeli conditions for elections in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. They are expected to make
Palestinian acceptance of the elections less likely.
   Israel's deputy foreign minister, Benyamin Netanyahu, said in a
television interview the Howe-Sharif meeting was ``a setback not
only for genuine peace in the Middle East, but ... for British
policy against terrorism.''
   Despite the its public renunciation of terrorism and recognition
of Israel's right to exist, he said, the PLO supports terrorist
activity and openly declares in the Middle East that it plans to
destroy the Jewish state.
   The Board of Deputies of British Jews said it had ``strongly
protested'' to Howe.
   Sharif was invited last week to confer with Minister of State
William Waldegrave, whom he last met in May. After 35 minutes with
Waldegrave, he was taken to see Howe.
   A Foreign Office spokesman said the purpose was for Howe ``to
encourage the PLO to stick to its moderate policy despite the
disappointing outcome of the Likud meeting and the rising tide of
violence in the occupied territories.''
   More than 550 Palestinians and 35 Israelis have been killed
during a 19-month-old uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank
and Gaza.
   Likud's new conditions for elections, which would choose
Palestinians to negotiate peace with Israel, demand that the
uprising end before they are held and specify that Palestinians in
Arab east Jerusalem cannot participate.
</TEXT>
