<FIRST>u w AM-SocialSecurity-Nominee     07-13 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security-Nominee,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Nominate Former Thornburgh Aide at Social Security, Source
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former aide to Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, Gwendolyn King, will soon be nominated by the White
House as head of the Social Security Administration, a source close
to the situation said Thursday.
   A news release announcing the nomination has been sent by the
White House to Paris, where President Bush flew Thursday for a
summit meeting, according to a source familiar with the release. The
source spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   If nominated by Bush and confirmed by the Senate, King would take
over an agency criticized by organized labor and by congressional
Democrats for cutting back from 80,000 to 65,000 employees during
the Reagan administration.
   She would also face questions of whether to continue to invest
the mounting Social Security surplus into government securities, or
channel funds into financially pressed domestic programs.
   Reached Thursday at the government relations firm of Gogol &amp;
Associates, where she is executive vice president, King said it
would be premature to comment. When told in April she was being
considered for the post, she told The Associated Press, ``I will be
pleased to serve wherever the president needs me.''
   Dorcas Hardy resigned as commissioner last month after lobbying
to keep her job in the face of congressional criticism and
indications that Bush wanted to replace her. She had worked for
Reagan on welfare issues when he was governor of California, and was
a health and human services assistant secretary before being named
to run Social Security in 1986.
   King, a former legislative aide to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., also
headed the Washington office of Thornburgh when he was Pennsylvania
governor.
</TEXT>
