<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 2104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     07-13 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Tells Party to Face Up to Complaints</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party officials who lack the gumption to
respond to the passionate demands and complaints of Soviet citizens
should quit, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said in a speech
reported Thursday.
   Gorbachev offered that blunt opinion to Leningrad Communist Party
leaders Wednesday just before they sacked their local party chief,
Yuri F. Solovyov, a candidate member of the ruling Politburo.
   ``Passions are boiling on the streets, but in many party
organizations there is silence,'' Gorbachev said in his speech,
which was released by the official news agency Tass Thursday. ``It
is necessary to quickly blast out this silence, this dangerous
silence!
   ``It is necessary to face life, to go into life. Whoever doesn't
have the strength, whoever cannot find his place, let him leave,''
Gorbachev said. ``Before anything else, we must think of the party,
of perestroika, of socialism.''
   Perestroika, or restructuring, is Gorbachev's campaign to
overhaul Soviet society and the economy.
   Although Gorbachev never mentioned Solovyov by name, he was
clearly referring to him. When Soviet election law was reformed to
allow multiple candidates, Solovyov and other Leningrad leaders
engineered their parliamentary races to run unopposed. Then they
suffered humiliating defeats when angry citizens crossed their names
off ballots, denying them the required 50 percent approval.
   Solovyov also ignored calls for his resignation and the issues
raised during the election campaign, which brought thousands of
Leningraders into the streets for public meetings.
   In his speech, Gorbachev charged that the Leningrad regional
party committee failed to pay attention to the roots of people's
complaints, in particular their demand for practical results from
perestroika.
   The party, he indicated, must defend itself through its actions.
   As an example, he cited local authorities for failing to improve
a particular factory's working conditions. He said the conditions
were like those facing laborers in the time of Peter the Great, who
founded Leningrad in 1703.
   ``They've been talking about ventilation for two years, and they
cannot put it right. The dust is terrible, the conditions
unbearable. It's shameful!
   ``Well, comrades, for this, you need billions?'' Gorbachev asked
rhetorically.
   ``So people look at this and say, `Perestroika has been going on
for four years, and nothing has changed. This is where we get
irritation, indignation and criticism,'' he said. ``Where is their
(official) union? Where is their party organization?''
   Local authorities often blame Moscow for failing to solve purely
local problems ``which the central government doesn't handle, and
shouldn't handle,'' he said.
   Gorbachev also told his audience not to fear new ideas _ a
failing he had previously found in Solovyov. In April, Gorbachev
reprimanded the Leningrad party chief for complaining that the party
was becoming ``a discussion club.''
   The current period of change, Gorbachev said Wednesday, brings
forth diverse opinions, ``which many people perceive as a threat to
what we have achieved, as a threat to perestroika. Comrades, we must
preserve our strength of spirit, our tolerance, our realism in
evaluating the progress of perestroika, in predictions for the
future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
