<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Police     07-13 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Police,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Chairman Attacks Administration's Drug War As `Phony'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a Senate narcotics
subcommittee, attacking the anti-drug campaigns of the Reagan and
Bush administrations as ``phony,'' proposed a $120 million program
Thursday to help local police establish and expand drug intelligence
units.
   Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., introduced legislation to provide
direct aid to local police departments for computers, electronic
intelligence-gathering equipment and added personnel for anti-drug
task forces.
   ``It's time we gave police officers .... the kind of support they
deserve,'' Kerry said at a news conference. ``We would be expanding
the kind of police work which prevents drug-related crime from
happening in the first place.''
   The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations narcotics
subcommittee said $63 million would go to state governments _ at
least $500,000 to each state _ for drug intelligence units and
equipment. About two-fifths of that money would be passed on to
cities with fewer than 100,000 people.
   The rest of the money, $57 million, would go directly from the
Justice Department to big cities.
   Kerry said the Drug Intelligence Act would ``provide an extra
boost to local police departments at a time when their budgets are
the tightest but their needs in fighting a real war on drugs are the
greatest.''
   ``Police drug intelligence units that already exist in major
cities are important components in the war on drugs,'' he said.
``But even where these units exist, they need upgrading and more
equipment.''
   Kerry, deriding the anti-drug efforts of Republican
administrations through the 1980s, said the Bush administration has
spent only $500 million of the $2.7 billion Congress allocated last
year for the government's anti-drug effort.
   ``We don't have a real war on drugs today,'' Kerry said.
``They're talking out of both sides of their mouth. ... It's phony.''
</TEXT>
