<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Kadar     07-13 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Kadar,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Mourn Former Communist Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Hungarians on
Thursday mourned longtime Communist Party leader Janos Kadar, who
died last week more than a year after being eased from power by
reformers.
   ``We came to thank him for what he did for us and the Hungarian
people,'' said Viktor Segre, who said he and his wife, Eva, waited
more than three hours to view Kadar's red and black shrouded casket
lying in state at the Central Committee headquarters in Budapest.
   Kadar, 77, died on July 6. He is to be buried Friday in a state
ceremony attended by Hungary's new leadership and delegations from
the Warsaw Pact.
   On Thursday, mourners, many weeping and carrying flowers,
gathered in the late afternoon to pay their respects to Kadar, who
took power as Soviet troops crushed the 1956 anti-Stalinist uprising.
   In the 32 years before he was ousted by a new generation of
reformers in 1988, Kadar was conciliatory or ruthless by turns as he
searched for consensus in party ranks.
   But Kadar gained respect at home and abroad by the 1970s after
launching economic reforms and ushering in a new spirit of tolerance
that was in stark contrast to the early years of his rule and many
neighboring communist countries.
   Kadar's legacy of stability and reform efforts appeared to have
drawn many to the austere center of communist power in Hungary,
bedecked on Thursday with wreaths and floral displays in his memory.
   ``He gave us peace and a sense of security,'' said Eva Segre.
``He got the country going again after 1956 and won international
respect for Hungary.''
   ``Comrade Kadar was a great man,'' said an elderly woman, who
asked not to be identified. She said she waited four hours and
``would have waited longer if I had to.''
   The line of those waiting to file through the hushed gallery of
the Central Committee building stretched more than four city blocks.
Hundreds clutched small bouquets of carnations and roses and many
carried large wreaths.
   In May 1988, Kadar lost his post as party general secretary. A
year later, he was removed as honorary party chairman and stripped
of his membership in the policy-setting Central Committee, which
criticized him for mistakes during his long rule.
   Although he ushered in economic reforms in the late 1960s and
early 1970s, Kadar was increasingly blamed for an economic decline
after the reforms stalled. Many in the party leadership viewed him
as an obstacle to renewal in the country.
   The Communist Party's re-evaluation of the 1956 uprising as a
popular revolt and the rehabilitation of Imre Nagy, the prime
minister who led it, eroded the legitimacy of Kadar's rule for many.
   Nagy was executed in 1958 and was buried in an unmarked grave.
His remains were reburied in an elaborate ceremony June 16 that was
attended by hundreds of thousands of Hungarians.
   Under the leadership of a new generation of reformers, Hungary
has embarked on an ambitious program of economic and political
reforms designed to move the nation toward a market economy and
closer ties to the West.
</TEXT>
