<FIRST>r w AM-Dodd-LatinAmerica     07-13 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dodd-Latin America,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Elections Will Be Fair: Dodd</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Chris Dodd, D-Conn., said Thursday that
Nicaragua's national elections next year will be fair and free and
that its Sandinista government deserves some credit for that from
the Bush administration.
   Dodd, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
Latin America, also said he expects significant progress in the
Latin American peace process at the Aug. 7 meeting of the region's
presidents.
   Dodd returned early this week from a visit to the region, and
told a news conference the Bush administration should be encouraging
the process by rewarding the Sandinista government for its progress.
   The administration, he said, has characterized its policy toward
Nicaragua as one of ``carrots and sticks,'' rewards when progress is
made toward democratic reforms and sanctions when there are reverses.
   ``At this point, there have been no carrots offered,'' Dodd said.
``You almost get the sense that the administration is disappointed
that the Nicaraguans have made progress in some areas.''
   Asked for an example of positive steps taken by the Sandinistas,
Dodd cited the provisions made for election observers to be present
in the country for a full six months before the balloting and for
impromtu political rallies.
   ``On paper it doesn't look bad,'' he said. ``I can see these
words come back to haunt me in 10 months. But on paper, it's not
bad.''
   On another subject, Dodd sharply criticized the Organization of
American States for taking no action against Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, Panama's military ruler, who retained power in May after
nullifying the results of presidential elections.
   ``If the OAS cannot be supportive on Noriega, I don't think we
can get together on anything,'' Dodd said.
</TEXT>
