<FIRST>u a AM-NursesStrike     07-13 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nurses Strike,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurses Strike Puts Hospital Group at One-Fifth Patient Load</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patients of the state's largest hospital company
had to cross picket lines to see their doctors Thursday as 1,300
nurses began striking for higher wages and guaranteed hours.
   The strike left Group Health Cooperative of Puget Sound with a
non-union staff capable of handling only one-fifth of the normal
patient load at its three hospitals.
   About 130 patients were moved to other hospitals and 72 remained,
said Phil Nudelman, the health maintenance organization's executive
vice president and chief operating officer.
   Negotiations broke off shortly after midnight Thursday, and
picketing began at 6 a.m. at Group Health hospitals and clinics in
five Puget Sound counties that include this city and Tacoma.
   Picket lines were up at all Group Health centers except its
specialty medical center, which provides urology, oncology, internal
medicine and other services, Sosne said.
   The cooperative also runs 23 family medical centers and four
specialty medical centers. All the centers will be open and staffed
by physicians and other staff, Nudelman said.
   Group Health began hiring non-union nurses and preparing to lay
off non-nursing staff in preparation for what's expected to be a
long strike, Nudelman said. The layoffs were intended to save money.
   Diane Sosne, president of Local 1199 of the National Union and
Health Care Employees, said the talks broke off because Group Health
refused to compromise on key issues, particularly staffing decisions.
   Nudelman said the cooperative's latest offer was still on the
table, and that a phone call was all that was needed to reopen talks.
   ``Our wage and benefit package would make Group Health nurses the
best paid in the state of Washington,'' he said. ``It would also
give our nurses significant input into decision-making that directly
affects their workplace.'' The latest contract offer would boost
yearly pay for a first-year nurse to $27,706 from $23,000, based on
a 40-hour work week. A nurse with 15 years' experience would earn
about $41,000, up from $33,000.
   The nurses were seeking raises of 16 percent in the first year
and 14 percent in the second. Management's offer amounts to 23.5
percent over two years.
   Also at issue in the talks is the company's practice of cutting
nurses' hours when there are few patients in the hospital. The
nurses are seeking contract provisions to protect their income.
   The company, a health maintenance organization, has about 370,000
members.
   An HMO is a type of medical insurance plan that offers members
treatment for a fixed monthly payment, rather than reimbursing them
on a per-visit basis.
</TEXT>
