<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0703 07-13 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0703,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister Says Indian Troops Will Be Treated As Occupation Army</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with moderate Tamil killed, strike
over. No pickup.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE _ This report was submitted to a government</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   censor, who made significant changes.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lankan soldiers and police will
take charge of law and order from Indian troops in the northeast,
who then will be treated as an occupational army, Foreign Minister
Ranjan Wijeratne said Thursday.
   He said the takeover will occur July 29, the deadline President
Ranasinghe Premadasa set for the pullout of 40,000 Indian troops
deployed in Sri Lanka. India is refusing to withdraw them.
   A moderate Tamil leader who supported the deployment of Indian
soldiers in Sri Lanka and a party colleague were killed in a Colombo
home Thursday, officials said.
   In his comments Thursday, Wijeratne said President Ranasinghe
Premadasa would stick to the pullout deadline.
   ``Sri Lankan army and police will come out of their barracks to
maintain law and order in the north and east, because after July 29
the Indian troops will be treated as an occupational army,''
Wijeratne said.
   On Wednesday, Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi said a pullout
of the troops could only be decided through negotiations and had to
be accompanied by increasing powers for the Tamil government in the
Northeastern Province. The message was tantamount to refusing to
withdraw the troops by Premadasa's deadline.
   In a reply Thursday, Premadasa said military action by the Indian
armed forces was ``unnecessary and prejudicial to a settlement by
discussion and negotiation.''
   He said his government was willing to hold talks on the issue but
the pullout and political issue were ``totally unconnected.''
   Indian soldiers were deployed in Sri Lanka's Tamil-dominated
north and east on July 29, 1987, under an agreement between the two
countries. The Indian-mediated accord was aimed at ending a
rebellion by Tamil insurgents.
   The rebels were to give up their weapons in exchange for limited
autonomy in regions where they dominated and Indian soldiers were to
ensure peace.
   But the peace plan fell apart after the largest rebel group, the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, backed out and began fighting the
Indians. Smaller Tamil groups surrendered and were voted to power in
the province's local elections last year but now accuse the
government of not giving them enough power.
   The moderate Tamil leader who was killed was identified by an
Information Department official as Appapillai Amirthalingam, the
62-year-old leader of the Tamil United Liberation Front. The
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said another party
member was also killed and three people were injured.
   In New Delhi, the United News of India news agency said
Amirthalingam and his colleague were killed by three gunmen
belonging to the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam. The three gunmen
were later shot and killed by Amirthalingam's bodyguards, the news
agency said.
   India and Sri Lanka exchanged sharply worded letters after
Premadasa asked India on June 1 to pull out its soldiers by the
second anniversary of the agreement. The request followed talks in
May between his government and the Tamil Tigers, the first direct
contact between the two sides since the insurgency began in 1983.
   Under the 1987 agreement, Indian soldiers took over law and order
in the north and east and Sri Lankan troops were confined to their
barracks.
   India became involved in the troubles of the island nation off
its southern coast because of the sympathies of its own 60 million
Tamils for the rebel cause. Sri Lankan Tamils launched a war for a
separate nation complaining of discrimination by the majority
Sinhalese community.
   The predominantly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people, and the Buddhist Sinhalese make up 75 percent.
   Also Thursday, officials announced that more than 40,000 public
transport workers ended a crippling monthlong strike after reaching
a wage agreement with the government.
   Bus drivers, clerks and mechanics of the state-owned transport
company walked off their jobs on June 12, demanding higher wages.
But the government said the strike was sponsored by Sinhalese
militants using the wage issue to fuel civil unrest.
   The militants say the government has been too soft on the Tamils.
   Transport Minister Wijepala Mendis said in a statement that the
government would increase workers' monthly salaries by $5.60 and
give monthly back pay of $1.50 retroactive to January 1982.
</TEXT>
