<FIRST>u w AM-Immigration 2ndLd-Writethru a0752 07-13 0863</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immigration, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0752,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Immigration Overhaul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS day in lede to Thursday, ADDS two grafs listing opponents
and those not voting, which will serve in lieu of a roll call.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Thursday approved an overhaul of
the immigration system that would limit new arrivals to 630,000 in
each of the next three years and expand the number coming from
Western Europe.
   ``This bill not only carries forward and increases the present
emphasis on family reunification, it also opens opportunities for
new immigrants with new skills,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., one of the bill's sponsors.
   The bill, approved 81-17 after two days of debate, now goes to
the House. It was originally designed to cap immigration at 600,000
in each of the next three years but was expanded by 30,000 visas
before final passage.
   The ceiling represents 136,000 more visas than were issued in
1988, but but critics say the bill still could reduce visas for all
but the closest relatives of American citizens and permanent
residents of the United States.
   The Senate approved a similar bill in 1988 but it died in the
House.
   The measure now goes to the House with Kennedy and the measure's
co-sponsor, Sen. Alan K. Simpson, R-Wyo., saying they are optimistic
about the prospects this year.
   Lawmakers voted 78-21 to expand the cap by 30,000 visas a year
following an emotional appeal from Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who
recalled how his father fled ``the boot of the czar'' in 1911 and
arrived in America ``with no rubles in his pocket. He had to come
steerage.''
   ``There is nothing magic to me about the number 600,000,''
Specter said.
   But senators fought back 52-46 a move by Sen. Rudy Boschwitz,
R-Minn., to expand by 40,000 the number of brothers and sisters of
American citizens that would be allowed into the country annually.
   ``My heart is on the side of what Sen. Boschwitz is doing,'' Sen.
Paul Simon, D-Ill., said. But he added that ``there is a saturation
point with the American public and I want to be prudent as we move
ahead.''
   Simpson said it was ``time to face the unfortunate but hideously
cold reality that there are many more people who want to come here
than there is room or intent to accommodate them.''
   Following intense floor skirmishing, the Senate did approve an
amendment from Sen. Richard C. Shelby, D-Ala., that would force the
Census Bureau to halt its practice of including illegal aliens in
its official count.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said that under the current system
``states like California would gain a (congressional) seat at North
Carolina's expense'' because their populations are swollen with
illegal aliens.
   Kennedy called the amendment ``flatly unconstitutional,'' but
lawmakers refused 58-41 to kill it and eventually adopted it on a
voice vote.
   The legislation would reserve 120,000 visas annually for those
entering on a basis other than family ties.
   That category includes 54,000 visas subject to a point system
giving credit for those with special skills needed by American
industry but who do not have employers ready to sponsor them.
   The Senate Judiciary Committee voted 12-2 to delete the provision
that would provide extra points to individuals who speak English.
Simpson appealed to the Senate in vain to restore the point system
but lawmakers rejected the idea, 56-43.
   ``English is the language of success,'' he declared. He said
those who are unable to understand English will have a tough time
obtaining jobs and urged lawmakers not to be swayed by sentimental
portrayals as immigrants as the heart and soul of the American dream.
   ``The heart and soul disappears when you can't get work,'' he
said.
   Simon, however, quoted a news clipping that said 13 of the 16
valedictorians in Boston's publish high schools this year were born
in foreign countries and the majority apparently did not have
English for a mother tongue.
   Simpson expressed frustration that the sentiment-tinged debate
appeared to be going against him.
   ``You have snorted and ripped and rolled around in it and you
have just given birth to a mouse,'' he declared.
   Meanwhile, the House approved, 358-44, and sent to the Senate
separate legislation to ease immigration of certain Soviet and
Southeast Asian refugees.
   It would temporarily re-establish the legal status of Soviet Jews
and evangelican Christians as well as certain categories of
Vietnamese, Laotians and Cambodians as persecuted, without
individuals having to prove it in their own cases. That would aid
them in obtaining standing as refugees.
   The measure is opposed by the Bush administration, which contends
it unnecessarily establishes special preferences for certain
refugees and makes it more difficult to administer the U.S. refugee
program fairly.
   Those voting against the measure were Sens. John Breaux, D-La.;
Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.; Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.; Kent Conrad, D-N.D.;
Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; J. James Exon Jr., D-Neb., Wendell Ford,
D-Ky.; Albert Gore, D-Tenn.; Howell Heflin, D-Ala.; Jesse Helms,
R-N.C.; Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C.; Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii; Barbara
Mikulski, D-Md.; Harry Reid, D-Nev.; Warren Rudman, R-N.H.; Shelby,
and Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
   Not voting were Sens. James Jeffords, R-N.H., and Spark
Matsunaga, D-Fla.
</TEXT>
