<FIRST>r a AM-FloridaGuns     07-13 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Guns,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Kills Sister Hours after Gun Bill Signed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baby died Thursday after being shot by
her 6-year-old sister hours after Gov. Bob Martinez signed a bill to
protect children from accidental shootings in the home.
   Nine-month-old Enereida Suarez of Tampa was the fourth Florida
child killed this summer in an accidental shooting.
   She was shot late Wednesday after her sister, Llasmin, found a
.38-caliber revolver lying under a towel on their parents' bed,
police said.
   Martinez was horrified by the news, said his press secretary,
Jack Peck.
   ``It just underscores the whole problem, when a child is shot
just hours after he signs a bill to stop these things from
happening,'' Peck said.
   Although the law signed by Martinez doesn't take effect until
Oct. 1, Tampa authorities could bring charges under existing laws.
   ``We will gather all the information and turn it over to the
state attorney's office for review under the culpable negligence
statute,'' said police spokesman Steve Cole.
   Under the new law, no grieving parent of an injured or fatally
wounded child shot by another member of the family could be arrested
until seven days after the incident.
   The law provides for adults to be charged with a felony,
punishable by up to five years in prison and a $5,000 fine, if a
child shoots himself or another because of the owner's carelessness.
   If a minor threatens someone with the gun or displays it in
public, the gun owner faces a misdemeanor charge and up to 60 days
in jail and a $500 fine.
   The law requires gun owners to prevent loaded weapons kept in
homes and businesses from falling into the hands of children 15 and
younger by using such precautions as trigger locks or keeping a
weapon in a locked box.
   Three children died in early June in similar household shootings,
inspiring lawmakers to push for the legislation during a special
session intended to deal with other issues last month.
</TEXT>
