<HEAD>Thunderstorms Boom Over Plains, Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell in much of the eastern two-thirds of the nation
Thursday, including storms that caused flooding in the Philadelphia
area and a thunderstorm that unleashed 81-mph winds in Georgia.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms stretched from western
portions of the central Plains to central Oklahoma, and from eastern
Texas to the central Gulf Coast states, Florida and southern Georgia.
   Rain and a few thunderstorms lingered in eastern North Carolina,
in rain-soaked areas of West Virginia and the mid-Atlantic states
and in portions of the Rockies.
   The Philadelphia area received more than 2 inches of rain,
causing minor flooding in low-lying areas. In northwestern West
Virginia, more than 1{ inches of rain fell in three hours in parts
of Calhoun County, where some roads were closed by high water.
   A severe thunderstorm with wind gusts to 81 mph dumped 1{ inches
of rain on Albany, Ga., within 40 minutes Thursday afternoon. Strong
thunderstorm winds snapped tree limbs at Abbeyville, Ala., where 1{
inches fell within an hour.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 1} inches at Polk Mountain, W.VA., and about 1{ inches in
New Jersey at Wrightstown, McGuire Air Force Base and Lakehurst
Naval Air Station.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees in Marysville, Calif., to 110 degrees in Palm Springs,
Calif. The low in the Lower 48 states Thursday was 34 degrees in
Burney, Calif.
   The forecast for Friday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the northern and coastal Rockies to the Great
Plains, from the Gulf Coast states to Florida, and along sections of
the Eastern Seaboard, with storms most numerous over Nebraska, South
Dakota and northeast Wyoming and from the central Gulf Coast to
northern Florida.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 70s from the Great Lakes
region to the upper Ohio Valley and the northern Atlantic Coast, in
Montana and Wyoming, and along the Pacific Coast; a few 100-degree
readings along the Rio Grande Valley of Texas and in inland valleys
of California; 100 to 115 degrees in the desert Southwest and in the
80s and 90s elsewhere.
