<HEAD>Execution Appeal Denied in Alabama Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday twice refused to
block the execution of Alabama death-row inmate Horace Franklin
Dunkins Jr.
   Dunkins, 28, described in court papers as mildly retarded, was
convicted of a 1980 rape and murder in Warrior, Ala.. He was
scheduled to be executed early Friday morning.
   Late in the afternoon, the high court voted 7-2 to deny a stay of
execution. Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood Marshall, who
oppose the death penalty in all circumstances, voted to spare
Dunkins.
   At 8:25 p.m., by an identical vote, the court denied a second
application for a stay.
