<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 2240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     07-13 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guards Kill 10 Who Tried to Kill Leftist Councilman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen stormed a leftist city
councilman's house in Medellin and tried to assassinate him
Thursday, but his bodyguards killed 10 of the attackers, including
two police officers, the national police said.
   Elsewhere, leftist guerrillas kidnapped a federal congressman and
blew up the country's biggest oil pipeline for the 25th time this
year.
   The 10 slain attackers had tried to kill councilman Gonzalo
Alvarez Henao in Medellin, where drug traffickers have been
financing right-wing death squads to exterminate members of a
leftist party.
   Alvarez is the leader in Medellin of the Patriotic Union party,
organized six years ago with the support of leftist guerrillas.
   Right-wing death squads have killed 729 members of the Patriotic
Union in the last four years.
   Alvarez was attacked twice, first while he was in his car shortly
before midnight Wednesday, police Col. Antonio Sanchez Vargas said
at a news conference in Medellin.
   Alvarez's guards held off the attackers while the councilman and
other guards got away, Vargas said.
   Then, shortly after midnight, gunmen stormed the councilman's
house, and his guards killed 10 attackers, Vargas said.
   ``Unfortunately, among the dead attackers we found two policemen
who had broken their vows to serve society,'' Vargas said.
   Medellin, a city of 2 million people in northwest Colombia, is
the the headquarters for Colombia's biggest drug traffickers. The
traffickers began killing leftists after guerrillas kidnapped and
held for ransom members of some of the traffickers' families.
   Traffickers and guerrillas also are at war because the guerrillas
demand that the drug traffickers pay for having their
cocaine-processing laboratories in rebel controlled areas.
   The congressman kidnapped by guerrillas was Alfonso Campo Soto,
according to the national police in the northwest state of Cesar. He
was kidnapped Thursday in Cesar state near his ranch, the police
said.
   Police blamed the National Liberation Army, which has abducted 54
persons this year, including congressmen, mayors, city councilmen,
policemen and news reporters.
   The police quoted Campo's family as saying that the guerrillas
told them that Campo would be released soon.
   Most of the people who have been kidnapped by the guerrillas, of
the National Liberation Army, have been released after being
lectured on the guerrillas' political objectives.
   The National Liberation Army also blew up the country's main oil
pipeline Thursday for the 25th time this year, the national police
said.
   The attack again forced suspension of the pumping of 220,000
barrels of oil a day from the big Canon Limon field in northeast
Colombia.
   Colombia's oil production has plunged to 312,000 barrels a day
from 420,000 barrels a day in January because of the guerrilla
attacks, the state oil company Ecopetrol said last week.
   The pipeline runs 500 miles from the Cano Limon field to the
Caribbean port of Covenas. Cano Limon is operated jointly by
Occidental Petroleum, Royal Dutch Shell and Ecopetrol.
   The National Liberation Army wants foreign oil companies out of
Colombia.
   In another development, the national police said antinarcotics
police arrested a captain and two lieutenants of the national police
on suspicion of drug trafficking.
   The three police officers were arrested Wednesday as they landed
in a helicopter in the southwest state of Valle, the police said.
The police had $259,000 in U.S. currency with them, the police said.
   The chief of the national police, Gen. Miguel Gomez Padilla,
began raids on drug laboratories two hours after taking over in
January from a general who was fired by President Virgilio Barco for
allegedly trafficking in cocaine.
   Gomez has fired more than 1,000 policemen for their associations
with known drug traffickers or other criminals.
</TEXT>
