<FIRST>r w AM-DroughtRelief     07-13 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Relief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Goes to Work On Drought Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators from the South and upper Midwest
pressed Thursday to get aid for weather-damaged crops in their
states included in drought-relief legislation lawmakers are rushing
to finish this summer.
   ``We've got a comprehensive problem that's going to take a
comprehensive approach,'' Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told fellow
members of the Senate Agriculture Committee. ``The loss is great ...
and the time is short.''
   The Bush administration and Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of
Kansas have been backing off their insistence that drought relief be
limited to winter wheat farmers. However, it is uncertain whether
enough money would be available to cover losses of other crops.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter had said he would recommend
President Bush veto a drought relief package approved by the House
that would cover more than 500 crops and cost more than $900 million.
   However, recent flooding has severely damaged crops such as
cotton across the South, and North Dakota Gov. George Sinner this
week declared his entire state a disaster area because of hot, dry
weather.
   Soybean and cotton crops are rated fair to poor in Arkansas,
Mississippi and Louisiana primarily because of heavy rains. Crops
also have been hurt in Alabama, Georgia, North Carolina and South
Carolina, nine southern senators said in a letter Thursday to
Yeutter.
   Parts of Louisiana have received up to 60 inches of rain, said
Sen. John Breaux, D-La.
   The committee is scheduled to vote on a drought-relief bill next
week that lawmakers hope to get approved by Congress before the
August recess.
   Dole said Yeutter could be authorized to provide aid to other
crops where farmers can demonstrate weather-related losses.
   However, he argued that the legislation should first take care of
winter wheat farmers, who already have lost much of their crop.
   ``What we need to figure out in this committee, hopefully on a
bipartisan basis, is how we're going to deal with areas that have a
demonstrated loss and how we're going to find the money,'' Dole said.
   Winter wheat farmers deserve first crack at drought relief
because most of the money the government is saving in the farm
program this year is because of the lower wheat production, Dole
said.
   The Agriculture Department estimated the government would save
$950 million in farm program payments to winter wheat growers
because wheat prices are high. The Congressional Budget Office has
said overall savings to the farm program from wheat and other crops
this year could run as high as $1.5 billion.
</TEXT>
