<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 2119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-StealthTest     07-13 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Test,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>B-2 Bomber Passes Last Ground Test, Ready for Flight Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>With B-2 Bomber, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALMDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B-2 stealth bomber sped down a runway
Thursday, successfully completing its final ground test and setting
the stage for a first flight that could come as early as Saturday,
an Air Force general said.
   The sleek, bat-winged bomber raced down the runway at Air Force
Plant 42, achieving a top speed of 75 mph, said Brig. Gen. Richard
Scofield, director of the B-2 program.
   Although Scofield said the bomber's long-delayed first flight
could come Saturday, he cautioned that the Air Force is being
prudent and will not be rushed despite political controversy
harrying the bomber's progress toward full production.
   ``The plane will fly when it is ready,'' he said.
   However, Scofield said that B-2 builder Northrop Corp. and Air
Force officials believe they have all the data they need to send the
bomber airborne.
   The radar-evading bomber was tested in high winds that kicked up
clouds of dust on the 11,000-foot runway at the Air Force's prime
research and development plant in the Mojave Desert.
   During the test, the bomber's nose wheel lifted up into the air,
a procedure that was anticipated, Scofield said.
   ``It was not an aborted takeoff,'' he said.
   The bomber rolled to the end of the runway and one of its tires
became stuck in soft asphalt, making it necessary to tow it back to
its hangar.
   However, Scofield said everything went perfectly in conducting
the test as far as the Air Force was concerned.
   No first flight is anticipated Friday because the crew and the
pilots needed rest, the general said.
   The flying wing was decked out with orange highlights that were
used to cover sensors and test equipment.
   On Monday, the gray bomber built from composite materials rather
than metal conducted slow-speed tests on the ground, achieving a
speed of approximately 102 mph.
   In Washington on Thursday, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney pleaded
with Congress not to ``nickel and dime to death'' the B-2, saying
the stealth bomber is essential for U.S. capability to ``penetrate
improving Soviet air defenses.''
   Testifying before the House Armed Services Committee, Cheney
urged lawmakers to try to overcome ``sticker shock'' at the $500
million to $750 million price for each plane and to restore some
$800 million the panel cut from the B-2 budget last month.
   Lawmakers warned Air Force officials earlier this week that the
B-2 faces a tough uphill fight in Congress despite the warplane's
strategic importance.
   ``Put it in perspective or there's a real possibility that the
B-2 will become a museum piece,'' Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman
of the House Armed Services Committee, told Air Force officials at
the start of a hearing.
   The Air Force campaign comes amid growing opposition to the
bomber, which recent estimates indicate would be the most expensive
aircraft in history.
   The Pentagon announced last week the first flight tests of the
bomber, which are 18 months behind schedule, would be held during
the next two weeks.
   The Pentagon is proposing a $4.7 billion budget in fiscal 1990
for the B-2.
   The plane will cost about $24 billion over a three-year peak
period beginning in fiscal 1992, according to Defense Department
figures.
   The department has invested about $22.4 billion in the plane so
far.
</TEXT>
