<FIRST>r w AM-Tongass 1stLd-Writethru   07-13 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tongass, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0705,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Wants to End Tongass Forest Timber Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Changes references to ``lumber'' to timber throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved environmentalist-backed
legislation Thursday that would cancel 50-year deals under which two
timber companies have been harvesting trees from Tongass National
Forest at bargain basement prices.
   The legislation, which passed 356-60, also establishes more
wilderness areas in the forest in southeastern Alaska and creates
buffer zones around many streams and tributaries to protect fish
from logging operations.
   The timber contracts have been a ``raid on the taxpayers,'' said
Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., who led debate in favor of the bill.
``We say get your hands out of our pockets.''
   ``The timber companies keep the bureaucrats employed and the
bureaucrats keep the timber companies wallowing in federal
subsidies,'' said Miller.
   ``I'm terribly disappointed,'' said Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, who
led the fight against the bill in the name of jobs for his state's
residents. ``It goes to show the influence of the environmentalist
point of view.''
   The legislation is directed at Louisiana Pacific-Ketchikan and
Alaska Pulp Co., a Japanese firm, and Young said 6,000 jobs could be
lost if the companies go out of business.
   Proponents of the bill, however, said it throws the door open to
competition from independent timber companies, owned by Alaskans,
which could create more jobs for the state population.
   ``If we cancel these contracts, it doesn't drive the timber
industry out of Alaska,'' said Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., co-sponsor of
the bill. ``It simply puts these companies on same footing as other
companies.''
   Young, Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper and many members of Congress,
including Agriculture Committee Chairman Kika de la Garza, D-Texas,
favored a version of the bill that would have called for
renegotiation rather than cancellation of the timber contracts. The
Agriculture Committee oversees the Forest Service, which is part of
the Agriculture Department.
   But that version, offered as an amendment, failed on a 269-144
vote.
   The bill now goes to the Senate, where Young said he expected an
outcome more to his liking. If the legislation is not changed, it
will be vetoed by President Bush, said Young.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter has said he would recommend
a veto of legislation that called for termination of the contracts.
   The House bill eliminates the $40 million that now goes annually
for such activities as road-building to aid the timber companies in
Tongass and requires an amount to be set each year in the federal
budget. Proponents said that could save the government $205 million
over the next five years.
   It also would end the requirement that the government make 4.5
billion board feet of the forest's timber available each decade.
   The bill would designate 23 areas as wilderness, barring timber
harvesting and development on 1.8 million acres. The legislation
also would ban logging within 100 feet of salmon streams.
   In an effort to establish a stable economy in southeast Alaska,
Congress in 1947 authorized the Forest Service to later sign the
unprecedented 50-year contracts with timber companies. The contracts
with the two firms expire in 2004 and 2011.
   The forest is the size of West Virginia and Delaware combined and
stretches over most of Alaska's 500-mile long panhandle.
   It's one of the few remaining temperate rain forests, with an
annual precipitation of averaging 150 inches. It and the Olympic
National Park in Washington are the last remnants of a rain forest
that used to stretch from northern California to Alaska.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
