<FIRST>r a AM-BuggedPoliticans     07-13 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bugged Politicans,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Busboy Finds FBI Camera in Restaurant Favored by Politicians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A busboy who found a video camera and wire hidden
in a booth at an eatery near City Hall has blown the cover on an
apparent federal corruption probe, the restaurant's lawyer said
Thursday.
   Owners of Counselors Row Restaurant, a spot popular with
lawmakers and others with clout, were ``shocked, outraged and
extremely upset that this type of conduct exists in the United
States,'' said restaurant attorney Nicholas M. Spina.
   ``The FBI planted the listening devices, and they were discovered
by one of our busboys,'' Spina said.
   The FBI also tapped a telephone on a pedestal next to a table
often used by influential politicians, the Chicago Tribune reported,
quoting unidentified sources.
   The sophisticated, wide-angle camera with a small lens was found
Friday hidden in the base of a booth, Spina said.
   FBI spokesman Bob Long declined to comment on whether the FBI was
involved, as did U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas. The federal prosecutor
added that ``Counselors Row is not the target of any investigation.''
   Restaurant co-owner George Borovilos said that after he talked to
the FBI Tuesday, agents came to the establishment and removed the
camera. They left behind a connecting wire that ran under a seat
cushion, through a concrete wall and down into the basement of the
building, Borovilos said.
   Spina said Gary Shapiro, the federal prosecutor in charge of
organized crime investigations in Chicago, confirmed that he had
authorized planting the device.
   Shapiro has refused to comment on the case.
   A judge approved the installation of the surveillance equipment
and it was placed in the restaurant without the owners' consent,
apparently on a weekend when the place was closed, Spina said.
   ``We are awaiting word from Valukas' office to see if they'll
agree to make the sealed court order a public one,'' Spina said
Thursday.
   Spina said the camera was pointed at a table often used by
Alderman Fred Roti and Democratic ward Committeeman John D'Arco,
among other local politicians.
   Roti said in a news release, ``There is no reason for me to be
investigated, and no reason to believe that I am being
investigated.''
   He added in an interview broadcast by WGN-TV Thursday, ``I don't
like it. I'm sure a lot of other people don't like it. But whether
we like it or not, they have court jurisdiction and the right to do
it, so being angry is meaningless to me.''
   The telephone rang unanswered at D'Arco's office Thursday.
   Alderman Bernard Stone told WGN, ``It's an open restaurant. It's
an open table. When we leave at 9 o'clock, God knows who sits here.''
   Alderman Richard Mell, who also frequents the table or ones
nearby, said, ``I have no problem with (the bugs). Is it true? It
looks like a very interesting story.''
</TEXT>
