<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0697 07-13 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban War Hero, Three Others Executed By Firing Squad At Dawn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS two grafs for 11th pvs to ADD quote from U.S. official;
pickup graf 12 pvs `The investigation...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A war hero who fought with Fidel Castro in
Cuba's revolution was executed by firing squad at dawn Thursday with
three other officers for smuggling tons of drugs into the United
States, the official Cuban news agency said.
   The drug scandal has stunned and embarrassed Castro and his
communist government, which for years denied U.S. accusations that
Cuba was being used to smuggle cocaine and marijuana to the United
States.
   In a brief dispatch monitored in Mexico City, the Cuban news
agency Prensa Latina said the sentences against Maj. Gen. Arnaldo
Ochoa, Col. Antonio de la Guardia Font, Maj. Amado Padron and Capt.
Jorge Martinez had been carried out.
   Ochoa was a trusted aide to President Castro, commanding Cuban
forces in Ethiopia and Angola and heading a Cuban military mission
to Nicaragua.
   The news agency noted that the four men, along with 10 other
officers, were convicted by a summary court-martial and that the
deliberations on their appeal were broadcast to the Cuban nation.
   Castro, who long rejected U.S. drug smuggling accusations as a
plot to defame Cuba, said Sunday the scandal had done immense
internal damage and eroded Cuba's international image.
   He called the sentences a ``bitter decision,'' but added that he
also thought about ``others who have died.''
   ``I think of those who fell to build a decent society ... to
create a republic where justice ruled, where there was no
corruption, dishonesty, fraud or treason,'' Castro told the Council
of State before it voted to affirm the death sentences.
   U.S. officials said Thursday the United States isn't convinced
Cuba is serious about combating drug trafficking, despite the
executions.
   Deputy State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said the
administration has had information linking Cuba to narcotics
smuggling since 1982 and has expressed its concerns since then.
   He reacted coolly to a suggestion by Castro that the United
States and Cuba join to wage this ``common battle'' against drugs.
   ``You don't automatically start negotiating cooperation until you
have an indication the other side is really serious. And that's what
we're looking for,'' Boucher said, asserting that drug smuggling
through Cuba continues.
   The investigation, court-martial and appeal were given
unprecedented publicity aimed at showing they had a fair trial and
at erasing a stain on the honor of Cuba and the Communist Party.
   Ordinary life virtually came to a halt during televised
proceedings that began June 12. Cubans gathered around their sets in
fascination not just at the drug scandal but also because of the
scenario of unbridled greed that unfolded.
   The trial indicated that Ochoa helped smuggle tons of cocaine and
marijuana into the United States in alliance with Colombia's
Medellin cartel, the world's largest drug trafficking organization.
   The officers were also convicted of black marketeering and
smuggling diamonds, ivory, sugar, fine woods, manufactured goods and
U.S. dollars.
   All confessed guilt but asked for mercy based on their records
and contrition. Ten of the officers, including one woman, were
sentenced to terms that ranged from 10 to 30 years in prison.
   In a statement before a military court of honor that stripped the
accused of military ranks and decorations, Ochoa said he deserved to
die for betraying Castro and the revolution.
   Defense Minister Raul Castro, Fidel's brother, told an earlier
court of honor that Ochoa had been ``spreading around gifts and
handing out objects of value, mainly to officers ... in a delirious
exercise of self-indulgence, for the creation of an image and links
of gratitude to his person.''
   That seemed to imply that Ochoa was trying to bring others into
his ring. There was speculation that Ochoa was either trying to
avoid being turned in or even building his own power base, perhaps
to challenge or gain some measure of independence from the Castro
brothers, who have ruled Cuba since 1959.
   Ochoa, 57, fought in the guerrilla war that brought Castro to
power and was made a Hero of the Revolution, Cuba's highest honor,
for heading the Cuba's 50,000-man expedition in Angola and an
earlier one to Ethiopia.
   In his summation to the Council of State, made up of top
government and party officials and constituting Cuba's final court
of appeal, Castro tried to distance himself from Ochoa, citing
mistakes he made in Angola that led to battlefield defeats.
   Castro said Ochoa had concentrated on his illicit activities and
risked defeat by South African forces aiding Angolan rebels. He said
people must wonder how an officer ``so out of control'' could have
been given such responsibility.
   In addition to the officers on trial, the transportation and
interior ministers have been sacked for failing to detect and halt
the ring, according to Cuban media reports. Unconfirmed reports said
other officials were arrested.
   Castro said commuting Ochoa's sentence could create an impression
that high-ranking officials could get away with anything. Ochoa and
his cohorts ``must have felt like the most untouchable people in the
world,'' Castro said.
</TEXT>
