<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 2145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ExxonValdez     07-13 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Test Shows No Oil Present In Slick From Valdez</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preliminary tests showed no oil in a slick from
the Exxon Valdez, the Coast Guard said Thursday, but the damaged
tanker will remain outside San Diego Bay while more tests are
conducted.
   The tests conducted by a Coast Guard laboratory conflict with the
preliminary conclusion of the state Fish and Game Department's lab.
   State officials said traces of petroleum were discovered in
samples taken from the 18-mile-long slick that developed when the
Valdez arrived off San Diego from Alaska on Monday.
   The Coast Guard test also used a sample from that slick.
   ``The results indicate no presence of oil,'' Coast Guard Cmdr.
Jack Scarborough said. ``They indicate the presence of some
unidentified organic matter.''
   A team of federal and state scientists, coordinated by a
specialist from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration,
has been assembled to analyze fresh samples from subsequent Valdez
discharges.
   ``There are questions that have been raised relative to the
sampling procedures used by both laboratories,'' said Pete
Bontadelli, director of the state Fish and Game Department. ``That
is the reason we are establishing a single, coordinated team so we
can resolve the question once (and) for all.''
   The Valdez was towed 2,500 miles to San Diego from Alaska, where
it was responsible for the nation's worst oil spill. The vessel was
damaged March 24, when it struck a reef in Alaska's Prince William
Sound, spewing nearly 11 million gallons of oil.
   Coast Guard officials have barred the Valdez from entering San
Diego Bay for repairs until they are sure it poses no environmental
or navigational threat. The ship remained about 50 miles off San
Diego on Thursday.
   ``We're quite comfortable with where it is and until everyone
understands what the analysis tells us. We are in no hurry to
move,'' said Frank Iarossi, Exxon Shipping Co. president.
   Before the Valdez can enter the harbor, five steel slabs that
peeled away from its hull during the trip from Alaska must be
removed so it can navigate the shallow harbor channel. For the
safety of the divers, the salvage work must be performed in a
sheltered cove or inlet, but officials don't want to move the ship
until they determine what's being discharged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
