<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-NorthKoreaToday Adv23   07-13 1176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-North Korea Today, Adv 23,1215</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>North Korea Opening Up, But Holds Fast to Regimentation</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is main story in package of three.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Communist North Korea is gradually ending decades
of secrecy and claims to have achieved paradise, but it is a
paradise where all 20 million angels march in lockstep. Here is a
report from the AP bureau chief in Beijing, who visited Pyongyang
recently.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hermit of Asia is emerging and
what is seen is a regimented society that, in contrast to more
liberal communism elsewhere, trains its 20 million people to obey
every command of the state.
   North Korea claims to have achieved Paradise on Earth. Its
leaders declare with pride that the nation has no taxes, no prisons,
no want, no social unrest.
   Well-informed outsiders, however, say the country has trouble
feeding itself, is burdened with foreign debts and is rapidly
falling behind the vibrant capitalist economy of rival South Korea.
   Western journalists got a rare glimpse of a closed society during
the World Festival of Youth and Students, held July 1-8 in Pyongyang.
   The meeting of 15,000 young people, most of them from
left-leaning organizations, was the first major international event
in the North Korean capital and the city was carefully prepared as a
showcase.
   Pyongyang had a well-scrubbed look of prosperity. Tree-lined
avenues were festooned with banners and flags, and balconies of
well-kept apartment buildings were draped with flowers.
   Stores in the capital, which foreign residents said usually were
poorly stocked, bulged with goods and shoppers.
   Visitors were given tours of kindergartens with chandeliers and
indoor swimming pools, of hospitals outfitted with new Japanese and
West German equipment, of homes with color televisions and
refrigerators.
   They found another, jarring, element everywhere: total control of
the populace and the pervasive personality cult of President Kim Il
Sung, the 77-year-old ``Great Leader,'' and ``Dear Leader'' Kim Jong
Il, his son and presumed successor.
   Above their hearts, North Koreans wear badges with the elder
Kim's portrait.
   Nearly every room of every office and home has a picture of the
senior Kim, and many have portraits of both Kims.
   Billboards and monuments recite and depict heroic deeds of the
man who has led the North since the Korean Peninsula was divided in
1945, after the defeat of Japan in World War II.
   ``This is our happy land and it's all due to the Great Leader and
the Dear Leader,'' said Kim Ho Sok, manager of a collective farm
outside Pyongyang. ``Some people call this Paradise on Earth.''
   Visitors heard the same statement again and again from other
North Koreans.
   In Pyongyang, the national showcase, visitors see neat apartments
of three or four rooms with central heating, hot water and basic
appliances. The average factory worker is paid only about 100 won a
month, $45 at the official rate, but enjoys free housing, education
and medical care.
   Life is harder in the countryside. Many cottages do not have
running water or private toilets, but in areas around the capital,
stucco apartment buildings of two or three stories are being built
to replace them.
   Several foreigners with extensive knowledge of North Korea said
it has enormous problems.
   Many basic foods are rationed and, the foreigners said, the
government often cannot supply the average monthly meat allotment of
4.4 pounds per family. They said no fruit and few vegetables are
available in winter.
   Kim Byong Hun, an economist at Kim Il Sung University, denied
food was in short supply. He said the reason for rationing rice was
to build up reserves to feed South Korea after reunification.
   A foreigner who has made 18 visits to North Korea said the
government forces people to donate from their savings for the
purpose, it says, of helping poor people in South Korea.
   Some of the rules are difficult to fathom. Bicycles are banned in
Pyongyang even though cars are seldom seen on the broad boulevards.
The few traffic lights at intersections were turned off.
   North Koreans said vehicles are scarce because the nation lacks
petroleum deposits. This country's creed has become ``juche,'' a
philosophy of self-reliance.
   Everyone does ``voluntary'' work for the government once a week.
   Tens of thousands were mobilized to help build stadiums and
apartments when the North tried, in vain, to become co-host with the
South of the 1988 Summer Olympics. The facilities were used for the
youth festival.
   Where a person lives and works is not his business, but the
state's. Although many homes have televisions, few have radios,
apparently to prevent people from listening to foreign broadcasts.
   Several rural homes visited had wall loudspeakers used by local
officials to broadcast instructions and ideological teachings. North
Korea has almost no private telephones.
   Li Chol Sin, vice chairman of the Committee for Cultural
Relations with Foreign Countries, denied claims by Amnesty
International and other human rights groups that North Korea is a
major abuser of human rights.
   In North Korea, ``everyone has housing and free medical care and
there's no unemployment,'' he said. ``How can countries with
unemployment criticize us for human rights?''
   The regimen appears to accomplish its aim. Several students
stopped randomly at Kim Il Sung University said they never would
question government policy.
   ``In our country, students absolutely support the party,'' said
Pak Song Ok, a 21-year-old studying the philosophy of ``juche.''
   Economists said North Korea will not follow other communist
nations in experimenting with capitalist-style reform even though
the growth rate is only 2 percent to 3 percent a year, compared to
about 11 percent in South Korea.
   ``We will not liberalize our economy and not put much stress on
material incentives,'' said Kim Hwa Chon of Kim Il Sung University.
   He said workers receive some extra pay for exceeding quotas and
farmers may grow vegetables in private plots around their homes, but
the main rewards for hard work remain political: citations as model
workers or appointments as deputies in local legislatures.
   The economist illustrated allegiance to the self-reliance creed
by opening his shirt to show that even his T-shirt was a domestic
product.
   Foreign debt has accumulated _ despite ``juche'' _ to somewhere
between $5 billion and $8 billion, according to foreign observers.
   Dealing with North Korea is a gamble, one foreign businessman
said, because the government sometimes pays bills promptly and
sometimes neglects them. Another said his company accepts only
barter deals or cash in advance.
   Other foreigners said North Korea finances imported technology
for factories and limousines for high officials by selling gold and
other precious metals.
   In its hesitant opening to the oustside world, the government has
enacted a joint venture law and begun several projects, mainly with
communist countries or overseas Koreans.
   A 105-story, pyramid-shaped hotel now dominates the Pyongyang
skyline. It is to be finished in 1990 for what North Korea hopes
will be a flood of tourists with wads of foreign currency.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday July 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-NorthKorea-Leader Adv23   07-13 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-North Korea-Leader, Adv 23,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kim Il Sung Is Father, Teacher and Saint to North Koreans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-North Korea Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He is the ``Great Leader'' whose
deeds are praised, whose portrait and words are everywhere. Kim Il
Sung has nearly deified himself in his self-made world of
regimentation and mass obedience.
   President Kim, who is 77 and has ruled North Korea since the
peninsula was divided in 1945, has crafted an unmatched cult of
personality.
   Four-year-olds at Changgwang Kindergarten in Pyongyang sit around
a detailed model of his birthplace, singing and chanting of his
exploits. Children in another room carol, ``We wish good health and
long life to Comrade Marshal Kim Il Sung.''
   At a nearby middle school, a 15-year-old recites to her English
class: ``Thanks to the Great Leader and the Dear Leader, we have no
worries about food or housing and we all lead happy lives.''
   The Dear Leader is the president's son and heir apparent, Kim
Jong Il.
   A chair and desk in the library of Kim Il Sung University are a
shrine, covered with a white cloth. Kim sat there during a visit to
the university in 1970.
   Stuffed animals he donated fill a display room at the university,
which also contains a shotgun the Great Leader provided so students
could add to the collection.
   At the main entrance of every school, institution, store, office
and factory is a larger-than-life portrait of Kim Il Sung in
appropriate context.
   Hospitals show him counseling doctors; schools portray him
receiving the adulation of children; in bookstores, his image bends
over weighty tomes.
   Visitors to a factory or school are told how Kim stood on a
nearby hill to order it built, then provided ``on-the-spot
guidance'' now and then.
   Li Hung Son of Pyongyang's largest textile mill said Kim had
visited it 48 times. ``Only under the wise guidance of Great Leader
Kim Il Sung have we achieved prosperity,'' he declared
   Kim Ho Sok of the Haksan collective farm outside Pyongyang said
Kim had visited 18 times to teach farmers which crops to grow and
how to manage the enterprise. ``Parents only give children life, but
the Great Leader takes care of all the people,'' he said.
   A huge stone monument that dominates the farm entrance is
emblazoned with the words he uttered during his visits.
   Nearly every room of every home has a portrait of the Great
Leader, often accompanied by one of the Dear Leader. Adults wear
badges with Kim Il Sung's picture just above the heart.
   From billboards and statues, Kim observes the streets and subway
stations of Pyongyang. An Arch of Triumph replica 200 feet high
honors his achievements as a young revolutionary.
   More than 40,000 people a day visit the shrine of Mangyongdae,
the thatch-roofed farmhouse on Pyongyang's outskirts where Kim was
born in 1912. Equal numbers go to the Korean Revolution Museum,
which has 100 rooms and 140,000 items relating to his revolutionary
accomplishments.
   Accounts in the museum say Kim's great-grandfather helped sink a
``U.S. pirate ship'' that was scouting possible invasion routes in
1866. They say his father was a leader in fighting the Japanese, who
ruled Korea from 1910 to 1945, and died young after imprisonment and
torture.
   The Great Leader himself, it is said, left home at 13 to join the
resistance and founded Korea's first Communist organization a year
later.
   Works by and about Kim fill Pyongyang's bookstores.
   One volume is titled ``A Great Man.'' It begins by saying history
has recorded the stories of many great men, but ``none can match
those of General Kim Il Sung, genius of mankind produced by Korea in
the 20th century.''
   His appearance in public can ignite a near-frenzy of celebration.
At opening ceremonies of an international youth festival in
Pyongyang, Kim's arrival on his dais was the signal for fireworks to
explode, doves to be released, trumpets to sound and thousands of
Koreans to genuflect worshipfully.
   An economist, Kim Hwa Chon, was asked about the high cost of
building memorials to the Great Leader and replied: ``We never count
the money for monuments. The hearts of the Korean people built
them.''
</TEXT>
