<FIRST>s i BC-NorthKorea-Regimen Adv23   07-13 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-North Korea-Regimen, Adv 23,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>North Korea: Regimentation on Grand Scale</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-North Korea Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Expert precision singing or dancing
by tens of thousands is no trick for North Koreans because
regimentation, to them, is the story of life.
   An international youth festival opened with ceremonies involving
70,000 youngsters from the host country, including a dazzling
display of rapidly changing pictures by 50,000 card flashers.
   Most of the 20 million citizens were mobilized to make sure
communist North Korea's first major international event would be a
success.
   Nearly everyone in Pyongyang helped build Kwangbok Street, a
high-rise apartment complex for 25,000 families, which was finished
in two years and housed festival delegates.
   Office workers ``volunteer'' for public service work once a week.
   Kindergarten teachers initiate a lifelong course in patriotism,
absolute loyalty to the system and reverence for President Kim Il
Sung.
   Ideological training and service to the state dominate the
education system. Workers have political study sessions at least
once a week.
   Songs, books, television, movies and loudspeaker announcements
beamed into homes reinforce the message.
   For those not convinced an entire nation could be trained to
obey, the youth offered some examples:
   _Thousands of pedestrians along the airport road waved whenever a
carload of foreigners passed.
   _Several hundred folk dancers in a city square stopped dancing
and applauded when told through the loudspeaker of a passing bus
that it carried foreigners.
   _A foreigner entered a department store and one order from his
North Korean interpreter opened a path in the crowd so the visitor
could be served first.
   _Buses and military trucks took thousands of North Koreans to
each festival event to make sure all were well-attended.
   _When festival delegates rallied at a school against China's
suppression of pro-democracy students, about 1,000 North Koreans
suddenly appeared and began dancing in the schoolyard, leaving no
room for a demonstration.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday July 23</NOTE>
