<FIRST>s i BC-Nicaragua-Directors Adv16   07-13 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nicaragua-Directors, Adv 16,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday July 16 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sandinista Directorate Remains Intact</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Nicaragua 10 Years Later, b0515-516 of July 12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The members of the Sandinista
directorate have not changed since the overthrow of dictator
Anastasio Somoza a decade ago.
   Their unity has surprised foreign diplomats, who had expected a
split among the nine Commanders of the Revolution. No such problem
has arisen, although some former guerrilla leaders and sympathizers
have gone over to the anti-Sandinista resistance.
   Members of the Sandinista National Liberation Front directorate
control the executive, legislature, police, army and other key
posts. Some well-known officials, such as Vice President Sergio
Ramirez and Foreign Minister Miguel d'Escoto, are not among the nine.
   These are the directorate's members:
   _Daniel Ortega, 43, president and likely Sandinista presidential
candidate in general elections scheduled for Feb. 25. His leadership
style _ hard work, and a decision-making process that is open to
many opinions _ has done much to hold the directorate together.
   _Humberto Ortega, 47, defense minister. Opponents refer to ``the
government of the Ortega brothers,'' reflecting the widespread
attitude that together _ as in Cuba with Fidel and Raul Castro in
the same posts _ they represent the real power in Nicaragua.
   _Bayardo Arce, 39. As vice-coordinator of the Sandinista
executive commission, Arce is Ortega's deputy for ideology. He is
described as an ideological hard-liner and the main link between the
Sandinistas and Salvadoran guerrillas.
   _Tomas Borge, 58, the directorate's senior member, who helped
found the Sandinistas in July 1961 and is known as a hard-liner. As
interior minister, he is in charge of police and state security.
   _Luis Carrion, 37, minister of economy, industry and commerce.
Carrion was born into one of Nicaragua's wealthiest families.
   _Carlos Nunez, 38, president of the National Assembly, the
unicameral legislature.
   _Henry Ruiz Hernandez, 49, minister of external cooperation since
1985 and planning minister before that.
   _Victor Tirado, 49, head of the Department of Mass Organizations.
Tirado, born in Mexico, joined the Sandinistas in 1963 and became a
Nicaraguan citizen in September 1979.
   _Jaime Wheelock, 42, agriculture minister and son of a wealthy
landowning family.
</TEXT>
