<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-13 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0896</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices nosedived after the Chicago
Board of Trade ordered liquidation of large positions in its July
contract, a move widely interpreted as an effort to break a foreign
firm's attempt to corner the market.
   Activity in the soybean pit was heaviest at the beginning and end
of the session Wednesday as traders tried to sort rumors from facts.
   A Board of Trade spokesman said the exchange's board of directors
late Tuesday issued the order to liquidate large soybean positions
to correct a wide disparity between the number of contracts being
held for deliverable soybean supplies and the actual supply of
soybeans available.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC's stock declined as investors
took profits and speculated whether a high-powered group led by Sir
James Goldsmith could pull off its bold $21 billion hostile bid for
the conglomerate.
   Possible hurdles could include reluctance by institutional
shareholders to accept the group's cashless offer, public-interest
scrutiny by the British government and defensive litigation in the
United States, experts said Wednesday.
   BAT fell the equivalent of 37 cents to close at $14.21 a share on
the London Stock Exchange, following a $3.24-a-share runup on
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Sousuke Uno packs the
promise of billions of dollars for the environment and the world's
poorest nations as he prepares for this week's Paris summit of major
industrialized nations.
   At the summit that begins Friday, Uno will pledge to increase
Japan's ``recycling of funds'' program for debt-ridden countries by
$35 billion and extend the program until 1991, a Foreign Ministry
official said Wednesday.
   The $35 billion is in addition to a 3-year, $30 billion program
that Japan started in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration tried to calm growing
criticism of its draft clean-air legislation and urged opposing
environmental and industry critics to stop ``nitpicking this thing
apart.''
   Officials said Wednesday they were worried that intense criticism
of the proposed legislation, before it even reached Congress, could
lead to legislative gridlock similar to that which has prevented
passage of a bill the past decade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Settlements totaling $89.5 million have been
reached in ``greenmail'' lawsuits by Walt Disney Co. shareholders
against the Disney board of directors and Wall Street financier Saul
Steinberg, the parties announced.
   Suits brought by present and former Disney shareholders alleged
they lost millions when Disney ended a Steinberg-led takeover
attempt in 1984 by paying a premium price to buy out his Disney
stock.
   Of the settlements _ which are subject to court approval and
mainly will be paid by insurors _ $29.5 million will be split among
thousands of former Disney shareholders included in a class action
suit.
</TEXT>
