<FIRST>r f PM-ComexPresident     07-13 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comex President,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comex Board Appoints New President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arnold F. Staloff, a senior officer of the
Philadelphia Stock Exchange, has been named president and chief
executive officer of the Commodity Exchange of New York, the Comex
announced.
   Staloff, 44, who also is president of the Philadelphia Board of
Trade, replaces eight-year veteran Alan J. Brody, who resigned at
the end of June to pursue other business opportunities.
   Brody had been the youngest person ever to named to the
presidency of a U.S. futures exchange when he was appointed in 1981
at age 27.
   Comex Chairman John Hanemann on Wednesday called Staloff ``a
financial sector all-star.''
   ``His record in Philadelphia is one of successful innovation and
effective management ... from the creation of the world's first
foreign currency option to the development of the Phildelphia
Exchange's computerized trading system,'' Hanemann said.
   Staloff worked for the Philadelphia exchange from 1971 to 1978,
and again from 1980 to the present.
   The Comex is the world's most active metals futures market.
</TEXT>
