<DOCNO> AP890713-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time     07-13 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Stock Regains Ground As Traders Await Delaware Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors bid Time Inc.'s stock higher as they
continued to speculate about how a Delaware judge might rule on the
three-way battle for the media giant.
   Time rose $1.87{ to close at $148.12{ a share Wednesday on the
New York Stock Exchange as Wall Street waited for Chancery Court
Judge William T. Allen's verdict on Paramount Communications Inc.'s
request for an injunction against Time's $14 billion tender offer
for Warner Communications Inc.
   Allen was expected to rule by week's end, before he leaves for a
vacation and before Time's $70-a-share offer for Warner expires at
midnight Monday.
   After Allen heard arguments in the case Tuesday, investor
pessimism about the chances for success of Paramount's $12.2
billion, $200-a-share bid for Time sent Time's stock tumbling $6.37{
a share to $146.25. Analysts said that at under $150 a share, the
stock attracted bargain hunters Wednesday.
   Fred Anschel, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said the
market continued to speculate on the outcome of the Delaware court
case.
   If the judge decides in favor of Time, the company plans to allow
its tender offer for Warner to expire as scheduled Monday even if
Paramount appeals to the Delaware Supreme Court.
   Edward Adler, a Time spokesman, said Wednesday he did not
immediately know whether Time would extend the tender offer if the
judge ruled in favor of Paramount.
   It also was not known what Paramount planned to do if Allen
denied its request.
   Paramount stock was up 50 cents to $58.50 a share on the NYSE
Wednesday, while Warner stock fell 37{ cents to $62.50 a share.
   In arguments Tuesday, attorneys for Paramount and some of Time's
shareholders contended that Time's directors violated their duty in
refusing to let shareholders vote on Paramount's bid.
   The lawyers claimed the Time board effectively put the company up
for sale when it agreed to a stock-swap merger with Warner in March.
Under Delaware law, if a company is up for sale, its board must
entertain any bids that would fetch the most money for shareholders.
   Time attorneys dismissed that argument, saying the merger was
simply a business transaction that followed two years of
negotiations.
   Time announced the tender offer for Warner after Paramount
launched its bid.
</TEXT>
