<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TVAFinancing     07-13 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TVA Financing,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>TVA to Refinance $6.5 Billion in Treasury Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tennessee Valley Authority, operator of the
nation's largest electric power system, said it will refinance $6.5
billion in debt to the federal Treasury by issuing bonds in the
public market for the first time in 15 years.
   The agency expects to save $100 million a year in interest costs
by refinancing.
   Of TVA's total $18.1 billion in long-term debt, $16.7 billion is
held by the Federal Financing Bank, an agency of the Treasury
Department, and the average interest rate on $6.5 billion of the
debt is 12.25 percent, according to William F. Malec, the TVA chief
financial officer.
   Malec said Wednesday the agency expected to pay about a 9 percent
average interest rate on the newly issued debt.
   TVA said it was compelled to go to the public market to raise the
money because the Federal Financing Bank will not lend money for
refinancing.
   TVA, based in Knoxville, Tenn., provides electricity to about 8
million people in parts of Tennessee, Mississippi, Kentucky,
Georgia, North Carolina and Virginia.
</TEXT>
