<DOCNO> AP890713-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0755EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OilDrilling     07-13 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Drilling,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Expansion of Protected Coastal Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An effort to sharply limit oil drilling off the
U.S. coast, spurred by the Exxon Valdez disaster, is headed to the
Senate with a strong voice of approval from the House.
   The House on Wednesday approved the most extensive ban on
offshore oil leasing of the decade, widely expanding prohibitions
for one year against drilling off large portions of the Atlantic,
Pacific and Alaska coasts.
   ``Those people who have allied themselves with the oil industry
understand how dramatic a statement this is now,'' Rep. George
Miller, D-Calif., said before the vote.
   The one-year moratorium was part of the $11 billion Interior
Department appropriation bill, which was approved 374-49. There was
no separate vote on the oil leasing provision.
   The Senate has not voted on the Interior appropriation and
several senators plan to introduce similar prohibitions.
   The Bush administration opposes the expanded prohibitions.
   Under the House bill, leases for offshore oil drilling would be
banned in areas off the coasts of California, Florida, a stretch of
the Atlantic Ocean between Maine and Maryland and, for the first
time, off part of Alaska's coast.
   The appropriations bill sets spending by the Interior Department
and related agencies for fiscal 1990, and the provision prohibits
appropriated money from being used to lease or approve oil drilling
or exploration in the areas during the year.
   Miller and other legislators are seeking to permanently ban
drilling in some areas of the outer continental shelf.
   ``This moratorium will provide needed breathing room to enact the
stronger safeguard I have proposed of a 10-year moratorium,'' said
Rep. Jim Courter, R-N.J.
   Support for limits on offshore oil exploration has grown since
the March disaster in which the tanker Exxon Valdez spilled 1.6
million gallons of oil into the pristine Prince William Sound water
off the Alaska coast.
   Smaller tanker accidents over one weekend last month spilled oil
into water off the Texas, Delaware and Rhode Island coasts.
   The American Petroleum Institute, the major industry trade group,
called the House vote ``a tragedy for our nation.''
   ``In an emotional reaction to tanker oil spills, the House has
taken an action that will inevitably boomerang,'' the institute said
in a statement. ``Tanker traffic bringing imported oil into U.S.
waters will have to increase as domestic oil production continues to
decline.''
   In a June 29 letter to House Appropriations leaders,
administration budget director Richard Darman said the oil leasing
provision and the bill's total budget, which is $2.45 billion more
than Bush requested, are the main reasons the White House opposes
the bill.
   The administration also objects to a ``buy America'' provision
that requires offshore oil and gas rigs to be constructed with at
least 50 percent U.S. labor and materials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
