<HEAD>London Shares Weaker At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were weaker but off their minimum
levels around midday Thursday, as profit-taking crept into the
market before the end of the current two-week trading account on
Friday.
   London's Stock Exchange divides trading into two-week and
three-week trading periods for accounting purposes.
   Dealers said there wasn't any concerted selling pressure. ``You'd
have to be a fool to take a short (position) with all the bids on
the table at the moment, and the possibility of a few more,'' one
market maker said.
   A host of rumors were making the rounds, highlighting a number of
stocks, dealers said.
   At about noon, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was 7.6 points, or 0.3 percent, weaker at 2,249.1, just a shade
below its best level for the day of 2,249.4. The index sunk as low
as 2,242.9 during the morning before rebounding to its current level.
   Volume amounted to a moderate 318.4 million shares at midday
compared with 539.1 million shares at the same time Wednesday.
