<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Pepsico     07-13 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Pepsico,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsico Chairman Says ``Guerrilla Warfare'' Needed Against Coke</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsico Inc. Chairman D. Wayne Calloway said
Thursday his firm needs to resort to guerrilla tactics to make an
appreciable dent in Coca-Cola's share of the Japanese soft drink
market.
   Coca-Cola dominates Japan's cola market with a 92 percent share,
compared with Pepsi's 6 percent, according to food and beverage
industry statistics.
   ``When you have as strong a share as Coca-Cola, that calls for
guerrilla warfare,'' Calloway said. That means ``chipping away at
the convenience store chains, store by store, vending machine by
vending machine,'' he said.
   Pepsico also owns the Kentucky Fried Chicken, Pizza Hut and Taco
Bell restaurant chains, and the snack food company Frito Lay. Pepsi
Cola has been successful in other countries, such as the Soviet
Union, where it has 21 bottling plants and contracts for 20 more.
   But gaining market share in Japan ``is trench warfare, store by
store, pizza by pizza. It's that kind of business,'' Calloway told
reporters over a hotel-catered lunch of consomme Mille Fanti and
filet steak au poivre.
   Pepsico was a sponsor for the worldwide tour of pop superstar
Michael Jackson, who performed in Japan in 1987 and 1988. Those
visits boosted Pepsi Cola sales in Japan briefly to 12-15 percent of
the cola market, but they fell back each time.
   ``Coca-Cola says Japan is its most profitable market,'' Calloway
said. ``That says you're up against a pretty formidable force.'' He
said problems remain with brand recognition and the complex Japanese
distribution system.
   ``We're not going to go out and do something crazy,'' he said.
``There is no silver bullet, no bomb we can drop.''
   But he said Pepsico would keep up steady efforts at market
penetration, including increasing local retail outlets and investing
in vending machines.
   Pepsico also is expanding into non-carbonated drinks such as
fruit juices, sports drinks and coffee, Calloway said.
   ``We're not the market leader so we can't afford to do a lot of
advertising and marketing. We have to do it in a controlled manner.
If I went out and matched Coca-Cola's spending here, unless you have
the distributors and the vendors, it won't help.''
   Pepsico's other ventures in Japan have fared better. Kentucky
Fried Chicken, a joint venture with the trading giant Mitsubishi
Corp., has cornered 98 percent of this country's fried chicken
market, according to Shinsuke Ohkawara, president of Kentucky Fried
Chicken Japan, who accompanied Calloway.
   Kentucky Fried Chicken has 834 outlets in Japan, the largest
Western-style restaurant chain in this country, and projected sales
of $863 million this year, Ohkawara said.
   By the end of the year Pepsico will have 18,000 restaurants
worldwide, the largest restaurant chain in the world, and directly
own or operate 40 percent of them, with the rest franchises or joint
ventures, Calloway said.
   By contrast, the McDonald's fast-food chain has some 11,000
outlets worldwide, with 20 percent of them directly operated, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
