<FIRST>u f PM-MortgageRefinancing 1stLd-Writethru f0025 07-13 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mortgage Refinancing, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0025,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fannie Mae `Greases the Skids' for Refinanced Mortgages</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 8th graf, That would, to include amount of mortgage in
example</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homeowners seeking to take advantage of falling
interest rates this summer should be able to refinance their
mortgages faster and more cheaply under a new program offered by the
nation's largest mortgage buyer.
   The Federal National Mortgage Association, known as Fannie Mae,
said Wednesday the changes would offer lower closing costs and
speedier approval to homeowners replacing fixed- or adjustable-rate
mortgages with new fixed-rate loans.
   ``What we're trying to do here is grease the skids and make it
easier for people to refinance,'' said economist David W. Berson of
Fannie Mae, a congressionally-chartered, shareholder-owned company
that provides money for home buyers by purchasing mortgages from
lenders and packaging them into securities for sale to investors.
   Lenders are anticipating a surge in refinancing this summer
because fixed-rate mortgages have fallen by about 1\ percentage
points since March and are expected to fall by another quarter of a
point by fall.
   Fixed rates are below 10 percent for the first time in more than
a year. One-year adjustable rates have edged down in recent months,
but not by as much, and still are about a percentage point higher
than a year ago.
   Berson said he expected roughly 300,000 homeowners to refinance
in the July-September quarter. He said about $90 billion in
fixed-rate mortgages would be written in the quarter and between 25
percent to 35 percent of those likely would be refinancings. Fannie
Mae helps finance one of every eight mortgages.
   Much of this summer's refinancing activity will come from
homeowners who took out discounted, adjustable-rate mortgages and
are now facing higher payments. For instance, home buyers who took
out an adjustable-rate mortgage at a 7{ percent rate in 1987 are
probably now paying 11{ percent.
   That would, on average, increase their monthly principal and
interest payments on a $100,000 mortgage from $699 two years ago to
$990 now. Refinancing to a fixed-rate mortgage at 9} percent would
lower the payment to $859.
   During the last refinancing boom in 1986 and 1987, homeowners
often had to wait three months before getting approval for their new
loans, Berson said. The waiting period has dropped to about six
weeks and the company's new program could shorten the process by
another week or two, he said.
   With certain restrictions, Fannie Mae will waive a new home
appraisal, saving homeowners several hundred dollars. In that case,
the new loan must come from the original mortgage lender. However,
the waiver will not apply if the current loan is backed by the
Veterans Administration or Federal Housing Administration.
   Also, Fannie Mae for many loans will not require borrowers to go
through another credit and income check. Those loans must be for a
one- or two-family main residence or a second home. The new mortgage
must not exceed 90 percent of the home's value, or 95 percent with
mortgage insurance.
   Homeowners will not be allowed to take more than 1 percent of the
new loan in cash. They will be permitted to borrow the money to pay
for the closing fees of the new loan, thus eliminating most up-front
costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 0952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MidwayAirlines     07-13 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Midway Airlines,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Midway Expansion May Open Jobs For Striking Eastern Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An expansion of Midway Airlines, which is trying to
acquire jets, routes and gates from Eastern Airlines, may provide
jobs for strike-weary workers, the chairman of the Chicago-based
carrier said.
   David Hinson, Midway chairman and chief executive officer, said
Wednesday the carrier should sign a $206.5 million agreement next
week for 16 Eastern planes, two Canadian routes and 13 gates at
Philadelphia International Airport, which Midway plans to develop
into its East Coast hub.
   By the mid-1990s, Hinson said Midway hopes to have more than
1,000 employees in Philadelphia and operate routes from Canada to
the Caribbean.
   ``The former Eastern workers are high-quality professionals that
we would give top priority to hire under the appropriate
circumstances,'' said Hinson in a visit to Miami International
Airport, where Midway operates its principal maintenance facilities.
   Midway has hired nine former Eastern pilots since machinists,
pilots and flight attendants at the Miami-based airline went on
strike March 4.
   The Midway deal is part of Eastern's strategy to significantly
downsize operations from its pre-strike level of more than 1,000
flights. U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland in New York must
approve the agreement.
   Eastern, which filed for bankruptcy protection March 9, has
already sold its profitable Northeast Shuttle to billionaire Donald
Trump for $365 million and has announced plans to sell at least 20
more jets.
   While Eastern considers relocating its headquarters to Atlanta,
Hinson said Midway's expansion plans could more than double flights
into Miami.
   If the Philadelphia deal is approved, Midway may have up to five
flights a day to Miami from Chicago and Philadelphia, said Hinson.
The airline, which acquired bankrupt Air Florida as it expanded to a
national carrier during the past decade, also holds several of Air
Florida's former Latin American and Caribbean routes, which Hinson
said may be used after the Philadelphia hub is established.
   Midway currently flies via Miami to Nassau, Bahamas, and the U.S.
Virgin Islands.
   The East Coast service would put Midway in direct competition
with USAir, the Northeast's largest carrier, which first sought
Eastern's Philadelphia gates and routes.
   ``USAir is a formidable competitor and we have our work cut out
for us to move into their territory,'' Hinson said.
   Hinson, who predicted more airline bankruptcies before the
industry settles, said the Philadelphia expansion will be steady but
not overly aggressive.
   ``We're generally a conservative company,'' said Hinson, a former
Northwest Airlines co-pilot. ``We are not out to roll the dice.''
   Often dubbed ``the darling of deregulation,'' Midway was the
first carrier chartered after government control of the industry
ended in 1979 and began as a small Midwest carrier catering to
full-fare business travelers. By the early 1980s, it was losing more
than $20 million annually and began courting regular passengers soon
after acquiring Air Florida in late 1984.
   Midway operates more than 220 regular and commuter flights to 51
cities from Midway Airport south of Chicago. The carrier inaugurated
West Coast service this spring and made a $900 million order for 37
jets from McDonnell Douglas Corp. with an option for 37 more.
   For the first quarter, Midway reported record earnings of $2.9
million, but profits have been erratic in recent years, dropping
more than 40 percent last year.
   On Wednesday, Midway announced a tentative labor agreement with
the Teamsters, representing more than 450 mechanics, stock clerks
and aircraft cleaners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
