<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ShuttleAds     07-13 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Ads,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Companies in Running for Soviet Space Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five U.S. companies are vying to place ads
costing more than $1 million on the side of a Soviet space shuttle
scheduled for launch next month, according to a company with
exclusive rights to sell the advertising.
   San Francisco-based Soviet-Pacific Enterprises would only
identify the five as a major oil company, a television network, an
international courier, a consumer-goods produce and a food company.
   The ads, printed on thin plastic-like film stuck on the spaceship
with an adhesive, will disintegrate within 45 seconds of launch
because of the heat generated as the craft cuts through the earth's
atmosphere.
   Talks with the five companies are now in the final stages, said
Sam Hollis Jr., marketing director for Soviet-Pacific.
   ``But we're looking for just one sponsor,'' he said. Hollis said
his company doesn't want the space ship to ``look like an
Indianapolis 500 race car with 500 different advertisements.''
   For a payment estimated at more than $1 million, the company that
is picked will be allowed to place two 10-by-21-foot signs on the
side of the Soyuz shuttle, scheduled for launch Aug. 30. It also can
display its corporate logo or advertisements around the Baikonur
launch site and send a camera crew to film the August lift-off.
   The Soviet space agency, Glavkosmos, and Licensintorg, the
commercial-space and licensing agency in the USSR, have imposed only
one restriction, said Hollis. They won't allow sponsorship by liquor
or tobacco companies.
   More than 100 million people in the Soviet Union are expected to
view a live broadcast of the blastoff, presenting an ideal
opportunity to a company that wants to introduce a new product in
that nation.
   Less than 45 seconds might seem short for a million dollars, but
a company spokesman pointed out that a 60-second spot during a Super
Bowl broadcast costs more than that.
   Glavkosmos has signed commerical agreements with several Western
companies.
   In March, a Japanese televison network paid the agency $12
million for the right to send a correspondent into space in 1991.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration, which
administers the U.S. space program, does not accept advertising or
payment from private citizens for flights.
   In the past, U.S. space shuttles have carried some projects for a
fee, but that practice was canceled after the Challenger explosion
in 1986 that killed seven astronauts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-USFilmMakers     07-13 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-US Film Makers,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Clears Film Distribution Venture of U.S. Film Makers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
commission said Thursday it had cleared a film distribution venture
by three U.S. companies after they agreed to amend their pact to
comply with EEC antitrust rules.
   The commission said that the agreement between Paramount Pictures
Corp., MCA Inc. and MGM-UA Communications to create a joint venture,
United International Pictures, to distribute their films in the EEC
had contained exclusivity clauses which restricted competition.
   These clauses were changed so that the venture now only has the
right of first refusal on the parent companies' films. This means
that if United International chooses not to distribute a film, the
parent company could distribute it on its own or through a third
party.
   The companies also agreed to maintain ``appropriate records'' and
to establish an arbitration procedure to solve problems such as film
allocation and access to screen space, the commission said.
   The commission's clearance lasts for five years, after which it
will review the companies' agreement.
   It said the changes to the agreement were designed to ensure that
the parent companies remained autonomous and that the films were
distributed as widely as possible.
</TEXT>
