<FIRST>r f PM-Quaker-Layoffs     07-13 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quaker-Layoffs,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quaker Announces More Than 500 Staff Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Quaker Oats Co. plans to lay off more than 550
workers nationwide by next spring, the company says.
   An Ohio pet food plant that employs 390 people will be closed by
next spring, and 170 management workers nationwide will be laid off
in the next few weeks, Quaker said in a statement Wednesday.
   The management layoffs will trim 42 employees from Quaker's
Chicago headquarters. The rest of the cuts will be among sales,
manufacturing and distribution workers in the company's U.S. grocery
products division, said spokesman Ronald Botrell.
   The layoffs were announced to employees Wednesday, Botrell said.
   The company said in a statement that the plant in Marion, Ohio,
which produces Ken-L-Ration and Puss-N-Boots dog and cat foods, will
be closed in phases between the end of this year and next spring
   ``It's always difficult to make these types of decisions when it
affects loyal and dedicated employees,'' William Smithburg, chairman
and chief executive, said in a statement. ``But for competitive
reasons, we felt it necessary to take these steps.''
   Quaker said the actions would force the company to take a
one-time charge of $104 million, or 80 cents per share. A change in
accounting methods for grocery products inventories will force
another 20- to 25-cent-per-share charge.
   Those charges, coupled with a $21 million, 20-cent-per-share loss
by the European pet foods group mean the company will take losses of
more than $1.20 per share in the fiscal year ended June 30.
   The company said the plant closing was due to declining
popularity of semi-moist and canned pet foods made in Marion. The
products will continue to be made at plants in Kankakee, Ill., and
in Lawrence and Topeka, Kan.
   The company also announced that Philip A. Marineau had been
appointed to the post of executive vice president for U.S. grocery
products. Michael J. Callahan will take Marineau's old position as
executive vice president for international grocery products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
