<FIRST>r f PM-Pennwalt-FTC     07-13 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pennwalt-FTC,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Concerns Delay Pennwalt-Elf Aquitane Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission has put the
brakes on the proposed $1.05 billion acquisition of Pennwalt Corp.
by a French-government controlled oil and chemical concern, the
companies said.
   In a joint release Wednesday, the companies said the FTC had
postponed a decision about the deal until antitrust concerns were
resolved.
   Neither Pennwalt nor the French company, Societe Nationale Elf
Aquitaine, would elaborate on the FTC concerns.
   ``We are concerned in that we want to go ahead with the
transaction as soon as we are allowed to,'' said Lowell Williams, an
Elf Aquitaine spokesman. ``I don't think it's unusual, and you can't
always expect the government to agree with you. We are taking all
reasonable efforts to get the situation cleared up.''
   Susan Ticknor, an FTC spokeswoman, said she could neither confirm
nor deny any investigation of the deal. However, she said that in
general, companies often give the FTC more time to review a proposed
deal _ especially when they feel the FTC decision could be negative.
   Donald Pattison, a chemical industry analyst with Cyrus J.
Lawrence Morgan Grenfel Inc. in New York, said Wednesday the FTC was
worried the merger would make the company too strong in the
flourocarbon business.
   ``From what I've heard, the FTC is worried that a merger would
make Elf No. 3 in the world in flourocarbons, next to Du Pont and
Allied,'' he said. ``They are concerned that the entire market would
be in the hands of three giants.''
   Pennwalt stock tumbled Wednesday with news of the delay, trading
as low as $118.50 and closing on the New York Stock Exchange at
$124, down 25 cents from Tuesday. Elf Aquitaine's offer is worth
$132 a share.
   In their statement, the companies said the postponement was to
``permit Elf Aquitaine and Pennwalt to pursue discussion with the
staff of the Federal Trade Commission concering the possibility of
entering into an agreement which would address certain concerns
raised by the staff with respect to the proposed transaction.''
   Elf Aquitaine also announced it had extended to 5 p.m. July 21
the expiration date on its takeover offer for Pennwalt stock. The
offer has been extended regularly since the companies agreed to
merge on March 20.
   The management of the 139-year-old, Philadelphia-based
pharmaceutical company agreed in the spring to merge with Elf
Aquitaine after rebuffing offers from Centaur Partners of New York.
</TEXT>
