<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-CompactDiscs     07-13 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Compact Discs,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Slaps Provisional Anti-dumping Duties On Asian Compact Disc Players</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC Commission Thursday imposed
provisional anti-dumping duties on imports of compact disc players
from Japan and South Korea because they may threaten the survival of
the EEC industry.
   The duties, which range from 6.4 percent to 33.9 percent, hit
major Japanese consumer electronics companies including Sony Corp.,
Sanyo Electric Co., Pioneer Electronic Corp. and Matsushita Electric
Industrial Co.
   Major South Korean companies affected include Goldstar Co. and
Samsung Electronics Co.
   The duties, which take effect next week but must be ratified by
the EEC Council of Ministers within three months, followed a
two-year investigation by the EEC after it received a complaint by
the main EEC producers of compact disc players.
   These are NV Philips of the Netherlands, Bang &amp; Olufsen of
Denmark and Grundig AG of West Germany.
   In a statement, the commission said that the CD player imports
``seriously held back the development of the Community industry, the
main inventor and the major developer of the product.''
   It added that most of the Japanese and all of the South Korean
companies involved ``adopted marketing and pricing policies in clear
violation'' of international trading rules on dumping, or selling at
below market price.
   The commission calculates whether dumping occurs by comparing the
price on the exporter's domestic market with the price charged in
the 12-nation trade bloc.
   The commission said that it found CD player dumping ``margins''
of between 1.54 percent and 45.54 percent in the case of the
Japanese exports and of between 20.1 percent and 32.5 percent for
the Korean exports.
   It said that the low prices of the imports caused ``an important
price depression'' which resulted in ``severe'' losses for EEC
producers, which lost about 30 percent of their annual revenue.
   The EEC inquiry covered the period June 1, 1986 to May 31, 1987,
although sales of the players started in 1984.
   The commission did not give a total value of the EEC market for
CD players although it said that the imports in 1987, which made up
about two-thirds of the market, were valued at 300 million European
currency units, or about $33 million.
   Imports surged 23-fold to about 2.3 million units in 1987 from
97,924 units in 1984 of which more than 90 percent came from Japan.
This compared with a fivefold increase in EEC producers' sales, the
commission said. It did not give figures for sales by EEC producers.
   The market share of Japanese and South Korean exporters rose to
more than 75 percent in 1987 from just under 50 percent in 1984,
while the share of the EEC industry fell from more than 50 percent
to 18 percent in 1987, the commission said.
   The EEC investigated 14 producers of CD players but imposed
duties on 11 of them.
   The duties on the companies are as follows:
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Co., 33.9 percent; Pioneer
Electronic Corp., 28.8 percent; Sanyo Electric Co., 27.8 percent;
Yamaha Corp., 23.7 percent; Victor Co. of Japan (JVC), 20.9 percent;
Kenwood Corp., 19.3 percent; Nippon Columbia Co., 17.5 percent; Sony
Corp., 15.9 percent; Onkyo Corp., 8.5 percent; Funai Electric
Trading Co., 8.4 percent; Teac Corp., 6.4 percent.
   Duties also were imposed on four South Korean companies: Inkel
Corp., 20.1 percent; Goldstar Co., 32.5 percent; Samsung Electronics
Co., 23 percent and Haitai Electronics Co., 21.3 percent.
   An official, who asked not to be named, at Sony Belgium NV,
Sony's Belgian subsidiary, said that Sony was not so concerned by
the duties because its factory in Colmar, France had been producing
between 75 percent and 80 percent of Sony's CD players for the EEC
market since 1988.
   He said that the factory was not established to avoid paying
duties but was in line with Sony's policy of making products in the
company's local markets.
   NV Philips was unavailable for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
