<HEAD>Crop Report Sends Soybeans Up, Wheat Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rose in early trading today
on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to a bullish government
crop report while wheat futures fell and corn futures were mixed.
   The soybean market's strongest gains were in the new-crop
contracts, for late summer and autumn delivery, following an
Agriculture Department report that indicated farmers planted fewer
soybeans than the market had expected.
   Slight gains were posted in the July soybean contract, which is
under heavy pressure due to an exchange order requiring traders to
reduce their holdings. The unusual order was seen as a move to block
one player's attempt to corner the market.
   The USDA report, released Wednesday afternoon, pegged planted
corn acreage at a higher-than-expected level and also showed
higher-than-expected winter wheat production.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.86{ a bushel; corn was 1} cents
lower to 1\ cents higher with July at $2.57 a bushel; oats were {
cent to 2 cents higher with July at $1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were {
cent to 8{ cents higher with July up { cent at $6.87 a bushel and
August up 8{ cents at $6.73 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher, with cattle futures up
sharply in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .95 cent higher with August at 71.70
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to 1.05 cents higher with
August at 82.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .68 cent
higher with July at 47.20 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.20 cent to .55 cent higher with July at 29.30 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Wednesday while pork futures
were mixed.
