<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Nissan-UAW     07-13 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nissan-UAW,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan Appeals Labor Department Citation, Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. USA said
it will appeal a state Department of Labor citation and $5,000 fine
for refusing to release worker injury logs from its Smyrna plant.
   Nissan lawyers informed state Labor Commissioner Jim White of the
decision on Wednesday.
   The Tennessee Occupational Safety and Health Administration fined
the company $5,000 on June 22 over the Japanese automaker's refusal
to release copies of its ``OSHA 200'' worker injury records. TOSHA
had given Nissan 20 days to respond to the citation and fine.
   ``We've entered into the appeals process. The contestment now
goes through the TOSHA review procedures,'' state Labor Department
spokeswoman Nancy McNulty said.
   The matter will be examined by the state TOSHA Review Commission,
an unbiased third party that will decide if the citation should be
upheld or rule that Nissan may keep the records secret, Ms. McNulty
said.
   If state labor lawyers and Nissan attorneys fail to reach
agreement, the issue will go before an administrative law judge.
State labor lawyers have said the appeals process could take up to
six months.
   Worker safety and assembly line speed have emerged as the key
issues in the United Auto Workers efforts to organize Nissan's
Smyrna plant. About 2,400 production workers will vote July 26-27 on
whether they want to be represented by the United Auto Workers.
   ``I'm not surprised that Nissan has appealed the case. The OSHA
logs will show that they have a very high injury rate and that the
company has misled the employees and the public as to the working
conditions at the plant,'' UAW spokesman Maxey Irwin said today.
</TEXT>
