<DOCNO> AP890713-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Honda-Rover     07-13 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Honda-Rover,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honda Car Company to Invest in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda Motor Co., the Japanese carmaker, will invest
300 million pounds, or $486 million, in a new plant in southwest
England that will create 1,300 new jobs, Industry Secretary Lord
Young said Thursday.
   Honda will extend its engine plant in Swindon, southwest England,
to a full car manufacturing plant capable of producing 100,000 cars
a year, Young told the House of Lords.
   The new plant is part of an arrangement in which Honda will take
a 20-percent stake in Rover Group, the British carmaker with which
it has had joint ventures over the last 10 years. Rover said it will
acquire 20 percent of Honda's manufacturing operation in Swindon.
   Honda and other Japanese carmakers have expressed an interest in
expanding in Europe ahead of 1992 when the 12-nation European
Economic Community becomes a barrier-free market.
   Young said Honda's announcement brings the total investment
commitments in Britain by the three major Japanese car companies to
1.8 billion pounds, or $2.9 billion.
   Young said the new plant is to begin manufacturing at the end of
1991, ``with a limited volume of Honda cars,'' which will substitute
for imports from Japan on the European market.
   ``One year later, a full range of production operations will
start with output rising rapidly to 100,000 cars (per year) in
1994,'' Young said.
   He said this will include cars built for the Rover Group, with
which Honda has had various joint ventures for 10 years. Rover will
continue to build cars for Honda at its plant in Longbridge,
northwest of London.
   Graham Day, chairman of Rover Group, said the deal with Honda
``will help both companies, while preserving their separate
identities, to develop long-term strategies to meet the demands of
an increasingly global market.''
   Rover Group is owned by British Aerospace PLC, which bought the
former state-owned carmaker from the government in July 1988.
   Young called Honda's announcement a ``vote of confidence'' in
Britain and said it signaled a ``renaissance of the U.K. motor
industry.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
