<DOCNO> AP890713-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-McCaw-LIN 1stLd-Writethru   07-13 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McCaw-LIN, 1st Ld-Writethru,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw, Lin Talking about LIN Buyout at $127.50 a Share</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with new figure under discussion.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede KIRKLAND, Wash.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. is discussing
sweetening its $5.4 billion cash offer for LIN Broadcasting Corp.
shares that it does not already own by including stock that would
boost the offer to $6.2 billion.
   In a joint statement, the companies said they are in continuing
negotiations over a proposal under which each share of LIN stock
would be exchanged for cash and stock having an aggregate value of
$127.50 a share.
   The cash portion of the deal would come to at least $110 a share,
the statement read, with McCaw Class A stock making up the remainder
of the offer.
   McCaw's latest offer for LIN was for $110 a share in cash.
   The companies cautioned in the statement that ``there can be no
assurances that the negotiations will result in an agreement.''
   They said the transaction under discussion would not be completed
before Nov. 1 and would preclude LIN's previously-announced spinoff
of its television stations.
   If the Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw's takeover attempt is
successful, it would result in the largest cellular telephone market
in the country.
   The announcement came a day after McCaw disclosed in a filing
with the Securities and Exchange Commission that McCaw and LIN had
``recommenced negotiations through their advisers.''
   Steven Bruce of Abernathy MacGregor, McCaw's outside public
investor relations counsel in New York, said Wednesday's
conversation between McCaw and LIN financial advisers was a
resumption of talks that occurred last weekend.
   McCaw had launched a bid of $120 a share for LIN in June, but LIN
rejected it as inadequate. LIN has about 53.9 million shares on a
fully diluted basis, and McCaw already owns about 5 million, or 9.8
percent, of those shares.
   On Monday, McCaw lowered its bid to $110 per share, citing a New
York court settlement that was unfavorable to LIN.
   The New York Court of Appeals recently denied LIN's claims to
certain cellular interests of Metromedia Co. in the New York City
and Philadelphia markets.
   The new offer reduced the value of its bid for shares it does not
already own to about $5.36 billion, from $5.8 billion.
</TEXT>
