<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market hovered in a narrow range today,
pausing after Wednesday's rise to new post-crash highs.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 92.57 points over the
past seven sessions, rose another 2.08 to 2,534.71 by 2 p.m. on Wall
Street.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 673 up, 717 down and 517
unchanged.
   Analysts said traders had grown leery of chasing after stocks
following the market's latest rally, which produced gains in each of
the first seven trading days in July.
   Wall Streeters were looking ahead to several economic reports due
from the government on Friday, including monthly statistics on
industrial production and the producer price index of finished goods.
   The figures are expected to provide further confirmation that
economic growth is slowing, fulfilling a primary goal of the Federal
Reserve's credit policy.
   Investors will give especially close scrutiny to the report on
producer prices which, if it lives up to its advance billing, will
show a slackening of inflationary pressures.
   Sun Electric tumbled 6{ to 18[. The company, which had been
soliciting takeover bids, said it had attracted no suitable offers
and expects to remain independent.
