<FIRST>u f AM-Unilever-Faberge Bjt   07-13 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unilever-Faberge, Bjt,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unilever, Faberge Sign Sale Pact After Resolving Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer products giant Unilever will acquire the
Faberge and Elizabeth Arden lines of toiletries, cosmetics and
fragrances for $1.55 billion, salvaging a deal that had been
abandoned in April, it was announced Thursday.
   A definitive contract between Faberge's owner, Riklis Family
Corp., and Unilever United States Inc., the holding company for
Unilever's American operations, has been signed and the transaction
is expected to be completed within 30 days.
   Unilever and Riklis had reached an agreement in principle on the
takeover back in February and intended to negotiate details of a
final contract within 3 months but the talks broke down.
   In late April, Unilever said it was dropping its plan to acquire
Faberge Inc. and its independent subsidiary Elizabeth Arden because
Meshulam Riklis' Riklis group was demanding changes in the tentative
agreement that would have raised the price.
   In a joint news release Thursday, the companies said their
differences have been resolved. Completion of the transaction is
subject to a number of technical conditions that the companies did
not specify.
   Chris Atkins, a spokesman for Unilever, described the conditions
as minor matters that won't jeopardize the deal.
   ``They are fully confident this deal is going to happen,'' Atkins
said.
   The signed contract resembles the arrangements made in February.
   ``We are delighted that negotiations were resumed and that they
have resulted in a transaction in line with the original terms,''
said Unilever Chairman Michael Angus.
   ``Faberge will be an excellent fit with Unilever's existing
personal products operations and Elizabeth Arden furthers our
ambition to be strongly represented in the important prestige
skin-care, color cosmetics and fragrance sectors,'' he said.
   Under the contract, Unilever is to buy all of Faberge except for
the McGregor Apparel Group, which comprises clothing lines such as
Botany 500, Wonderknit and Bill the Kid.
   Faberge, bought by the Riklis group in 1984 for about $180
million, is a well known manufacturer of personal care products,
including hair sprays, shampoos, deodorants and fragrances. Among
Faberge's brand names are Aqua Net and Brut.
   Elizabeth Arden makes an assortment of premium skin care
products, perfumes and makeups marketed under the names Elizabeth
Arden, Lagerfeld, Fendi and Chloe. New York-based Riklis, whose
other holdings include Samsonite luggage and Culligan water
softeners, acquired Elizabeth Arden from the drug maker Eli Lilly &amp;
Co. for about $700 million in late 1987.
   Combined sales of Faberge and Elizabeth Arden amounted to more
than $800 million in the year ended January 1989 and profit was $93
million.
   Unilever, with dual headquarters in the United Kingdom and the
Netherlands, is among the world's major consumer products companies
and had worldwide sales of $31 billion in 1988. Its products in the
United States range from soaps and laundry detergents to packaged
foods.
   Through acquisitions and internal growth, Unilever for several
years has been building its personal products operations around the
world. It has concentrated its attention on several segments of the
market, among them the prestige end of the fragrance and beauty aid
business.
   Two years ago, Unilever bought Chesebrough-Pond's Inc. for $3.1
billion, thereby acquiring many widely known personal-care products
and several prestige, or expensive, lines such as the Prince
Matchabelli fragrance collection. Unilever also owns Elizabeth
Taylor's Passion scents.
   Just last month, Unilever agreed to acquire the European
cosmetics businesses of U.S. company Schering-Plough Corp. for $120
million.
   Currently, Unilever is in the process of acquiring assets of
Minnetonka Corp. through a tender offer at $22.86 a share, or a
total of $376.2 million.
   Once the process is completed, which is subject to clearance by
federal anti-trust regulators, Unilever will own Minnetonka's Calvin
Klein cosmetics and accessories businessses that comprise fragrances
Obsession and Obsession for men.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
