<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1508EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SoybeanCorner 2ndLd-Writethru f0109 07-13 1030</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soybean Corner, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0109,1061</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Italian Firm Denies It Attempted to Corner Soybean Market, Sues CBOT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Ferruzzi subsidiaries filing
lawsuit against exchange. Picks up 2nd graf pvs, ``Soybean futures ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two subsidiaries of an Italian agribusiness giant
today filed a federal lawsuit seeking to block further
implementation of the Chicago Board of Trade's order limiting
soybean futures holdings, a CBOT official said.
   The lawsuit was filed against the exchange in U.S. District Court
in Chicago by Ferruzzi Trading International SA and Ferruzzi USA
Inc., said Ray Carmichael, CBOT spokesman.
   He said the exchange would ``vigorously'' fight the lawsuit.
   The parent of the two firms, Ferruzzi SpA, has denied it
attempted to corner the soybean market, charging instead that a
CBOT's order calling for liquidation of large positions in the
exchange's July contract ``undermines the reliability'' of such
contracts.
   Soybean futures rebounded moderately in early trading today.
Analysts said the buying was a reaction to a government report
released late Wednesday that indicated spring soybean plantings were
below expectations.
   Exchange spokesman Raymond Carmichael said the Board of Trade
order was issued late Tuesday to correct a wide disparity between
the number of contracts outstanding and the actual supply of
soybeans available.
   In a statement released Wednesday in Milan, Italy, Ferruzi said
its ``accumulation of beans was undertaken so that the group could
assure the uninterrupted operation of its processing plants ... and
to satisfy export commitments, particularly to the Soviet Union.''
   ``All actions taken by the group were within accepted practices,
and the emergency order ... was taken in disregard to the true
economics of the marketplace,'' the company said.
   Ferruzzi, Western Europe's leading grain trader, said it had been
accumulating soybeans openly in compliance with CBOT rules because
last year's drought could have caused a shortage, but it did not say
how much it had bought.
   The statement also said the BOT action would ``undermine the
reliability of the contracts'' of the Board of Trade.
   In Minnesota, the state agriculture commissioner on Wednesday
asked the FBI to investigate whether any Board of Trade officials
benefited from the emergency order.
   Commissioner Jim Nichols said a drop in soybean prices would
benefit those holding ``short'' positions, or obligations to sell
soybeans.
   ``It is possible that some of the members of the board of
directors who made this order held short positions and benefited
greatly from this order,'' Nichols said in a letter to FBI director
William Sessions.
   Soybeans are used for products ranging from tofu and cooking oil
to cosmetics and animal feed.
   Activity in the BOT soybean pit, the world's largest for that
commodity, was heaviest at the beginning and end of the session
Wednesday as traders tried to sort rumors from facts.
   A BOT soybean trader said the late sale Wednesday of 3 million to
4 million bushels by a large brokerage near the close of trading
helped soybeans close 39{ cents down on the day at $6.86{ a bushel.
   The trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that sale
had all the earmarks of a foreign firm moving to comply with the
BOT's emergency liquidation order.
   One of the reasons for the midday trading lull, according to
several traders, was a report that a Ferruzzi subsidiary in Belle
Chasse, La., planned to ask a federal court for a restraining order
against the BOT action.
   Spokesman Edward Barron of the Ferruzzi subsidiary declined to
comment on the report.
   Ferruzzi's holdings in Louisiana include American Bank and Trust
of New Orleans, a grain elevator and land.
   BOT spokesman Raymond Carmichael said the exchange's board of
directors issued the order to liquidate large soybean positions to
correct a wide disparity between the number of contracts being held
for deliverable supplies of the product and the actual supply of
soybeans available.
   Carmichael refused to comment on whether the BOT's effort was
designed to break up any firm's attempt to corner the market.
   A number of traders and analysts compared the soybean market
situation to an alleged effort by the Hunt brothers of Texas a
decade ago to corner the world silver market. But others doubted
such extensive manipulation of the soybean market had taken place.
   The exchange ordered all traders holding commitments to buy or
sell more than 3 million bushels of soybeans for delivery this month
to reduce those positions by at least 20 percent each trading day
through July 20, when the July contract expires.
   The emergency resolution said no trader may control more than 3
million bushels of July soybeans at the close of trading Tuesday,
and no trader may control more than 1 million bushels by the
contract's expiration two days later.
   Futures are binding contracts to buy or sell a set amount of a
commodity at an agreed-upon price at a later date. A typical corner
occurs when a trader holding a large number of buy contracts also
owns so much of the commodity that sellers cannot acquire enough to
honor their delivery commitments.
   The artificial supply squeeze causes the commodity's price to
soar until the trader working the corner sells out at a huge profit.
   The Sun-Times also quoted unidentified sources saying the BOT
action stemmed in part from complaints by Archer Daniels Midland
Co., the Decatur, Ill.-based agribusiness giant.
   ADM spokesman Dick Burket said the company had no comment
Wednesday.
   A trading source who insisted on anonymity told The Associated
Press that the situation began as a battle between ADM and Ferruzzi
for export business.
   ``Ferruzzi was smart enough to cover itself by getting supplies
from the cash market and the futures market,'' he said. ``ADM relied
almost entirely on the futures market. When supplies got tight, ADM
had to go to the cash market to satisfy export demands and the
tighter the supply, the higher the premium they paid.''
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which regulates the
futures industry, said Wednesday in Washington that it had been
monitoring the soybean market for several months. But it would not
comment on whether an investigation was under way into any attempt
to corner the soybean market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1533EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Gateway     07-13 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Gateway,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Isoceles Claims Control of Gateway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isosceles PLC on Thursday claimed victory in its
nearly 3-month-old battle for Gateway Corp. PLC, saying it had more
than 50 percent of the British food store group's shares under its
control.
   A rival bidding group that includes the U.S. investment firm
Wasserstein, Perella &amp; Co. said it wouldn't give up its interest in
Gateway. It said it would hold on to its stake of nearly 34 percent
in Gateway and that it would be an active shareholder.
   Isosceles, a group of disgruntled Gateway shareholders, said it
had received acceptances for its 2.1 billion-pound, the equivalent
of about $3.4 billion, bid from shareholders owning 120.7 million
ordinary shares, or 13.5 percent of the total. Isosceles already
owned 37.4 percent of Gateway shares.
   The announcement claiming control came minutes after the rival
bidders said they had bought an additional 20.3 million Gateway
shares in the market Wednesday to lift their holdings to 33.79
percent.
   A spokesman for Newgateway PLC, the takeover vehicle of
Wasserstein, Perella and its partner, Great Atlantic &amp; Pacific Tea
Co., said: ``There's no drama'' in Isosceles crossing the 50-percent
threshold first.
   Isosceles' gaining a majority stake in Gateway stock ``was always
a possibility'' that was considered at the time Newgateway made its
``final offer,'' said the spokesman, who wasn't identified, in
accordance with British custom.
   Isosceles began its hostile takeover attempt in April, offering
210 pence, or about $3.42, a share. Later, it increased its offer to
230 pence, or $3.75, a share after Newgateway entered the bidding.
Newgateway's offer stands at 242 pence, or $3.94, a share.
   Alec Monk, Gateway,'s chairman, said the situation was ``still a
stalemate,'' and that Isosceles would need around 75 percent of
Gateway to ``consolidate'' the company.
   ``And they can't possibly achieve that because Newgateway
controls nearly 34 percent,'' Monk added.
   Isosceles plans to break up Gateway, to help repay its debt, by
selling 62 major superstores to Asda Group PLC for around 703
million pounds, or about $1.15 billion. Although Newgateway's bid is
also highly leveraged, the group has pledged to sell only a limited
number of less profitable stores.
   Isosceles can press ahead with its reorganization plans with just
over 50 percent control, but analysts predict it will run into
fierce resistance from Newgateway.
   Newgateway said it ``looks forward to its role as a major
long-term shareholder in Gateway.''
   ``We regard this as an important investment in a major British
food retailer,'' the group said. ``We intend to be an active
shareholder.
</TEXT>
