<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Surge On Ferruzzi Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade following news of a lawsuit
seeking to block the exchange's order that traders reduce their
holdings in the July soybean contract.
   Wheat and oat futures also advanced while corn futures finished
mixed.
   Two subsidiaries of Italian agribusiness giant Ferruzzi SpA filed
a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Chicago seeking an injunction
against the Board of Trade's emergency directive.
   The exchange's order, issued Tuesday, is widely seen as an
attempt to block an attempt by Ferruzzi to control the soybean
market.
   Soybeans had opened strongly higher, but the market had eased by
midday on profit-taking. Wire service reports of Ferruzzi's lawsuit
appeared at about 1 p.m. CDT.
   ``From the time it showed on the wire, we had a pretty decent
recovery in here,'' said Dale Gustafson, grain market analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.90{ a bushel; corn was 6\ cents
lower to } cent higher with July at $2.56{ a bushel; oats were 3
cents to 4{ cents higher with July at $1.48\ a bushel; soybeans were
9} cents to 18{ cents higher with July up 10{ cents at $6.97 a
bushel.
