<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     07-13 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0302</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gained more ground today, extending
the advance that carried the market to new post-crash highs on
Wednesday..
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 92.57 points over the
past seven sessions, rose another 12.70 to 2,545.33 by 3 p.m. on
Wall Street.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 733 up, 696 down and 519
unchanged.
   Analysts said some traders had grown leery of chasing after
stocks following the market's latest rally, which produced gains in
each of the first seven trading days in July.
   But Wall Streeters were looking ahead optimistically to several
economic reports due from the government on Friday, including
monthly statistics on industrial production and the producer price
index of finished goods.
   The figures are expected to provide further confirmation that
economic growth is slowing, fulfilling a primary goal of the Federal
Reserve's credit policy.
   Investors will give especially close scrutiny to the report on
producer prices which, if it lives up to its advance billing, will
show a slackening of inflationary pressures.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Eastman Kodak, up 1{ at
48~; International Business Machines, up ] at 115[; Union carbide,
up ~ at 28, and General Motors, up { at 42[.
   Sun Electric tumbled 6\ to 18]. The company, which had been
soliciting takeover bids, said it had attracted no suitable offers
and expects to remain independent.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.25 to 184.40. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .16 at 367.02.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 128.10 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
