<FIRST>r f AM-Mack-UAW     07-13 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mack-UAW,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mack Tells UAW It Will Not Appeal Union Vote Results</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mack Trucks Inc. has notified the United
Auto Workers that it will not appeal the results of a union election
held at its new plant in Winnsboro, S.C., the company said Thursday.
   By doing so, the company said it would recognize the UAW and
proceed to negotiations for a contract. Mack said the new policy was
in the best interest of the company and its customers.
   Mack is one of North America's largest producers of heavy-duty
deisel trucks. Mack vehicles are sold and serviced in more than 65
countries around the world.
   Shortly after the union election in April, Mack officials said
the Allentown-based company would block certification of the results
and refuse to recognize the UAW in South Carolina.
   Some workers in South Carolina said Mack reversed its policy
because of Ralph E. Reins, the company's new president.
   Reins, former president of ITT Automotive of Highland Park,
Mich., was named Mack's president on June 13. In a surprise visit to
the 23-month-old plant in Winnsboro last week, he spoke with many of
the 850 workers.
   ``I talked to him at the plant,'' said Rudy Feagin, a worker who
heads the plant's Unity Committee for South Carolinians backing the
UAW. ``He told me and many other people that he thought this
situation had to be resolved.
   ``He was determined to squash the appeals and give us a contract.
He said we deserved one.''
   Reins then urged Mack's board of directors to change tactics with
the UAW, the union said. The board, chaired by chief executive
officer John B. Curcio, agreed.
   Workers in Mack's plants in Maryland and Pennsylvania earn up to
$15 per hour. If Winnsboro workers are elevated to that level from
their current $10 per hour, Mack will be handed an annual wage
increase of more than $8 million.
</TEXT>
