<DOCNO> AP890713-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-China-Japan Bjt   07-13 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Japan, Bjt,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Pessimistic About Business in China, But Will Stay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-China-Japan Business on Business News Digest.
Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese businessmen and trade officials see
dismal prospects for investment in China in the coming year, and
dispute suggestions Japan may profit from China's current political
maladies.
   Fears that Japan will take advantage of the flight of other
foreign businesses to tighten its grip on the China market are
unfounded, said one Japanese trade office manager.
   ``It's a big misunderstanding'' said the official, who like other
Japanese interviewed spoke on condition he not be identified.
   He said that since the June 3-4 military assault on pro-democracy
protesters in Beijing, not one trade delegation from Japan has
passed through his office.
   After the attack, there was a mass exodus of foreigners,
including the Japanese. Japan warned its businessmen against a quick
return, saying it would give the impression of a ``thief at a fire''
_ someone profiting from another's misfortune.
   About half the 1,000 Japanese based in Beijing have returned and
more are expected back in the coming week. Most however, have come
mainly to settle accounts or fulfill existing contracts, one of them
said.
   A few companies may eventually reduce their staff here, he said.
``No one will increase'' their Japanese employees.
   Matsushita Electric spokesman Naomi Haga said in Tokyo that an
official opening planned for late July for a joint venture that has
begun producing color TV sets was now ``impossible.''
   ``Beijing is under martial law, and the Japanese government urged
Japanese to leave the country,'' he said. ``We can't give the
project up.... It would violate the contract. But it's dangerous to
be there now, and we don't have enough Japanese at the site to keep
it on schedule.''
   Japan's Prime Minister Sousuke Uno has said economic sanctions
won't be imposed on China, but Tokyo has stopped high-level contacts
and put off discussions on $5.8 billion in official development
loans Japan is to provide China for the 1990-95 period.
   More important, said an embassy official in Beijing, Japanese
companies won't be investing in China in the near future because of
an erosion of trust in the Beijing government.
   ``Even if martial law is lifted, the government has already lost
too much credibility,'' he said.
   He said Chinese companies will have increasing difficulties
borrowing money on the world market. One Japanese securities firm
has put off lending $100 million to southern China's Guangdong
International Trust and Investment Corp.
   The embassy official said Japanese companies, much criticized by
China for their reluctance to invest in projects, had finally
decided the time was right after former Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita signed an investment protection agreement in Beijing in
August. Since then, more than $100 million in investment had been
pledged.
   But China's recent crackdown on political dissent, and fears the
arbitrary use of force could some day be applied to the foreign
business community, ``have thrown cold water'' on future investment
plans, he said.
   So far, no one is talking about leaving. ``It's too early for
such a decision,'' said Kazuhiro Takeda of the Japan-China
Association of Economics and Trade in Tokyo. ``Most companies are
watching the conditions, seeing what direction the Chinese
government takes.''
   Those already in China won't give up, he said, but for at least a
year there will be few newcomers, he said.
   Short-term prospects also were poor for trade between China and
its biggest trading partner outside Hong Kong.
   Last year trade volume reached a nearly balanced $19.3 billion,
and expectations were it would top $20 billion this year. In the
first five months of 1989, trade was up 15 percent to $8.2 billion.
   But the political chaos, coming on top of a faltering economy,
has put many Chinese companies in a serious economic pinch. Japanese
steelmakers temporarily suspended shipments to China because they
couldn't get letters of credit from Chinese banks. Chinese companies
can't get funds for raw materials because of the government's tough
austerity policies that have dried up credit.
   The diplomat said China can finally produce the quality light
industrial goods and silk that Japan demands, but now can't deliver
the goods because of transportation, supply and energy problems.
   He said Japan's trade surplus is likely to grow again, although
China may move to cut back imports as its exports tail off.
   He said Japan has exhausted most of its investment possibilities
in Thailand and other Asian countries, and Japanese companies
looking for ways to spend their money still consider China the top
candidate in the long run.
   But every Japanese interviewed stressed that ``caution'' will be
the guiding principle. ``The Chinese say there will be no change in
their open-door policy but at the same time they are criticizing
capitalism,'' the trade official said. ``For the time being, we'll
have to wait and watch.''
</TEXT>
