<DOCNO> AP890713-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-HormelBooks Adv17 1stLd-Writethru 07-13 1016</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hormel Books, Adv 17, 1st Ld-Writethru,1043</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday July 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Books Recount Bitter Hormel Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS `this month' to June in 6th graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Geo. A. Hormel &amp; Co. meatpackers were
threatening to strike nearly four years ago, two reporters bet on
how long the strike would last.
   Paul Klauda said more than 10 days. Dave Hage said one day or
less, thinking the strike would never happen.
   ``I thought they would realize before they came to the brink that
the strike would be a failure and that they wouldn't strike,'' Hage
said.
   He was wrong.
   The bitter strike in Austin, Minn., lasted for months and
provided Hage and Klauda, both reporters for the Star Tribune in
Minneapolis, with enough drama to fill a nearly 400-page book.
   ``No Retreat, No Surrender: Labor's War at Hormel,'' published in
June by William Morrow &amp; Co. Inc., is one of several books about the
strike due on the market this year.
   ``There were so many strands that went beyond just a normal
labor-management fight. It wasn't just another strike,'' said
Klauda, who teamed with Hage to follow the battle for the Star
Tribune.
   The walkout's intriguing ingredients included the presence of a
Fortune 500 company in a small southern Minnesota town; the
half-century of labor peace Hormel had enjoyed; the benign history
of the Austin union, which struck for three days in 1933; and the
local's hiring of flamboyant union consultant Ray Rogers, known for
organizing J.P. Stevens textile mills in the South and, more
recently, helping Eastern Airlines strikers in their battle with
management.
   ``You just stumbled across one great story after another,'' said
Hage. ``And there just wasn't time to go back and revisit those
people to explore a certain accusation or to get to know a certain
person better, because tomorrow or Sunday there's always another
news story to write.''
   For a time, the strike was one of the nation's top labor stories.
While other plants in the Hormel chain agreed to wage concessions,
workers in Austin decided to fight a proposed wage cut. More than
1,400 union members walked off their jobs on Aug. 17, 1985.
   Local P-9 of the United Food and Commercial Workers objected to a
profitable company imposing a wage cut; Hormel said the cut was
needed for the company to stay competitive.
   Since the strike ended, the maker of Spam luncheon meat, Cure 81
ham and Black Label bacon has reported two consecutive years of
record earnings, continuing a five-year stretch of increasing
profits.
   Hage and Klauda said the strike symbolized worker anxiety about
concessions in the 1980s. But they concluded it failed to turn the
tide, partly because events in a town of 23,000 weren't going to
reverse nationwide economic forces.
   ``You're not going to overturn the high unemployment rate,'' Hage
said. ``You're not going to overturn all these trends in the
meatpacking industry that involve non-union competitors and falling
red-meat consumption.''
   In their book, Hage and Klauda trace the roots of the strike, the
first against Hormel since the Austin walkout 52 years before. The
reporters found it ironic that Hormel, with a history of good labor
relations and innovations such as profit-sharing dating to the
1930s, was the target of such bitterness.
   They also were fascinated by Jim Guyette, the young P-9 president
elected on a no-concessions platform. Guyette and other local
officers were suspended by the UFCW international union, which took
control of P-9 for refusing to end the strike and negotiated a
settlement ratified in September 1986. The trusteeship has since
been lifted and new local officers elected.
   In Klauda's view, the uncompromising Guyette was driven ``the
same way someone would be driven to go serve in a Third World
country, (in) some kind of humanitarian way.''
   Guyette now works for a hospital and health-care workers union in
Michigan. ``I was after a fair and decent contract that people could
work under,'' said in an interview. ``A safe place to work. A place
where you didn't have to raise your hand to go to the bathroom.
That's all I was after.''
   Five months after the strike began, Hormel reopened the plant and
began hiring replacement workers. The company was flooded by
applicants and former strikers who crossed the picket line. Gov.
Rudy Perpich called out the National Guard to maintain order at the
plant.
   One of those hired as a replacement worker was Michael T. Fahey,
whose book on the strike, ``Packing It In! The Hormel Strike
1985-86,'' was published in April by Kirwin &amp; Sons Publishing Inc.
of St. Paul.
   Fahey concludes Hormel was the wrong target for a meatpackers
strike and that Guyette was on an ``ego trip.''
   ``Jim Guyette had a very strong ego, and he ran into another ego
just as strong: Dick Knowlton (Hormel's president, board chairman
and chief executive officer),'' Fahey said. ``Thing was, Knowlton
had more horses.''
   Another book, ``On Strike at Hormel,'' takes a pro-strike side
and offers an insider's account, according to its author, Hardy
Green. The book will be published this fall by Temple University
Press of Philadelphia.
   Green worked for Rogers' New York-based Corporate Campaign and
was in Austin for much of the strike. He disputes claims that
Guyette was on a ``power trip.''
   ``Anyone who was in Austin could see this was not the strike of
one person,'' he said. ``It could never be the strike of one person
leading a bunch of zombies, because these people went all over the
country.''
   Three years since the strike ended, there are signs that wounds
are healing in Austin. Hormel has notified 35 of 442 former strikers
on a preferential hiring list that they will be called back to work
by July 24. The company also held an employee appreciation picnic in
Austin that attracted more than 5,000.
   But some scars remain. ``You almost wonder whether some day
grandkids are going to look back and say, `Which side were you
on?''' Hage said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday July 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
