<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Westinghouse     07-13 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Westinghouse,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Reports Higher Net, Revenue For Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. said Thursday that
net income for the second quarter rose 6 percent as nearly each of
its main business units posted gains in operating profits.
   For the quarter ended June 30, Westinghouse reported net income
of $228.3 million, or $1.56 per share, up from $215.3 million, or
$1.47 a share in the year-ago period.
   Net income for the 1988 period was restated to reflect a lower
tax provision. Compared to previously reported results,
second-quarter net income was up 13 percent.
   Revenue during the period rose 4.5 percent to $3.18 billion from
$3.04 billion a year ago.
   Westinghouse Chairman John C. Marous said in a statement,
``Orders entered for continuing businesses in the first half are up
almost 10 percent over last year, and our backlog of $11.5 billion
is a record for the decade.''
   He also noted that ``order rates for both electronic systems and
power generation were very strong. In fact, power generation is
having its best order year since the mid 1970s.''
   Operating profits from the energy and utility systems segment and
the industrial segment rose, while operating profits from the
broadcasting unit were even for the quarter but up for the year's
first half.
   Revenues from the financial services unit rose because of higher
levels of outstanding loans and marketable securities, but operating
profit for the quarter was static compared to the 1988 period.
   Operating profit from the electronic systems unit was up, while
operating profit from the commercial group was even despite a sharp
decline in the company's beverage business.
   For the year's first half, profits increased 5.4 percent to
$417.3 million, or $2.86 per share, from a restated $395.8 million,
or $2.72 per share. Revenue for the six-month period rose 4.7
percent to $6.06 billion from $5.79 billion.
</TEXT>
