<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-13 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher; Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved mostly higher against major
foreign currencies Thursday in choppy trading ahead of potentially
market-moving economic reports due Friday.
   Gold prices declined. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery fell $1.70 to $377.00 a troy ounce.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of $375.50 for an
ounce of gold bullion at 4 p.m. EDT, down from Wednesday's late bid
of $377.40.
   Activity in the foreign exchange markets featured dealers
adjusting their holdings in anticipation of government reports to be
released Friday on U.S. wholesale price inflation, retail sales and
industrial production.
   ``I think people feel the statistics will be pointing to a weaker
economy and hence a weaker dollar,'' said Bob Morrissey, a trader in
the Bank of Boston's New York office.
   Despite this perception, the dollar finished higher against most
currencies except the Japanese yen. The dollar's strength was a
byproduct of dealers' desires to lighten their holdings of West
German marks, mainly so they could buy more yen.
   Trading probably was slightly lighter than normal due to some
reluctance to establish significant new positions before the annual
economic summit of the Group of Seven major industrial countries,
which gets under way Friday in Paris.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed lower at 139.05 Japanese yen, down
from 140.50 late Wednesday. In London late Thursday, the dollar
traded higher at 139.20, and in New York, the dollar ended at 139.45
yen, down from 139.60 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound closed at $1.6240, cheaper for
buyers than Wednesday's late level of $1.6255. Sterling fetched
$1.6205 in New York, compared to $1.6300 on Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Wednesday, included: 1.8885 West German marks, up from 1.8745;
1.6240 Swiss francs, up from 1.6135; 1.19295 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.18955; 6.4085 French francs, up from 6.3575; and, 1,369.50
Italian lire, up from 1,359.00.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with levels late
Wednesday were: 1.8815 West German marks, up from 1.8755; 1.6190
Swiss francs, up from 1.6135; 6.3870 French francs, up from 6.3645;
2.1155 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1160; 1,362.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,361.50; and, 1.1922 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18965.
   Bullion dealers said there was little interest in gold ahead of
Friday's U.S. economic statistics. They said if the news indicated
slower economic growth, that could push the dollar lower and gold
could head upward.
   Gold closed in both London and Zurich at a bid of $375.75 a troy
ounce, down from Thursday's levels of $379.75 in London and $379.50
in Zurich.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $377.45 bid, down from
$380.05.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.20 bid a troy ounce,
down from $5.27. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery closed at $5.195 a troy ounce, up from Wednesday's
settlement of $5.188.
</TEXT>
