<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     07-13 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rose $4.39 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 468 money market mutual
funds increased by $4.39 billion in the latest week to a new record
of $328.15 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday broke the record
set the previous week, when the fund assets rose by a revised $2.96
billion to total $323.76 billion, the Washington-based mutual fund
trade group said. That weekly rise originally was reported as $2.83
billion.
   The institute said that in the latest week, assets of 231 general
purpose funds fell $196.4 million to $104.85 billion, assets of 95
broker-dealer funds increased $2.59 billion to $139.19 billion, and
assets of 142 institutional funds rose $1.99 billion to $84.11
billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.75 percent from 8.85 percent the
previous week, said Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade journal
based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.84 percent from 8.91 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 40
days, up from 38 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts fell to 6.54 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.55 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was 5.14 percent, unchanged from the previous week.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.62
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.79 the
previous week. Yields were 8.63 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
8.83 percent; 8.50 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.66 percent;
and 8.45 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.63 percent.
</TEXT>
