<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices posted their eight straight gain
Thursday as traders waited hopefully for new signs of a slowing
economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which closed Wednesday
at a new high since the 1987 crash, rose another 5.69 to 2,538.32.
   That extended the average's gain so far this month to 98.26
points, leaving it about 184 points shy of the record closing high
of 2,722.42 it reached on Aug. 25, 1987.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 6 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
798 up, 671 down and 526 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 153.80 million
shares, down from 160.55 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 183.97 million shares.
   Analysts said traders were looking ahead optimistically to
several economic reports due from the government on Friday,
including monthly statistics on industrial production and the
producer price index of finished goods.
   The figures are expected to provide further confirmation that
economic growth is slowing, fulfilling a primary goal of the Federal
Reserve's credit policy.
   Investors were likely to give especially close scrutiny to the
report on producer prices which, if it lives up to its advance
billing, will show a slackening of inflationary pressures.
   Estimates on Wall Street call for the index to be up about 0.3
percent for June, compared to a 0.9 percent jump the month before.
   As had happened on Wednesday, the market encountered some mild
selling in the first half of the session, but then resumed its
advance in afternoon trading.
   Honeywell, widely discussed of late as a possible takeover
candidate, jumped 6{ to 86.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included Eastman Kodak, up 1]
at 48}; Walt Disney, up ~ at 99}; Union Carbide, up } at 27~, and
General Motors, up ] at 42. GM shares got a boost from
