<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   07-13 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car and Truck Sales Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table,f0160</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early-July sales of North American-made cars and
light trucks jumped 8.9 percent over the same period last year, the
companies reported Thursday.
   The eight major U.S.-based automakers reported they sold vehicles
at an average rate of 35,614 a day during the July 1-10 period this
year compared with a rate of 32,696 during the same time last year.
   Car sales were up 9.3 percent and truck sales rose 8.3 percent.
   ``It's got to be surprising that they were up that much,'' said
analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
of New York.
   But David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. said he had
expected sales to be a bit stronger because General Motors had been
advertising in incentive programs to take delivery by July 10.
   ``Early-July sales were inflated by that artificial July 10
deadline,'' he said, adding he expected slower mid-July sales.
   General Motors Corp.'s early-July car sales were up 11.3 percent
and Ford Motor Co.'s car sales rose 16.9 percent. Car sales by
Chrysler Corp. fell 5.8 percent.
   Chrysler is plagued with product availability problems, Heaney
and Healy said. The company is getting production and marketing for
its Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim in line as it phases out its
K-cars, the Reliant and Aries.
   ``It's a phasing out and a phasing in and that's combined with an
overall weak market,'' Heaney said.
   The industry's early-July increases are compared with a period
last year that worked out to be just about on trend for the entire
year, the second-best in the industry's history.
   But for 1989 as a whole, sales this year are lagging behind last
year's pace.
   The eight companies reported their combined car and light truck
sales ran 4.4 percent behind last year's pace through July 10. So
far this yea, the automakers have sold vehicles at a daily rate of
38,100 compared with a rate of 39,835 a day last year.
   Car sales were down 5.6 percent and truck sales were off 2.1
percent.
   One of the surprises in the early-July sales figures was a 31.8
percent drop in sales of U.S.-made Hondas. Demand for the cars has
been tapering off and the company has offered its dealers incentives
to get customers in showrooms.
   Heaney said there may be another problem.
   ``There's going to be a new Accord launched in the fall and when
you know that, why do you want to buy last year's model?'' she said.
   Among the Big Three, Ford sold cars at a daily rate of 6,923
during early July this year, up from a 5,919 car-a-day rate during
the same time last year. Ford's car sales so far this year were
running 2.5 percent behind last year's pace.
   Ford truck dealers were selling 3.6 percent more vehicles in
early July this year than last year, but 3.8 percent fewer so far
this year.
   GM's car sales went at a daily rate of 10,615 during early July
this year compared with a rate of 9,534 during the same time last
year. GM's car sales for the year were down 9 percent from last year.
   The company's truck sales ran 13.2 percent ahead of last year's
pace in early July but were down 2.8 percent for the entire year.
   Chrysler's car sales fell to a daily rate of 2,921 this year from
the 3,100 daily rate of a year ago. For the calendar year,
Chrysler's car sales were down 14.6 percent.
   Chrysler's trucks sold at a rate 1.6 percent higher in early July
this year than they did a year ago. For the year, Chrysler's truck
sales were down 0.7 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
