<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Lockheed     07-13 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Lockheed,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockheed Posts 27 Percent Profit Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. reported a 27 percent
drop in its second-quarter earnings and blamed much of the fall on
the costs of three aircraft programs.
   The aerospace company said its after-tax earnings in the second
quarter fell to $77 million, or $1.20 a share, from $106 million, or
$1.77 a share, in 1988's second quarter.
   Revenue declined 3 percent to $2.45 billion from $2.53 billion a
year earlier.
   Dan Tellep, Lockheed's chairman and chief executive, said the
deterioration in profit reflected $27 million in costs involving
three aircraft programs.
   One of the programs included a phase-out of Lockheed's P-3
aircraft production. The plane designed for hunting submarines had
no customer prospects.
   The U.S. Navy last year selected Lockheed for development of the
P-7A, a new generation anti-sub plane.
   The other two programs on which cost adjustments were made
involve fixed-price development contracts for modifications to two
Air Force C-5As to transport space cargo and modification of a C-141
for an advance radar test bed.
   The overall decline in 1989 revenue and earnings was largely due
to the cost of completing the new generation C-5B, Tellep said in a
news release, which called the outlook for new defense contracts
``flat to declining.''
   ``We remain confident that Lockheed's strong core business
programs will provide the basis for resumed earnings growth in
1990,'' Tellep said, pointing to continuing projects such as the
stealth fighter plane and the P-7A.
   Lockheed in April issued 10.7 million shares for the ESOP plan
and successfully thwarted Dallas investor Harold Simmons' effort to
take over the aerospace company.
   Lockheed's move put 17 percent of the company's stock in employee
hands, making it impossible for Simmons to acquire the 85 percent
needed for buyout approval. Lockheed acted before Simmons made a
tender offer.
   For the first half of the year, Lockheed earned $139 million, or
$2.25 a share, down 37 percent from earnings of $220 million, or
$3.61 a share, in 1988's first six months.
   Revenue amounted to $4.45 billion, down from $4.92 billion.
</TEXT>
