<FIRST>r f AM-NorthwestPilots     07-13 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest Pilots,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Continues Talks With Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilots at Northwest Airlines continued
mediated contract talks Thursday but a union spokesman said the
group is growing weary of the negotiations.
   ``We have made progress in the past few months but not enough
progress,'' said Andy Murphy, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots
Association. ``This thing has been going on for 2{ years and our
pilots are running out of patience.''
   Curt Kruse, another spokesman for the pilots, told the St. Paul
Pioneer Press Dispatch Wednesday that the union would consider
asking for an impasse, which would free the pilots to strike after a
30-day cooling off period. Such a request would be decided by the
National Mediation Board.
   Kruse told the newspaper the union would back away from
considering such a request only if the two sides reach a tentative
settlement or make substantial progress in their bargaining by
Friday.
   But Murphy backed away from the remark Thursday, saying a request
for an impasse is only one of several options being considered by
the pilots.
   He said the group is likely to make a statement next week about
the status of negotiations, which resumed this week for the first
time since mid-June, when Northwest accepted a $4 billion buyout
proposal from Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi.
   Former Republic Airlines pilots who joined Northwest in the
acquisition of Republic in late 1986 have been without a contract
for the past 2{ years while the contract covering Northwest pilots
expired three years ago.
   Talks to bring the pilots under one pact began in April 1987 and
broke off last November, when 96 percent voted to authorize a
strike. Northwest then requested federal mediation and talks resumed
in December.
   Murphy said more progress has been made in the past two months
than in the previous two years, but he said serious disagreements
remain over wages, work rules and benefits.
   Northwest spokesman Bob Gibbons said it's a positive sign that
the two sides are still at the bargaining table.
   ``As long as we are meeting we can move toward an agreement,''
said Northwest spokesman Bob Gibbons. ``There is momentum there and
hopefully we can keep that going.''
</TEXT>
