<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AsbestosSuit     07-13 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asbestos Suit,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Says Buyout was Attempt to Shirk Asbestos Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers seeking to represent more than 80,000
people filed suit Thursday against the investment firm Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. and leveraged buyout specialist Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co. seeking to reverse the $2.4 billion takeover of Jim
Walter Corp. two years ago.
   The lawsuit, filed in state court in Beaumont, claims the buyout
was a fraudulent attempt to escape more than $3 billion in
liabilities stemming from asbestos claims against Celotex Corp., a
subsidiary of Tampa, Fla.-based home-builder Jim Walter, also named
as a defendant.
   Jim Walter last year sold Celotex, a long-time producer of
asbestos, which has been proven to cause cancer and other health
problems.
   ``I think this will prove to be a landmark case in this
country,'' Houston attorney Stephen Susman said after the lawsuit
was filed.
   However, spokesman for Kohlberg Kravis and Jim Walter said the
claims were similar to those in a suit already in federal court and
were without merit.
   The suit, which asks for class action status, seeks no monetary
damages for three named plaintiffs or for the thousands of others it
says have similar, separate lawsuits pending in courts around the
country.
   Instead, it attempts to prevent the further sale of any Jim
Walter assets and to hold Kohlberg Kravis and the remaining
corporate structure responsible for any judgments related to
asbestos-related lawsuits.
   ``We want to undo this transaction,'' Susman said. ``We want the
people responsible for this transaction to be liable for any
judgments in favor of more than 80,000 people who are seeking
justice.''
   The suit alleges Kohlberg Kravis' 1987 buyout of Jim Walter was
part of a scheme by Jim Walter to evade its liability in the growing
number of lawsuits being filed against Celotex.
   ``The intended effect of these transactions was to strip Jim
Walter of virtually all of its valuable assets and, as a necessary
consequence, to limit the resources available to satisfy asbestos
judgments against Celotex and Jim Walter,'' the lawsuit states.
   About $2 billion of the buyout was financed by bank loans, and
the investment group led by Kohlberg Kravis later sold bonds through
Drexel to replace the bank debt. Selected Jim Walter assets have
since been sold to help pay for the deal.
   ``This was a standard, garden-variety leveraged buyout,'' Jim
Walter spokesman David Townsend said Thursday. ``Consequently, our
position has been and continues to be that the allegations set forth
in the previous (federal) complaint and in this complaint are
totally without merit and we intend to defend ourselves vigorously.''
   The federal suit is similar, but names neither Drexel or Kohlberg
Kravis as defendants and is limited to those plaintiffs who filed
their asbestos lawsuits within the Eastern District of Texas, Susman
said.
   Kohlberg Kravis spokesman Tom Daly said the lawsuit addressed
``the same substantive issues that are already in federal court.
That suit is without merit, and we think we'll win it.''
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said the firm declined comment on
the suit since it had not seen it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 1805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     07-13 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply rose in the week ended July 3, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose to a seasonally
adjusted $3,101.1 billion from $3.093.9 billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, rose to a seasonally adjusted
$3,992.0 billion from $3,977.4 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose to a
seasonally adjusted $777.4 billion from $769.5 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The Fed in February reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of 3
percent to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent
growth in M3. The Fed has not set a target for M1 growth since early
1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,081.9 billion, a 1.3
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13
weeks. M3 averaged $3,963.7 billion, up 3.1 percent, while M1 fell
5.5 percent to an average of $775.7 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose $714 million.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window, excluding extended credit,
averaged $530 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, down from
$612 million the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve said net free reserves averaged $382 million
in the two weeks ended July 12, up from $221 million in the previous
two-week period.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $289.5 billion in the two-week period ended June 28, down from
$290.0 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
