<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-13 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Rally on Ferruzzi Lawsuit News; Sugar Soars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rebounded Thursday on the Chicago Board of
Trade following news of a legal challenge to the exchange's order
that traders liquidate their holdings in the July soybean contract.
   Wheat and oat futures also advanced while corn futures finished
mixed.
   On other markets, sugar futures soared amid rumors of Soviet
buying; cattle futures were up sharply; pork futures were mixed;
energy futures advanced; and precious metals were mixed.
   Soybeans settled 10 cents to 17{ cents higher with the contract
for delivery in July up 11 cents at $6.97{ a bushel.
   Two subsidiaries of Italian agribusiness giant Ferruzzi
Finanziara SpA filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Chicago
seeking an injunction against the Board of Trade's emergency
directive.
   The exchange's order, issued Tuesday, was widely seen as an
attempt to block an attempt by Ferruzzi to control the soybean
market.
   Soybeans had opened strongly higher on Wednesday's government
report of smaller-than-expected soybean plantings but the market had
eased by midday on profit-taking. Wire service reports of Ferruzzi's
lawsuit appeared at about 1 p.m. CDT.
   ``From the time it showed on the wire, we had a pretty decent
recovery in here,'' said Dale Gustafson, grain market analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Analysts said the soybean market would likely take its cues
Friday from the outcome of the soybean ruling.
   Corn futures finished narrowly mixed with most of the pressure
stemming from Wednesday's Agriculture Department crop report, which
showed larger-than-expected corn plantings.
   The wheat market got a late boost from rumors that China had
purchased a large quantity of U.S. wheat.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 2} cents higher with July at $3.90} a
bushel; corn was 5} cents lower to { cent higher with July at $2.56\
a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 4{ cents higher with July at $1.48\ a
bushel.
   Sugar futures prices soared on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange on market talk that the Soviet Union was interested in
buying up to 100,000 metric tons of white sugar for August shipment.
   Sugar settled .50 cent to 1.11 cents higher with October at 13.67
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures posted near-limit gains as stronger cash markets
added to the bullish enthusisam generated by expecatations for a
steep decline in supplies by mid-August.
   Market analysts are predicting that next Friday's quarterly USDA
cattle-on-feed report will show a sharp reduction in placements of
cattle on feedlots during the second quarter.
   Live cattle were .62 cent to 1.35 cents higher with August at
71.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .55 cent to 1.35 cents
higher with August at 82.95 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent lower
to .45 cent higher with July at 47.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle
were 1.2 cents lower to .08 cent higher with July at 28.95 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures are limited to movements of 1.5 cents a pound.
   Energy futures advanced slightly on the New York Mercantile
Exchange on fears that maintenance and platform workers on North Sea
oil rigs might go on strike.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 20 cents to 44 cents
higher with August at $20.35 a barrel; heating oil was .50 cent to
.72 cent higher with August at 49.44 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .05 cent to .28 cent higher with August at 57.46 cents
a gallon.
   Gold futures slipped a bit and silver inched higher in subdued
trading ahead of Friday's bevy of economic reports.
   Gold settled $1.70 to $1.90 lower with August at $378.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.3 cent to 0.7 cent higher with July at $5.195 a
troy ounce.
</TEXT>
