<FIRST>u f AM-LIN-McCaw     07-13 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LIN-McCaw,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw, Lin Discuss $127.50 a Share Buy-Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. is
discussing a $127.50 per share buyout offer for LIN Broadcasting
Corp. that would give LIN shareholders stock in McCaw, the companies
said Thursday.
   A McCaw spokesman said the new cash and common stock offer
replaces the $110 per share cash offer McCaw made for LIN on Monday
following a New York court settlement unfavorable to LIN. That offer
was to expire July 21.
   The new offer raises to $6.2 billion the total amount McCaw would
have to spend to acquire the 90.2 percent of LIN's 53.9 million
shares that it does not already own. The $110 a share offer was
worth $5.36 billion.
   If the Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw's takeover attempt is
successful, it would solidify McCaw's position as the nation's
largest cellular telephone company.
   The new offer came after LIN complained that the $110 per share
offer was less than what McCaw believes LIN is worth.
   The offer of ``$110 (per share) is gone. Negotiations led to a
higher price potential,'' said Steven Bruce of Abernathy MacGregor,
McCaw's outside public investor relations counsel in New York.
   He said the price was upped in ``an attempt to reach a friendly
transaction.''
   Negotiations resumed between the two companies' advisers on
Tuesday.
   Bruce said the cash portion of the new offer could be higher than
$110 per share. McCaw had originally bid $120 per share for McCaw.
   The amount of McCaw that would be held by LIN will be determined
by the final cash offer and the price of McCaw stock on the day a
deal is closed, Bruce said. It is not clear if the Class A common
stock would be new stock or existing shares, he said. The shares
will have voting rights, he said.
   The offer ``means participation by LIN in McCaw,'' he said. When
asked if LIN wants participation on McCaw's board, he said,
``Everything is under discussion.''
   Trading in both companies' stocks was heavy on Thursday. They are
each traded in the over-the-counter market.
   McCaw closed at $40 per share, down 12{ cents, on a trading
volume of 1.1 million shares. LIN rose $2.50 a share to $116.75 on
volume of nearly 1.8 million shares.
   In a joint statement, the companies said the proposal provides
for each share of LIN stock to be exchanged for cash and stock
having an aggregate value of $127.50 a share.
   The companies cautioned that ``there can be no assurances'' the
new offer will result in an agreement.
   The announcement came a day after McCaw disclosed in a filing
with the Securities and Exchange Commission that McCaw and LIN had
``recommenced negotiations through their advisers.''
   The New York Court of Appeals recently denied LIN's claims to
certain cellular interests of Metromedia Co. in the New York City
and Philadelphia markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890713-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-89 2121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GE-Boycott     07-13 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-GE-Boycott,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Leading 3-Year-Old GE Boycott Claims It's Bruised Company's
Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An antinuclear group that has led a General
Electric Co. boycott for three years released figures Thursday aimed
at showing the campaign has cost the corporate giant $50.6 million
in lost business. GE rejected the claims.
   The group INFACT based the calculation on the number of people
whom it said have joined the boycott in an attempt to drive GE and
other defense contractors out of the nuclear weapons industry.
   ``GE wants you to think it brings good things to life,'' said
Nancy Cole, executive director of the group. ``It also brings death
and destruction. We think that's got to be stopped.''
   INFACT stands for Infant Formula Action Coalition. The
Boston-based group organized a boycott of the Nestle Co. a decade
ago to stop that company from selling what INFACT said was unsafe
powdered baby's milk. The group switched to the GE boycott in July
1986 and has claimed widespread success.
   By INFACT's calculations, at least 2.53 million people worldwide
have stopped buying GE products because of the boycott, resulting in
lost revenue to the company of $25.32 million in heavily populated
areas of the United States and an equal amount elsewhere.
   GE spokesman George Jamison rejected INFACT's assertions.
   ``Anybody can claim anything,'' Jamison said. ``The facts of the
matter are, since 1985 GE revenues are up 56 percent from $32
billion to $50 billion. Earnings are up 49 percent. Also during that
time, market share has increased in all GE consumer businesses.
These are facts which are reported in our annual report. They speak
for themselves.''
   GE, based in Fairfield, Conn., makes products ranging from
dishwashers to jet engines to high-tech medical equipment. It is one
of the nation's leading defense contractors and the fifth-largest
U.S. industrial concern.
   The company also owns the NBC television network and a
controlling interest in Kidder Peabody Group Inc., a large Wall
Street investment firm.
   INFACT has targeted GE because of what it calls ``the company's
extensive involvement in the production and promotion of nuclear
weaons and the trail of radioactive and toxic waste the company's
nuclear weapons work leaves behind.''
   Jamison said ``INFACT's goal is unilateral disarmament. We want
peace every bit as much as INFACT does. But along with a majority of
the American people, GE believes it can be assured only by a strong
national defense.''
</TEXT>
