<FIRST>r f BC-Honeywell-GE     07-13 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Honeywell-GE,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Electric Says It Has No Interest in Honeywell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co., in response to an
inquiry from the New York Stock Exchange, said Thursday that it had
no discussions about nor interest in acquiring Honeywell Inc.
   The Fairfield, Conn., company issued its brief statement after
Honeywell stock jumped $6 a share to close at $85.50 on the
exchange. GE stock was unchanged at $54.38{.
   GE did not comment beyond its statement and stock exchange
officials left work before they could be contacted about it.
   Late last week, analysts attributed a similar increase in
Honeywell's stock price to a rumor published in Business Week that
GE was considering acquiring the automated controls makers. General
Electric previously declined to comment on the rumor, and Honeywell
has refused to comment on all takeover speculation.
   Before Honeywell stock declined $1.75 Tuesday, it had been pushed
up more than $9 in the two previous days of trading. It was down
slightly Wednesday before surging again Thursday, when more than 2.1
million shares traded hands.
   ``The stock is trading very heavily,'' said Kurt Rivard of
Minneapolis-based Dain Bosworth Inc. ``The action you're seeing in
Honeywell can be attributed to more than the General Electric
rumor.''
   Rivard said Honeywell's value to an acquirer could range from
$110 a share to $140 a share.
   Thursday's trading included the sale of a 500,000-share block of
Honeywell stock at the market price, Rivard said. It was unclear who
moved the block, he said.
   Takeover rumors concerning Honeywell intensified after the
company lost $435 million in its fiscal 1988.
   Chairman James Renier said at the company's annual meeting May 5
that the speculation was inevitable given the ``discrepancy between
stock market values and perceived true-asset values.''
   With the exception of fiscal 1987, Honeywell's financial
performance has lagged for the past seven years.
   The company sought approval at the annual meeting of two
anti-takeover measures. But an opposition group led by North
American Partners of Fort Worth, Texas, lobbied to defeat the
proposals in a proxy fight.
   North American has said it is not interested in acquiring
Honeywell.
</TEXT>
