<FIRST>r f BC-Casino-Bass     07-13 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Casino-Bass,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Company Gets Casino License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British company that owns about
10 percent of a casino's parent company received casino licensing
Thursday from the state Casino Control Commission.
   Bass PLC of London owns more than 200 Holiday Inns around the
world, including 13 in the United States. Bass also owns and
operates 13 breweries in the United Kingdom, thousands of pubs and
more than 90 hotels in Europe.
   As part of the transaction to purchase the Holiday Inns, Holiday
Corp., which owns the hotel chain, issued Bass a $100 million
subordinated debenture that can be converted into 9.99 percent of
Holiday's stock.
   Because of the possible stock conversion and because Holiday
Corp. owns Harrah's Marina Hotel and Casino in Atlantic City, Bass
had to meet certain New Jersey's casino licensing requirements.
   At a hearing Thursday, without opposition from the state Division
of Gaming Enforcement, Bass received its license. All Bass profits
that had been placed in trust during the licensing investigation may
now be released.
</TEXT>
