<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Starts Higher, Share Prices Inch Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar started higher at the start of
Friday's trading, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
rebounded slightly from Thursday's close.
   The dollar opened at 139.60 yen, up 0.55 yen from Thursday's
close of 139.05 yen. In New York, it ended at 139.50 yen overnight.
   Trading was quiet as dealers waited for the release of major U.S
economic indicators later Friday, including the nation's wholesale
price index for June, traders said.
   The market expects the index to be only slighty lower than the
previous month, said a Bank of Tokyo trader, speaking on condition
of anonymity. A lower figure would mean inflation is slowing.
   ``If the figure is larger than our expectation, it could be a
major dollar-buying incentive,'' he said.
   ``Considering the dollar is not declining now despite our
expectation for quite some time over the possible relaxation of
monetary policy, I see little incentive for further
dollar-selling,'' the trader added.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which shed 70.36 points Thuarsday, inched up within the
first 15 minutes of morning trading to 33,660.00, up 24.84 points,
or 0.07 percent.
   The index's rise in Tokyo followed a rise in the Dow Jones
industrial average of 30 major issues in New York overnight, dealers
said.
