<FIRST>u f AM-OryxTower     07-13 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oryx Tower,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Skyscraper in Years Planned For Dallas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The developer of Dallas' upscale Galleria shopping
and office complex announced plans Thursday to build a signature
office tower for Oryx Energy Co., the city's first major skyscraper
construction in several years.
   The announcement of the 26- to 28-story building does not
necessarily mean the city's lagging real estate market has
recovered, analysts said, but nevertheless is welcome.
   ``I don't think it signals a turnaround; it signals a situation
where you had a large user with a specific need,'' said Thomas
Katopody, a partner in the Dallas office of Kenneth Leventhal &amp; Co.
accountants. He said there is a two-year supply of office space
already built, with about a one-year inventory of Class A space.
   Neither will the tower add to downtown's distinctive skyline, as
it will be built about seven miles north of the central business
district near the intersection of two major highways.
   The building will be part of the Galleria complex, which includes
two office towers _ one of 24 stories and one of 25 _ a Westin hotel
and a four-story shopping mall. The complex was built by Houston
developer Gerald D. Hines Interests.
   Nearby is the 24-story Occidental Tower, headquarters of
Occidental Chemical Corp., a subsidiary of Occidental Petroleum Corp.
   Staman Ogilvie, executive vice president of Hines, refused to
discuss the building's cost, but analysts said it could run as high
as $200 a square foot, or about $118 million for the 590,000 square
feet.
   Construction will begin after the first of the year, with Oryx,
North America's largest independent oil company, moving in by the
end of 1991, Ogilvie said.
   Neither he nor the company would disclose leasing or equity
arrangements, and Ogilvie said the company still is pursuing
financing.
   He said many financiers were surprised when contacted about new
construction in Dallas, but Oryx' long-term lease commitment makes
the project ``a very `financiable' undertaking.''
   The Oryx headquarters had been a hotly contested prize in Dallas'
hungry real estate community. But company officials said there just
wasn't enough quality space in one place, despite millions of empty
square feet available.
   ``We wanted a building where we would be the only tenant, or at
least the major tenant,'' Oryx Chairman Robert P. Hauptfuhrer said.
``We want to establish a definite identity and presence in the
business community, so a Dallas location that will be recognized by
all as the Oryx Energy Building was a major consideration.''
   Oryx will move about 1,000 of its employees into the new building
from two locations elsewhere in Dallas.
   Oryx formerly was known as Sun Exploration &amp; Production Co.
before it was spun off last year by parent Sun Co., which kept the
retailing and refining end of the business.
   The last major skyscraper built in Dallas was Cityplace Center, a
42-story building announced in 1984 and completed last year. It
remains about half empty, occupied mainly by builder Southland
Corp., owner of the 7-Eleven convenience store chain.
   Most of the city's other towers were finished by 1987 and none
are currently under construction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
